“The Acraman impact structure (Williams and Gostin, 2005) is expressed topographically by a ~30 km diameter depression in the Gawler Ranges of northern Eyre Peninsula, South Australia. A ~20 km diameter subcircular playa lake with islands (Lake Acraman) is situated within the depression. The geomorphic expression of Acraman makes it clearly visible on maps and satellite images, but outcrop of bedrock in the central depression is strictly localised. The Gawler Ranges are comprised of flat-lying Early Mesoproterozoic (ca 1590 Ma) dacitic lavas of the Gawler Range Volcanics. An impact origin was first demonstrated by Williams (1986) based on the discovery of shatter cones, PDFs in quartz, and devitrified melt rock veins in isolated shattered dacite outcrops on islands near the centre of the lake. Acraman is one of few Australian impact structures involving a wholly crystalline target, and is also the only Australian impact structure to be confidently linked with distal ejecta deposits located in contemporaneous sedimentary basins (Gostin et al., 1986; Wallace et al., 1990; Hill et al., 2004).” - (Haines, 2005)
“Acraman has a distinctive aeromagnetic signature comprising a circular magnetic low with subdued magnetic relief 20 km in diameter, with a central high-amplitude dipole anomaly (Williams et al., 1996; Hawke, 2003). The structure is deeply eroded; Williams and Wallace (2003) estimated ³2.5 km of denudation since the impact event based on apatite fission track and geomorphic evidence. The original crater floor and rim are not preserved and therefore the original rim diameter must be inferred from indirect evidence, with opinions varying widely between different authors. Williams and Wallace (2003 pp. 552, 553) stated: ‘The original crater probably comprised highly disturbed rocks of a central uplift, a transient cavity or excavated area up to c. 40 km in diameter, and a possible final structural rim at 85 – 90 km diameter’. Williams et al. (1996) considered that the outer limit of structural disturbance beyond the crater rim may have been as much as ~150 km based on geomorphic evidence. In contrast, Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1996) suggested that the final crater might have been no more than 35 – 40 km in size, essentially coincident with the modern Lake Acraman depression, while Hawke (2003) inferred a slightly greater figure of 55 km based largely on aeromagnetic interpretation. Gurov (1993) and Gostin and Zbik (1999) have calculated the transient crater diameter as 30 – 40 km and at least 34 km, respectively, based on the average thickness of ejecta (Gurov 1993 actually stated ‘radius of the crater as about 15 – 20 km’ i.e. diameter of 30 – 40 km, but in fact the formula used determines transient crater radius: see Williams & Gostin 2005). This method assumes that the average ejecta thickness observed in the Flinders Ranges and Officer Basin are representative of the average thicknesses of the entire ejecta blanket at these respective distances from the crater.” - (Haines, 2005)
“K– Ar and Ar –Ar dating of an altered melt-rock vein in the central uplift provides a minimum age constraint of ca 450 Ma (Baldwin et al., 1991). This is significantly younger than what is considered a more reliable age estimates of ca 580 Ma (Grey et al., 2003; Williams and Wallace, 2003; Hill et al., 2004) determined from the stratigraphic position of the distal eject layer.” - (Haines, 2005). The uncertainty in the age adopted in the database is estimated from the stratigraphic  considerations discussed in the above papers and should represent ~95 % confidence interval. The projectile is thought to be chondrite (Williams et al., 1996 in Grey et al., 2003), chondritic PGE abundances found in ejecta (Wallace et al., 1990). More magnetics in Cowan and Cooper (2005).

Late Devonian Alamo breccia 1-135 m thick over 16000 km2. Probably generated by collapse of carbonate platform and tsunamis triggered by impact. Evidence for impact origin of the Alamo megabreccia and related features:     (1) Abundant shocked quartz, documented by petrography (e.g., Warme and Sandberg, 1995; Warme and Kuehner, 1998; Morrow and Sandberg, 2001; Morrow et al., 2005), TEM  analysis (Leroux et al., 1995), U-stage microscopy (Morrow et al., 2001), and SEM imaging (Morrow et al., 2005).     (2) Carbonate accretionary ejecta lapilli, containing shocked-quartz  silt within their nuclei (Warme et al., 2002).     (3) Larger accretionary ejecta bombs (e.g., Morrow et al., 2005).     (4) Target rock-derived, ejected lithic clasts occurring with lapilli  (Warme et al., 2002) that contain a suite of anomalous, pre-impact,  Lower Ordovician to lower Upper Devonian conodont microfossils (Morrow et al., 2005).     (5) The highly anomalous Alamo Breccia, which is well documented by  Warme and Sandberg, 1995, 1996; Sandberg et al., 1997; Warme and  Kuehner, 1998; Warme, 2004  , and other  correlative, event-related Alamo deposits such as deep-water Breccia channels  and onshore, inner-platform channels probably emplaced by the Alamo  tsunami (Morrow et al., 2005).  Both the deep-water and inner-platform  Alamo deposits contain shocked quartz and other ejecta material, as well.     The breccia shows minor enrichment in Ir (Koeberl et al., 2003).            Earlier 20-150 km diameter range of the Alamo crater (Warme and Kuehner, 1998) has been recently refined to 44-65 km (Morrow et al., 2005). Ongoing work by John Warme and colleagues (e.g., Pinto and Warme, 2004; Pinto and Warme, 2006) has  recognized a probable preserved tectonic slice of the Alamo crater.  The crater has been dismembered by periods of regional thrusting and extension and its segments are now partly hidden under younger sediments. The present crater location is at ~ lat/lon 38.0/-116.0 (Morrow et al., 2005); documented exposures of intra crater sections on Tempiute Mt. are at lat37.60/lon-115.34 (Pinto and Warme, 2006). Whole breccia interval lies in the middle of punctata conodont zone (the third one from bottom out of 10) (Warme and Kuehner, 1998). Calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004) the age would be ~382.6 Ma, 3 Ma uncertainty (95%) guessed from average length of conodont zones and uncertainty of the Frasnian boundary. Utilizing a recently refined Devonian numerical timescale developed by B. Kaufmann and colleagues (Kaufmann, 2005),  we (Morrow and coll.) currently favor a best age estimate for the Alamo of ~382.1 Ma. Chamberlain (2000) used the name Tempiute crater.

Amelia Creek structure is an elliptic zone of deformation 12 x 20 km overprinting older multiple folds and faults in metamorphosed Paleoproterozoic sandstones, siltstones, volcanics and volcaniclastics. There is no developed central uplift and it is unclear whether the arcuate features visible in aeromagnetic, ASTER and XSAR images represent original diameter of the structure (Macdonald et al., 2005). Unimbra sandstone on the southern toe of the central syncline hosts abundant conically jointed structures that Macdonald and Mitchell (2003) and Macdonald et al. (2005) interpreted as “unequivocal” shatter cones. Shatter cones nearly 1 m long also occur in felsic volcanics. Shatter cones occur within area of ~6 km2. After restoring beds in horizontal position, the shatter cones point toward south at ~5-10 º inclination. Macdonald et al. (2005) reported autochtonous breccias in fault zones but did not find any melt or allochtonous breccias despite extensive search. Thin sections from shatter cones display planar microstructures, which appear to be cleavage and not true PDFs. Common are “feather features” stemming from the fractures at an angle and could represent incipient PDFs (Macdonald et al., 2005). The age of the impact is Proterozoic, constrained by the oldest target rocks ~1815-1660 Ma and by the preserved relatively undeformed Neoproterozoic (~600 Ma) and Cambrian siliciclastics filling the Proterozoic paleovaleys (Macdonald et al., 2005). Coordinates from Google Earth based on Macdonald et al. (2005).

Ames is a buried structure on the shelf of the Anadarko Basin. The target rocks are Precambrian-Cambrian granites and Cambrian-lower Ordovician sandstones and carbonates (Arbuckle Group). The structure is overlain by ~2750 m of various sedimentary formations of middle Ordovician to lower Guadalupian (Permian) age. The anomalous character of the area was first recognized by drilling through abnormally thick and deep overlying Hunton carbonates (Silurian-Devonian). Subsequent drilling and seismic data delineated what became known as the Ames Hole (Carpenter and Carlson, 1997; Fischer, 1997). The floor of the structure is covered with abundant breccia and a few meters of melt breccia. Up to 27 m of the ejecta blanket consisting of mixed dolomite (~80%) and granite (~20%) are locally preserved within several kilometers outside the structure rim. Uplifted fractured granite in the center forms a ring of ridges, some of which are as much as 1.5 km wide, 3 km long and 500 m thick (Carpenter and Carlson, 1997). The core of the central uplift either collapsed or it was eroded away (Koeberl et al., 1997). The rim and breccia highs were subaerially exposed, karstified and eroded. Much of this material was deposited inside the structure. A stratified cap of tight dolomite was subsequently deposited over the breccias. The impact related rocks grade upward into an organic rich shale. The overlying strata represent regional deposition but they are thicker than outside the structure due to the preexisting morphological depression and due to differential compaction of impact generated rock facies (Carpenter and Carlson, 1997). Fischer (1997) interpreted the breccia below the dolomite caprock as a possible backwash and the graded dolomite caprock as redeposited mud disturbed by the impact. This led him to suggest (as other authors in Johnson and Campbell, 1997) that the impact occurred in a shallow sea. 

Multiple authors documented whole rock and selective mineral melts, enrichment in Ir, PDFs in quartz and feldspar, mosaicism and reduced birefringence in quartz and ballen quartz in samples from boreholes (e.g., Koeberl et al., 1994; Attrep et al., 1997; Fischer, 1997; Huffman, 1997; Koeberl et al., 1997).

Age:
The lithostratigraphic and biostratigraphic constraints place the impact event in the median Middle Ordovician (Carpenter and Carlson, 1997; Hannibal and Feldmann, 1997; Repetski, 1997), i.e. 445-456 Ma (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2004). Earlier commonly quoted ~470 Ma apparently reflects developments in chronostratigraphic calibrations. Three unaltered samples of fine grained impact melt rock dated with step-heating Ar/Ar method yielded plateau ages ranging from 282.7 to 312.0 Ma (Koeberl, 1997). Two freshest available melt rock samples where analyzed with spot laser heating Ar/Ar technique to avoid unmelted clasts (Koeberl et al., 2001). The samples yielded unweighted ages 298 ± 99 Ma and 255 ± 97 Ma (2σ). Koeberl et al. (2001) interpreted these ages as reflecting processes related either the regional Nemaha Uplift or resetting due to hot brines active on a midcontinent-wide scale, perhaps related to the Alleghenian and Ouachita orogenies. The age data indicate an extended burial phase associated with thermal overprint during Late Pennsylvanian-Permian (Koeberl et al., 2001). 

Coordinates determined from the position of wells, shallow sea here interpreted as <500 m water depth

Amguid crater was first reported by Karpoff (1954) and briefly described by Lefranc (1969). Lambert et al. (1980) described it as a fresh circular cavity with a raised rim and a steep wall, ~450 m in diameter and 30 m deep. Measurements on data on Google Earth reveal slightly rectangular perimeter 490x540 m in diameter and ~20 m depth. 

The target rocks are subhorizontal Lower Devonian sandstones. They dip outward within the wall progressively steepening upward and the topmost layers are overturned on the NNW and SSE part of the rim. The crater is surrounded by scattered blocks of sandstones up to several meters in size forming nearly continuous blanket of debris 100m from the rim. The center of the crater is filled by silt and a ring of gravel washed of the walls. The in situ sandstones in the wall do not show intense fracturing, shatter cones or breccia veins. Petrographic analysis discovered very limited deformation of mineral grains. All grains display undulatory extinction. One percent or less of the studied quartz grains displayed planar elements, mostly non-decorated. Measured crystallographic orientations include those characteristic for PDFs {1013}, {1012} and other orientations commonly observed in shocked samples {0001}, {1122}, {5161} and {1010}. The authors presented orientation statistics and photographs (Lambert et al., 1980). Lambert et al. (1980) argued that the field observations required excavation formation ruling out diapirism, solution and collapse, glacial activity etc. They noted there was no evidence for volcanic activity in the area. The freshness of the crater and a comparison to other young craters led Lambert et al. (1980) to estimate the age of the crater within about 0.01-0.1 Ma. Coordinates from Google Earth based on information in Lambert et al. (1980).

McHone et al. (2002) presented radar observation of the crater.

Aorounga structure is located in a desert of the Tibesti Massif, ~110 km southeast of the Emi Koussi volcano. Its preserved morphology defines ~13 km diameter. Early photogeological investigation of this structure suggested it was a granite diapir or an impact crater (Roland, 1976 in Koeberl et al., 2005). Grieve et al. (1988) listed the structure as a possible impact crater. Becq-Giraudon et al.(1992) visited the structure and reported possible shater cones and breccias with quartz showing multiple sets of planar structures. Koeberl et al. (2005) reviewed the samples of monomict quartzite and quarzitic sandstone breccias and confirmed presence of multiple PDFs in quartz. 

The crater formed in a fine-grained, well sorted, slightly carbonate-bearing sandstone possibly of Upper Devonian age (Koeberl et al., 2005 and references within). The sandstones belong to 2000 thick Paleozoic sequence of the SW Kufra basin (Miallier et al., 1997). The structure consists of a central hill (~1.5 km diameter) and two concentric rings (~7 and ~11 km in diameter) visible on photographs. The Shuttle Radar Topography Mission (SRTM) data revealed a positive morphological zone extending beyond the outer ring to a 16-17 km diameter (Koeberl et al., 2005).

Age:
Giraudon et al.(1992) estimated the age of the structure based on “the good conservation of the crater and the presence of a poorly developed hydrographic network” at about 3.5-12 ka. Koeberl et al. (2005), however, argued that the morphology and a lack of any melt among the studied samples indicates that the structure is strongly eroded. Bourlès et al. (1995 in Koeberl et al., 2005) obtained 10Be and 26Al minimum exposure age of 0.5 Ma. Thermoluminescence and electron spin resonance dating of quartz from Aorounga also indicated minimum age of 0.5 Ma (Miallier et al., 1997). Assuming that the uplifted sandstones in the structure are of Upper Devonian age the formation of Aorounga could be constrained between the base of Devonian at 385 Ma (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2006) and 0.5 Ma.

Other literature: (Garvin et al., 1995; Ocampo and Pope, 1996; Koeberl et al., 1998; McHone et al., 2002).
Listed as Aorounga south in Ocampo and Pope (1996).

390m diameter crater in Zli sandstone and Oujeft quarzite, with well developed rim 15-25 m tall. Filled with porly sorted silty sand and aeolian sand. Documented Si-rich glass, some samples contaning Ni-rich microspherules. The glass is inhomogeneous with schlieren, partly digested quartz and feldspar, lechatelierite, baddeleyite, low water content and enriched siderofiles. Considering the lack of any volcanic rocks in the area, the glass was taken as a proof of impact origin (Koeberl et al., 1998 and references within). Koeberl et al. (1998) reported rare possible remnants of PDFs in quartz from rim samples and Re-Os isotope analysis of the glass indicating meteoritic component in the glass. Koeberl (1998) in Tagle and Hecht (2006) idnetified iron projectile for the structure based on siderofile elements and osmium isotopes. K-Ar age of the glass is 3.1 ± 0.3 Ma (unknown 1or 2 σ) (Fudali and Cressy, 1976). Fission track analysis on the glass yielded 3.25 ± 0.5 (1σ) Ma (Storzer and Wagner, 1977). The age implies there was no water present at the time of impact.

The Avak structure is centered 12 km SE of the village of Barrow, in the northernmost part of the National Petroleum Reserve in Alaska. It is positioned on top of the E-W trending Barrow high (180x100 km, max. uplift >=900 m), which is superimposed on the broad uplifted Barrow arch trending along the coastline from Chukchi Sea to beyond Prudhoe Bay (>640 km length). 

The bedrocks in the area form four tectonostratigraphic units: 1) The Franklinian sequence consists of mildly metamorphosed lower Paleozoic argillites, greywackes and granites. Deformation of the Franklinian is attributed to the Devonian Ellesmerian orogeny. 2) The Ellesmerian sequence of Mississipian to Triassic clastics and carbonates developed on south-facing continental margin and overlies the Franklinian uncomformably.  3) The Beaufortian sequence consists of Jurassic and Early Cretaceous syn-rift deposits, dominated by marine mud with numerous sandstone intervals and derived locally and from the north. The sequence is truncated by erosion in the lower Cretaceous and progressively deeper toward north. This is a result of the rift related uplift of the Barrow Arch, subsequently accentuated by subsidence to the north and south of the arch. 4) The Brookian sequence represents clastic deposits of the Colville foreland basin derived from the Brooks Range orogene to the south. The middle part of the Brookian sequence has been removed by erosion in the Avak area (Kirschner et al., 1992; Houseknecht, 2004).

The Avak structure is characterized by: (1) a central uplift about 4 km in diameter in which Lower Cretaceous rocks have been uplifted more than 500 m above their regional structural position, (2) a surrounding annular structural depression, or ring syncline, about 1.6 km wide in which the top of Franklinian argillite lies as much as 300 m below its regional structural position, (3) circumferential, centripetally directed, listric faults that define the rim of the Avak structure and are downthrown toward its center, and (4) a structurally high rim with a discontinuous ring of gently outward-dipping homoclines in sedimentary country rock that created "rim anticlines". The anticlines have long outward-facing limbs and short to absent inward-facing limbs that are truncated by the listric normal faults that define the perimeter of the Avak structure. The diameter of the outermost listric fault ring is about 12 km. (Kirschner et al., 1992). 

The Avak structure has a pronounced gravity signature with a positive anomaly over the central uplift and a negative anomaly over the ring trough. Gravity modeling indicates uplift of the Franklinian basement, removal of the Ellesmerian sequence from the rim/trough and its thickening over the uplift. Avak has only a subtle magnetic signature, which does not favor an origin in igneous intrusion or concealed volcanic activity (Kirschner et al., 1992 and references within). 

Avak 1 well drilled in the central uplift encountered uplifted normal stratigraphic sequence with some structurally complex, steeply dipping zones containing repeated sections, breccias and slickenslides. The Ellesmerian sequence in the well is 2.5 times thicker then in wells outside the structure rim. Repeated intervals of Barrow sand host shatter cones, cataclastic deformation and increased percussion fracturing in quartz, chert and feldspar (Kirschner et al., 1992) and planar deformation features (Kirschner et al., 1992; Therriault and Grantz, 1995). Pre-Gubik (i.e., pre-late Pliocene) erosion apparently removed any ejecta. The structure is now covered by ~30 m of Gubik Fm. gravels and sands (Kirschner et al., 1992).

Age:
The youngest disrupted formation in Avak is upper Torok Fm. of likely middle to late Albian. Those beds are unconformably overlain by Pliocene to Holocene sands and gravels of Gubik formation indicating 100-3 Ma age (Kirschner et al., 1992). More recent calibration (Gradstein et al., 2006) assigns base of middle Albian to ~109 Ma. Lithologic logs and microfossil reports for wells within 50 km of Avak center did not indicate any disturbance and the youngest preserved rocks are middle Cenomanian ~95 Ma (Kirschner et al., 1992); more recent calibration places base of middle Cenomanian at ~96.5 Ma (Gradstein et al., 2006). Kirschner (1992) also speculated that submarine slumps at base of Torok formation mapped 170 km south east of Avak might have been triggered by the impact. Kirschner (1992) constrained their age with overlying prograding sandstones of 100 ± 5 Ma. Newer correlations place Torok Fm. at this location in Aptian (Arthur Banet, Bureau of Land Management, Alaska, personal comm. 13 Dec 2007), i.e. 125-112 Ma (Gradstein et al., 2006). Banet (2002; 2005, personal comm. Dec 2007) and Banet and Fenton (2008) described exotic rock fragments in  the Seabee mudstone from well cores drilled 50 to 70 km southeast of Avak that are representative of the stratigraphy in Avak. These fragments are rounded to angular in shape.  They include limestone, black platy shale, red to brown argillitic siltstone, chert and quartzite pebbles in sizes up to about 5 cm.  These lithologies occur in the core of the Avak #1 well which was drilled on the central uplift.   The exotic rock fragments occur in both the mudstone of the Seabee formation and in poorly organized sands, which lack sedimentary features.   Palynology of the Seabee mudstone from the core holes suggests it is Turonian to Coniacian in age.  Palynology of the matrix surrounding the clasts suggests a middle to late Turonian age for the emplacement of the exotic clasts (Banet et al., 2006, 2008), i.e. ~92-89 Ma (Gradstein et al., 2006; Banet and Fenton, 2008). No search for shock evidence in the fragments or Ir enrichment in the horizon has been performed (A. Banet, personal comm. 13 Dec 2007).

The impacting body have landed on a marine prodelta slope or on a delta plain of Albian to middle Cenomanian age or on a marshy coastal plain or a shallow marine shelf of late Cenomanian to Tertiary age (Kirschner et al., 1992).

Original reports, data and core photographs from several wells from Avak can be found in Zihlman et al. (2004).

Beenchime-Salaaty is a partly preserved flat-floored depression surrounded by 50-70 m high rim ~8 km in diameter composed of uplifted and upthrusted Cambrian carbonate rocks. Isolated hills of allogenic breccia are preserved in the depression. The target documented in the area involves 1000-1200 m of Cambrian rocks dominated by carbonates with minor siltstones, sandstones and oil shales. Dolomite and Permian sandstone fragments are present in the allogenic breccia. Carbonates are brecciated within 0.5-1 km zone beyond the rim. Breccias within this zone contain shatter cones. The floor is mainly covered by Quaternary sediments. The preservation of the bedrock rim with allogenic breccia suggest Cenozoic age (Mikhailov et al., 1979) in (Masaitis, 1999).

40 ± 20 Ma age is commonly quoted [EID, 2007 #2882; Masaitis, 1999 #2178] but here the Cenozoic age is calibrated at 65.5-0 Ma with Gradstein et al (2006).
Coordinates from Google Earth following geologic map in Masaitis (1999).

Slightly angular structure with 30-70 m high rim above flat bottom, about 8 km in diameter. The target rocks are Devonian sandstones, siltstones, andesites, basalts, dacites, rhyolites, their tuffs and other rocks folded striking NW and cut by numerous faults. These are cut by dikes and small igneous bodies and overlain by up to 200-300 m of Miocene and Lower Pliocene clays. Interior of the structure is filled with Quaternary sands and gravel.
Gravity data show negative anomaly, magnetic data indicate presence of central uplift. Together with two boreholes these data indicate 200-400 m thick crater fill. Several outcrops of ejecta occur outside the crater, at places resting on top of Miocene clays. Shatter cones occur in the rim. (Kiselev and Korotushenko, 1986) in (Masaitis, 1999).

Commonly cited age is 5 ± 3 Ma (Masaitis, 1999; EID, 2007) but the vague stratigraphic constraints cited by Masaitis (1999) suggest wider uncertainty range.

Bloody Creek structure is an elliptical 0.35 x 0.42 km diameter NW trending depression, 10 m deep, rimmed by a continuous low scarp and filled with lacustrine and wetland sediments. The structure formed within the medium- to coarse-grained biotite monzogranite of the Scrag Lake pluton, the older group of the 388-372 Ma South Mountain Batholith. The area has been glaciated, has a low relief and is mostly covered by <5 m thick till, wetland, lake and forest. The structure is now flooded by a dam and previously was exposed within a wetland. The low depth/diameter ratio indicates that the structure has been deeply eroded or that it formed in once overlying ice (Spooner et al., 2009). 
The gravity anomaly is highest at the rim and decreases outward. Ground Penetrating Radar imaged layered infill sediments overlying disturbed basement within the rim diameter (Spooner et al., 2009).
Samples of the bedrock from the rim and outside the structure reveal progressive occurrence of features consistent with impact: microbrecciation, cataclasis, kink-banding reduced quartz birefringence and mosaicism, degradation of biotite to chlorite showing plastic deformation and flow microstructures, and rare planar microstructures in feldspar and common 1 to 4 sets in quartz. The planar microstructures in quarts are decorated with fluid inclusions and similar to PDFs. One third of these are well developed and their width, spacing and crystallographic orientations dominated by (10-13) and (10-12) are consistent with PDFs. Photographs, and statistics of the measurements shown (Spooner et al., 2009). 
The peat sedimentation rate in the structure compared to nearby well-dated bogs suggests pre-deglaciation age, <12 ka. This is consistent with the deep erosion or impact in ice. Faulting within the sediments indicates active differential compaction and therefore young age (Spooner et al., 2009). The older age limit is the age of the granite. 
A cluster of arcuate, rimmed scarps 1 km north of the structure may record additional smaller impact sites (Stevens et al., 2007).
First report (Stevens, 1995).

Complex impact structure ~24 km in diameter buried under ~30 m of Quaternary sediments with poor surface morphologic expression. Target rocks include Kirovograd porphyroblastic granite (~1550 Ma) and minor biotite gneisses (1850-2220 Ma). Central uplift is 4 km in diameter at a flat top and records ~600 m stratigraphic uplift. The central uplift is surrounded by a deep annular basin ~12 km in diameter and a peripheral depression around the inner deep basin. Uplifted rim is exposed in the NW in the Tyasmin river valley. The deep basin is filled with breccias, suevite and melt. The whole crater is filled with post-impact sedimentary rocks reaching 470 m thickness above the central uplift and 550 m over the deepest part of the crater.  The crater is surrounded by patches of ejecta cropping out in valleys. These were deposited directly on the crystalline basement, which was exposed at the time. Various shock features have been documented in the crater and in the ejecta. The structure has been drilled extensively (Gurov et al., 2003 and references within).

Ar-Ar laser step heating yielded 65.17 ± 0.64 (95%) Ma age, which is a weighted average of three samples of crystalline impactite melts with age spectrum plateau (Kelley and Gurov, 2002). The analysis used GA1550 standard of Renne et al. (1998) and was reviewed and confirmed by Jourdan et al. (2009). This age is consistent with biostratigraphic age 65-66.8 Ma (Valter and Plotnikova, 2003) and a fission track age 65.04±1.10 (1σ) Ma (Kashkarov et al., 1998). Earlier ages obtained with K-Ar technique include 56 Ma, 88 ± 3 Ma and 173 Ma (Gurov et al., 2003 and references within).

Simple structure with raised rim ~170-190 m in diameter on a flank of a ridge. The target includes steeply dipping Palaeoproterozoic gneiss, schists and quartz vein, and pre-crater colluvium. Ejecta are preserved around the crater up to 300 m away (Shoemaker et al., 2005). Iron projectile yielded cosmogenic C-14 age of 0.00540 ± 0.0015 Ma (Kohman and Goel, 1963 in Shoemaker et al., 2005); erroneously listed in (EID, 2009) as 0.0540 ± 0.0015 Ma. 10Be-26Al exposure age of a quartz vein and an ejecta block is ~0.03 Ma (Shoemaker et al., 1990). Shoemaker et al. (2005) preferred 0.03 Ma age because the 0.0054 Ma age was acquired with pre-accelerator technology and would require unrealistically high erosion rates. Projectile octahedral iron (Shoemaker et al., 2005), IIIA (Bevan, 1996).

Observed fall of a meteorite on 15 September 2007, ~16:45 UTC. 
The impact occurred on the Puna Plateau, into red-dish brown soil 4 to 5 meters thick covering Cenozoic continental red beds, siltstones, sandstones and shales. The circular crater is located on a bed, and affected a bank, of a seasonal river. The fresh crater had a deep central depression 7.5 m in diameter and a raised rim up to 1 m tall and 13.5 m in diameter. Ejecta are focused to the SE quadrant of the rim and reach up to 250 m from the crater (Núñez Del Prado et al., 2008; Tancredi et al., 2008). Preliminary investigation revealed quartz grains with possible PDFs and little to no evidence for target melting (Harris et al., 2008). Kenkmann et al. (2009) did not observe any shock features in samples and their impact trajectory modeling indicates the impact did not generate a shock wave.
The recovered meteorite fragments were classified as ordinary chondrites H4-H5 (Connolly, 2008). Noble gases composition favors H5 classification (Ott et al., 2008). The unusual preservation of the projectile during atmospheric entry drew attention of several research groups (Borovička and Spurný, 2008; Brown et al., 2008; Kenkmann et al., 2008; Schultz et al., 2008; Kenkmann et al., 2009).

Target: 
crystalline metasedimentary and metaigneous Proterozoic to Paleozoic basement, 600-1000 m of unconsolidated siliciclastic sediments and ~300 m of sea water (Poag et al., 2004 and references within).

Diameter: 
The structure has a deep central part in the crystalline basement and a wider shallower depression in the sediments with a base at the top of the basement. The present day 85-90 km diameter of the final crater rim is a result of a large strength contrast between the crystalline basement and the soft sediment (Poag et al., 2004 and references within). Turtle et al. (2005) estimated ~25 km diameter for transient crater, ~38 final rim if formed in crystalline target entirely, and ~160 km outer limit of deformation. 

Age:
Ar-Ar dating of North American tektites correlated with the structure yielded 35.2 ± 0.3 to 35.5 ± 0.3 Ma.  Biostratigraphy indicates the event took place within the overlap of the planktonic foraminiferal zone P15 and calcareous nannofossil biochrone NP19-20, i.e. 35.2-36.0 Ma. Magnetostratigraphically-derived sedimentation rate indicates 35.78 Ma age (Poag et al., 2004 and references within). The uncertainties associated with each method suggest ~ ± 0.3 Ma uncertainty range. Jourdan et al. (2009) reviewed 40Ar-39Ar data from earlier studies and confirmed the 35.5 ± 0.3 Ma age.

Impact evidence includes shocked minerals, melts etc. (Poag et al., 2004 and references within). Presently buried under 300-500 m of post-impact siliciclastic sediments.

Multiring structure whose impact origin has been documented through multiple studies (e.g. Meteoritics and Planetary Science 2004, vol 39, issues 6-7). Target included basement granite, gneiss, and amphibolite and overlying ~3 km thick Mesozoic sequence of siliciclastics, carbonates and evaporates (anhydrite) (Kettrup and Deutsch, 2003) and a “very shallow, inner neritic” (Arz et al., 2004) water, i.e. <200 m deep. Suffered about 0.3-0.4 km of erosion before burial under ~1 km of sediments (Turtle et al., 2005 and references therein). Currently half of the structure in onshore and half offshore in up to ~100 m water depth. 

Diameter:
Transient crater ~100 km, final rim ~150 km, peak ring 80, external rings 170-180 and 195-200 km, outer limit of deformation 250 km (Turtle et al., 2005 and references therein). Original work on diameter (Hildebrand et al., 1995; Morgan et al., 1997; Morgan and Warner, 1999; Snyder et al., 1999; Unsworth et al., 2002; Pope et al., 2004; Vermeesch and Morgan, 2004; Morgan et al., 2006).

Age:
Jourdan et al., (2009) preferred 65.55 ± 0.05 Ma (2σ), which is the Ar/Ar step heating age of Swisher et al. (1992) recalculated with the Fish Canyon tuff calibration of Jourdan and Renne (2007). Kuiper et al. (2008) preferred ~65.95 Ma Ar/Ar step heating age on various impact glasses and volcanic sanidines tuned to astronomical cycles and using their revised age of the Fish Canyon tuff calibration 28.201 ± 0.046 Ma. The uncertainty in this age is ~0.055 Ma including the Ar/Ar data uncertainty ± 0.040 Ma (2σ) and ±~0.015 Ma uncertainty in the astronomical tuning. For review of previous ages (Izett et al., 1991; Swisher et al., 1992; Dalrymple et al., 1993; Swisher et al., 1993) see (Kuiper et al., 2008). (Keller et al., 2004; Keller et al., 2007) argued that Chicxulub predates the K-T boundary by 0.3 Ma based on occurrence of multiple ejecta layers but Smit (1999) interprets those as redeposited ejecta from a single impact event. Also see Keller, Smit and others (2003-4). (Kuiper et al., 2008) also considered their dating consistent with one event, not two.

Projectile:
Platinum Group Elements in K-T boundary sediments indicate chondritic projectile (Kyte et al., 1985). Cr isotopes in K-T boundary sediments (Shukolyukov and Lugmair, 1998) as well as petrographic and chemical characteristics of a fossil meteorite (Kyte, 1998) indicate carbonaceous chondrite.

First reported by Stone (1999), Cloud Creek is a circular structure documented using several 2D reflection seismic lines of fair to good quality, gravity, magnetic and borehole data (Stone and Therriault, 2003). The structure has a central core of brecciated, fractured and faulted rocks uplifted up to 520 m relative to the normal stratigraphy outside the structure. The core is surrounded by annular trough and a detached fault-bounded rim anticline. The rim anticline defines the 7 km diameter of the structure. The structure was compressed and upthrown during the Laramide compression. Morphometric parameters of the structure are consistent with known impact structures. The core is associated with positive gravity anomaly. Magnetic data could not be interpreted (Stone and Therriault, 2003). 
Thee is no evidene for volcanic activity, igneous intrusion, caldera or maar formation, salt tectonics or solution collapse and intersecting wrench fault tectonics (Stone and Therriault, 2003).
 
The target stratigraphy includes Precambrian crystalline basement overlaid by Paleozoic carbonates and sandstones and Triassic clastics.  Erosion during the latest Triassic through Middle Jurassic removed an unknown thickness of sediments and upper part of the structure. The structure is covered by ~1200 m of undisturbed Middle Jurassic to Cretaceous sedimentary rocks. Chronostratigraphic constraints date the structure at 190 ± 20 Ma. He impact probably occurred on an exposed lithified part of the non-marine Chugwater Fm., therefore it is unlikely that there was any significant amount of standing water present at the time of impact (Stone and Therriault, 2003).

Samples of drill cuttings documented breccias with fragments of siliciclastics, carbonates and anhydrite. PDFs in quartz were reported in samples from below the Tr-J unconformity, at the margin of the central uplift (Stone and Therriault, 2003). Presented photographs (Stone and Therriault, 2003, fig, 8) show single to multiple sets of linear features in quartz but the low resolution of the images does not allow a reader to evaluate them clearly. Presented statistics of PDF orientations measured with optical microscope documented 1 to 4 sets of PDFs in 9 grains representing <5 % of studied grains (ω > π > ζ > r,z). The grains were 0.3-0.5 mm in diameter and had straight to undulatory extinction resulting in <5 º error in orientation. The PDFs were described as decorated, straight to moderately curved, covering 100 % of the grain and having 1-5 µm spacing between individual planes (Stone and Therriault, 2003).

Subdued circular structure with a central hill barely visible on satellite images located at lat. 25.29992º, lon. 78.13419º (Pati et al., 2008). The structure was earlier assigned to cryptovolcanic or tectonic origin (references in Pati et al., 2008). Central elevated area consists of subhorizontal sandstone, shale and lateritized conglomerate (~1600 Ma or less, Vindhyan Supergroup) and bedded ash. This is surrounded by a ring of mainly flat-lying siltstones with local polymict conglomerate lenses. Occasional slumping and contorted bedding is observed mainly close to the central elevation. The rocks also contain centimeter to >2 m clasts of granitoids. The rocks of this ring area are overlain by the Vidhyan Supergroup rocks. The outermost annular zone is composed of a monomict breccia predominantly consisting of country rock granitoids with varied topographic expressions. Several outcrops of a melt breccia occur within the outer zone towards its inner margin. The basement rocks surrounding the structure include igneous and metamorphic rocks and giant quartz veins of the Bundelkhand craton. The basement rocks near the central area of the structure are overprinted by intensive brittle deformation and radial displacements up to 200 m relative to regional trends (Pati et al., 2008).

The melt breccia yielded numerous shock indicators: multiple PDFs in quartz and feldspar, ballen-textured quartz after diaplectic glass or lechatelierite, and checkerboard feldspar, fluidized clasts, diaplectic glass, coesite, shocked zircons (Pati et al., 2008).

The extent of the breccias defines the present day 11 km apparent diameter of the structure, which is likely the minimum estimate of the original rim-rim diameter. The age of the structure is constrained by the youngest 2000-2150 Ma pre-impact rocks and the lower Vindhyan 1600->1700 Ma post-impact sediments (Pati et al., 2008). 

The central area has been drilled (Pati et al., 2008).

Initial reports (Pati, 2005; Pati et al., 2006b; Pati et al., 2006a).

A crater with a present day diameter 4.5 km excavated in Silurian carbonates, Devonian sandstones and carbonates, and lower Carboniferous carbonates. 300-350 m thick allogenic breccia in the annular trough contains clasts from all the named target rocks. The central uplift consists of upper and middle Devonian rocks, which are ~300 m above their original stratigraphic position. The rocks contain occasional shatter cones and shocked quartz. The post-impact sequence within the crater includes 50 m of upper Permian and lower Triassic carbonates. The whole crater is covered by ~25 m of Quaternary clays and sands (Masaitis, 1999 and references within).
Abels et al. (2002) quoted biostratigraphic age 170-240 Ma without further explanation. Raukas (2000) quoted post-Triassic age referring to Puura et al. (1994). This age is inconsitent with the above stratigraphy. Masaitis (1999) and (EID, 2009) quoted 290 ± 35 Ma age without further explanation. Dutch (2003) quotes 300 ±35 Ma without further explanation. The above stratigraphy constrains the age post Devonian-Carboniferous boundary and pre- Permian-Triassic boundary, i.e. 359.2-251 Ma calibrated with Gradstein et al (2006).
Masaitis (1999), Abels et al. (2002) and (EID, 2009) all list lat/lon 56.58/23.25.

Deep water impact site. First evidence for an impact was an Ir anomaly in sediment cores (Kyte et al., 1981), later work documented impact ejecta across 600 km (Kyte et al., 1988). The ejecta were found to contain microtektites, microkrystites and Ni-rich spinels (Margolis et al., 1991), melted vesicular and unmelted basaltic fragments with major and trace element composition corresponding to howarditic meteorite and metal particles (Kyte and Brownlee, 1985). Following detailed geochemical work on melted and unmelted material documented that the projectile composition was closer to mesosiderite than howardite, i.e. low iron (~4 %) mesosiderite (Kyte, 2002a). 

The sedimentary cores from the area of the highest ejecta concentration document pervasive sediment disturbance but do not indicate that a crater was excavated at the ocean floor. The distributed meteoritic ejecta indicate 1-4 km asteroid, which would excavate 15-40 km diameter crater on land but would not penetrate the crust in deep ocean basin (Gersonde et al., 1997; Kyte, 2001). Claims of a much larger crater 132 ± 5 km in diameter discovered at 53.7S, 90.1W (Glatz et al., 2002; Abbott et al., 2003) have been met with skepticism (Gersonde et al., 2003a). The know strewn field now extends from core E10-2 (56°S, 82.8°W ) in the east to core PS58 280-2 (57.5°S, 93.8°W ) in the west, a distance of ~660 km, and from PS2708-1 (57.8°S, 91°W ) in the south to PS58 294-1 (55.8°S, 92.1°W ) in the north, a distance of ~200 km (Kyte et al., 2005). Coordinates of the impact site are near Freden Seamounts (Kyte et al., 2006). 

Combined magnetostratigraphic and biostratigraphic data from cores (essentially 1 core) initially placed the age of the impact at ~2.15 Ma (Gersonde et al., 1997) but analysis of 4 more cores costrained the age to 2.511 ± 0.07 Ma (Gersonde et al., 2003b). Other references: (Kyte, 2001, 2002b).

A structure formed in a succession of Neoproterozoic sedimentary rocks and mafic intrusions of northwestern Officer Basin. Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1997) described rock deformation and magnetic data consistent with impact but found no shatter cones or other shock features. Later field work further documented exposed steeply dipping siliciclastic rocks in otherwise flat lying or gently dipping rock sequences. Some of the outcrops are covered with Cenozoic laterite. The structure is associated with prominent circular magnetic anomaly ~14 km in diameter but the outcrops do not form prominent circular topography. The relationship of the magnetic anomaly to the bedrocks is not clear. Out of several considered scenarios, the pre-impact horizontal dolerite sheet uplifted and tilted in circular pattern during impact is the scenario most consistent with data. Plannar features occur in quartz grains but no PDFs have been observed (Macdonald et al., 2005). Macdonald et al. (2005) documented a conical feature with poorly developed horse-tailing striations and interpretted it to be a shatter cone. The extend of chaotic bedding and arcuate truncations of the regional magnetic fabric suggest a present day diameter of 19 km.

Macdonald et al. (2005) dated zircons from a dolerite 25 km away from the structure using SHRIMP U-Pb method. The results indicate that the dolerite sill intruded the target sandstone at 508 ± 5 Ma (95% confidence). Assuming that the altered mafic rocks exposed at Glikson correlate to these nearby dolerite sills, the 508 Ma date represent the older limit for the age of the Glikson structure. Considering the erosional rates in central Australia and the level of erosion of the Glikson structure, Macdonald et al. (2005) argued that the structure formed before Cenozoic and likely during Middle to Late Paleozoic.

Near circular depression bounded by steep 100-150 m cliffs in Kimberly Basin of northern Western Australia (Harms et al., 1980; Milton and Macdonald, 2005). The upper edge of the topografic rim defines 5.8 km east–west and 6.3 km north–south diameter. The target includes silicified Proterozoic Pentecost Sandstone of the Kimberley Group and the overlying Hilfordy Formation of the
Crowhurst Group. The northern sector of the crater is composed Liga Shale of the Crowhurst Group, and sandstone, siltstone and carbonate of the Egan and Yurabi Formations of the Late Neoproterozoic Louisa Downs Group, which locally overlie the Crowhurst (Milton and Macdonald, 2005). Harms et al. (1980) reported upturned and overturned layers, fractured bedrock sandstone overlayed with  breccia and a patch of melt breccia in the rim. Two drill holes penetrated 211 and 212 m of lacustrine sediments and brecciated sandstone below. Harms et al. (1980) reported well developed shatter cones in the drilled rocks and some in the rim outcrops. Harms et al. (1980) saw no evidence for central uplift but noted depth/diameter ratio inermediate between simple and complex craters. Harms et al. (1980) observed abundant shock features in quartz, and vesicular twisted silica glass (mostly recrystallized) in the outcrops but did not present any data to document any of the shock features. Milton and Macdonald (2005) confirmed all of the previous observations and documented them with detailed topographic and geologic maps, photographs of poorly developed shatter cones and PFs, PDFs and melt in quartz. 

Polen found in the crater lake sediments (at 139 m depth in total 211 m sediment thickness) indicated early Eocene age for the sediment (Harms et al., 1980). The crater therefore must be >48.6 ± 0.2 Ma (top Ypresian calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2004). Milton and Macdonald (2005) assumed the crater formed shortly before those sediments still within Eocene, i.e. after 55.8 ± 0.2 Ma  (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2004). This age has been variously quoted as <50 Ma (EID, 2004, 2009; Sharpton, 2004) or ~50 Ma (Glikson, 1996).

Gosses Bluff impact affected sedimentary rocks of the Late Proterozoic-Devonian Amadeus Basin. This intracratonic basin is filled with mostly siliciclastic sediments (siltstones, sandstones and conglomerates) with high proportion of arkosic sandstone. Exception is the Bitter Springs Formation at a lower stratigraphic level consisting of lower evaporitic Gillen Member and upper carbonate Loves Creek Member. Total sediment thickness below Gosses Bluff structure is 11 km (Tingate et al., 1996).
The structure is morphologically expressed by a ring of steeply dipping beds, 4 km in diameter, which represents the central uplift. Most of the original 24 km structure has been eroded to its floor level. Remnants of the structure fill are present around the morphological ring. Seismic data and two wells within the structure revealed totally disrupted sedimentary rocks below the structure down to 2300 m depth and on the surface over 6 km away from the center. The rocks are faulted and fractured, blocks of repeating stratigraphic ages are overturned or steeply dipping. Underlying rocks down to 6300 m depth are faulted and fractured but they preserve continuous seismic reflectors. The top of this zone has been uplifted by 680 m. Below 6300 m down to 7000 m lies the Gillen Member of the Bitter Springs Formation consisting of two or more thick halite units. The top of the halite is slightly doming; the base remains flat. This unit assimilated the impact shock wave so that the underlying silicified sandstone and the basement remained undeformed. The highly acoustically contrasting salt top probably reflected most of the propagating shock wave to the surface and caused an unusually high central uplift for the structure of its size (Tingate et al., 1996).
The impact origin of the Gosses Bluff has been documented with multiple shock indicators (shatter cones, high pressure minerals, shock deformation in minerals, melting) and geophysical studies (Milton et al., 1996b; Milton et al., 1996a).

The stratigraphy constrains the age of the structure between the Late Devonian (youngest deformed strata) (Milton et al., 1996a) and the Eocene-Oligocene erosional surface (Tingate et al., 1996). Zircons from sandstone breccia yielded a fission-track age of 134 ± 12 Ma (2σ). Analysis of pumiceous sanidine rich melt breccia yielded K-Ar age 136.5 ± 3 Ma (2σ). The 40Ar/39Ar analysis of the same material yielded a spectrum of apparent ages increasing with the fraction of released argon. The total-gas age was 137.8 ± 1.6 (2σ) Ma, consistent with the K-Ar age. Three heating steps between 56.5 and 91.3 % of cumulative released Ar yielded indistinguishable apparent ages averaging 142.5 ± 1.6 (2σ) Ma (Milton and Sutter, 1987). Jourdan et al. (2009) pointed out that the increasing age spectrum was characteristic of Ar loss and proposed an age ~143 Ma or older without further indication of uncertainty. Assuming the age spectrum represents a post-impact Ar loss, the ratio of the total-gas and “plateau” ages suggests an Ar loss of ~8 % and therefore somewhat older age. Alternatively, the spectrum could represent poorly reset pre-impact age of the precursor minerals and the age of the impact structure could be near the minimum age of the age spectrum ~125 Ma. Thus, ±15 % (~ ± 21.5 Ma) appears to be a reasonable range of uncertainty.

Other detailed work (Gorter et al., 1996; Gorter, 1998).

Circular structural anomaly in flat-lying Mesoproterosoic strata of McArthur Basin. Central uplift ~1.5km in diametr surrounded by outer annulus with outer diameter ~3 km.
Target: Abner Sandstone (+-mudstone) of the Roper Group exposed in the outcrops. It is presumably underlain by sandstones and mudstones of the Crawford Fm. The Abner Sandstone was likely covered by mudstone/sandstone of the Corcoran Fm. and still younger sandstone of the Bessie Creek Fm. (Haines, 1996). 
Shock evidence: insitu shatter cones within structural uplift with radial faults, one to multiple sets of PDFs in quartz typically decorated with fluid inclusions (photographed and measured) (Haines, 1996).
Diameter: present day 3 km diameter is an erosional remnant (below crater floor). Structural considerations sugest original 7-25 km diameter (Haines, 1996).
Age: ~1400 Ma age of the target rocks provides older age limit. Considering the wider geological context and evolution of the McArthur Basin the structure is likely pre-Cretaceous (Haines, 1996).
EID (2009) listed <1400 Ma age without reference, ignoring the younger age limit. Fortes (2000) listed unreferrenced age 136 Ma - probably misinterpreted from (Haines, 1996) as Goyder is "pre-Cretaceous" and J/K boundary in 1989 IUGS stratigraphic chart is 135 Ma.

Granby is a simple bowl-shaped depression over 377 m deep and ~2 km in diameter surrounded by up to 70 m high elevated rim of brecciated crystalline pre-Cambrian rocks. The depression is filled with 70 m of a polymict sedimentary breccia with angular fragments of Cambrian and Ordovician sandstones, limestones, shales, and crystalline bedrock. It is followed by 20 m of bituminous shale and by a sequence of limestones and mudstones typical for the Ordovician in the area (Bruun and Dahlman, 1982 in Alwmark, 2009).
The target at the time of impact consisted of 25-75 m of water, 50-200 m of sediment (Ordovician limestone, Cambrian sand and mudstone), and crystalline basement. The drill cores show evidence of slumping and preserved overturned flap at the rim. The rim was apparently high enough to prevent water flooding, as there is no evidence of resurge deposits in the cores (Ormö and Lindström, 2000). The structure has been buried and preserved on a down-faulted crystalline block (Bruun and Dahlman, 1982 in Abels et al., 2002) and was partially exhumed during the Neogene or later (Abels et al., 2002). The crater is presently covered by 10-40 m of soil (Alwmark, 2009, Fig.1).

The structure was biostratigraphically dated at the late Early Ordovician ~465 Ma (Grahn et al., 1996 in Ormö et al., 2000). Alwmark (2009) revised this age to the Middle Ordovician ~467 Ma following the 2004 Geological Time Scale. Multiple compilations listed ~470 Ma age without an explanation (Henkel and Pesonen, 1992; EID, 2004, 2009) but likely corresponding to an earlier calibration of the biostratigraphic age. Considering the various quotations, the uncertainty in the age appears to be ± ~5 Ma.

Alwmark (2009) studied samples from the borehole Fylla Norrgård using optical microscopy with universal stage and SEM, and documented multiple sets of decorated planar deformation features (PDFs) in quartz grains from sandstone and basement fragments. The shock evidence or any other accepted prove of impact has not been reported before although geologic evidence led others to consider the crater to be of impact origin since the 1980’s (Henkel and Pesonen, 1992; Ormö and Lindström, 2000; Abels et al., 2002; EID, 2004, 2009).

Abels et al. (2002) quoted 3.2 km diameter interpreted from drill cores citing Bruun and Dahlman (1982) and Ormö et al. (2000) quoted 3 km diameter (also citing Bruun and Dahlman, 1982). This diameter appears to correspond to the outer edge of the interpreted crystalline rim in the Figure 1 of Alwmark (2009, modified after Bruun and Dahlman, 1982). The ~2 km diameter quoted by Alwmark (2009) appears to correspond to the inner edge of the rim in the same figure. Assuming the figure is accurate and the crater is only mildly eroded, the ~2 km diameter is approximately the final rim-rim diameter of the crater.
Alwmark (2009) quoted lat. 58.417º, long. 14.917º for the crater location. Comparison with the Figure 1 of Alwmark (2009 modified after Bruun and Dahlman, 1982) and with the coordinates for the studied borehole Fylla Norrgård suggest lat. 58.426º, long. 14.932º for the center of the crater. This is also an intermediate location between coordinates quoted by EID (2009, 58.417/14.933) and Abels et al. (2002, 58.433/14.933).

The Gweni Fada structure is a broad crescent shaped depression ~12 km in diameter surrounding a central elevated complex, which is ~10 km in diameter. The rocks (limestones and sandstones) in the central zone and in the ~14 km diameter rim are tilted and folded. Preliminary petrographic study showed the presence of shock metamorphic effects in quartz grains from sandstones (Vincent and Beauvilain, 1996 in Koeberl et al., 2005). Structural analysis based on the Shuttle Radar Topography Mission (SRTM) data revealed 4-5 km wide rim zone, which defines the ~22 km diameter for the impact structure. This larger diameter is consistent with the ~9 km diameter (derived from SRTM data) of the central uplift (Koeberl et al., 2005). Petrographic analysis of quartzite, sandstones and quartz conglomerate documented local brecciation and multiple sets of PDFs (Koeberl et al., 2005).

Age:
The exposed sandstones in the structure are probably of Upper Devonian age (Koeberl et al., 2005 and references within). The base of Upper Devonian at 385 Ma (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2006) thus defines the oldest possible age of the structure.

"Eskola (1921) considered a volcanic origin for the Jänisjärvi structure and particularly for the melt rocks. An impact origin for the structure was proposed by Dence (1971) on the basis of a satellite image. The discovery of shatter cones and planar deformation features (PDFs) in a quartz clast from a breccia sample (Hopeasaari Island) proved the impact origin of the structure. It was also shown that chemical composition of the target rocks and the impact melt rocks (tagamites) are almost identical (Masaitis et al., 1976). These conclusions were later confirmed by other authors (e.g., Raitala and Halkoaho, 1992). ... Puura and Plado (2005) claim that Jänisjärvi was formed in a composite target consisting of crystalline basement covered by Precambrian sediments during the Neoproterozoic. ... The Jänisjärvi impact structure is situated in Proterozoic crystalline schists (Koistinen, 2003). Major phases are plagioclase, biotite, and quartz, with subordinate muscovite, garnet, staurolite, and cordierite (Masaitis et al., 1976; Raitala and Halkoaho, 1992). Due to the impact event, the schists around the lake are fractured. Puura and Plado (2005) claim that Jänisjärvi was formed in a composite target consisting of crystalline basement covered by Precambrian sediments during the Neoproterozoic. From the Early Paleozoic until the Mesozoic, marine sediments have been depositing over the Jänisjärvi structure. During the Cenozoic, the erosion of the structure became significant and slowly reached the actual shape, namely an eroded impact structure, where part of the impact-related lithologies are preserved. The present erosional margin of the Paleozoic sedimentary deposits (100–350 m thick) is located ~100 km to SE from Jänisjärvi, in the southern Lake Ladoga area, where the sedimentary rocks show an increasing thickness towards the north. The impactites are mainly exposed on the three named islands, but a minor exposure of these rocks also occurs at Cape Leppiniemi on the SW coast. Similar to other impact structures (Masaitis, 2005), the impact lithologies within the Jänisjärvi include impact melt rocks (tagamites), suevites, and lithic breccias. In particular, the approximately 15–20 m thick tagamite layer overlies suevites and the lithic breccias. The tagamites contain clasts of recrystallized schists, quartz, and other minerals from target rocks. Sizes of these clasts are a few centimeters across. The groundmass of tagamites consists of plagioclase, hypersthene, quartz, cordierite, small amounts of biotite, K feldspar, ilmenite, graphite, and glass. Suevite consists of fragments of schists and recrystallized glass. The schist fragments may reach about 2 m across, but most of them are not larger than 5–10 cm. The cement of this rock consists of the same comminuted and partly altered material. The lithic breccias are composed of clasts of schists and, rarely, pegmatites, and are cemented by a finely crushed matrix of the same rocks. Shatter cones up to 20–30 cm long occur in metasiltstones (Masaitis et al., 1976). These metasiltstones probably belong to the Late Precambrian cover, which was overlain by the crystalline basement at the time of impact (see also Puura and Plado, 2005)." - (Salminen et al., 2006).
Estimated original diameter 18 km (Abels et al., 2002).
PGE data and Cr isotopes indicate H chondrite projectile (Tagle et al., 2006).
Age:
Masaitis et al. (1976) in Salminen et al. (2006) determined K/Ar age at 718 ± 5 Ma. Müller et al. (1990) attempted 40Ar/39Ar step-heating age determination. They analyzed cryptocrystalline whole rock melt with some small pre-impact clasts. The main identified Ar carrier was feldspar. The analysis yielded a complex apparent age spectrum and the best age estimate 698 ± 22 (2σ) Ma.  Well-defined paleomagnetic data from tagamites, suevites,  lithic breccias and target rocks indicate two possible ages for impact induced magnetization of Jänisjärvi rocks: 1) Late Sveconorwegian age (900-850 Myr) or 2) Late Cambrian age (~500 Myr) (Salminen et al., 2006). Considering the inherent inaccuracy of K/Ar method and complex 40Ar/39Ar results the data broadly constrained the age of the structure between 500 and 900 Ma. Jourdan et al. (2008) obtained 40Ar/39Ar step-heating data on five melt rock grains. The data are all concordant and indicate an age of 682 ± 4 Ma (2σ).

Jebel Waqf as Suwwan  (Mountain of Upright Chert) is a complex circular structure in subhorizontal sedimentary strata in east central region of Jordan. It has a prominent outer rim rising 60 m above the surrounding plain and 5.5 km in diameter, an intermediate ring of up to 20 m elevation within a ring syncline, and a central stratigraphically uplifted zone. The central zone is intensely folded, faulted and shows widespread macroscopic, and locally mesoscopic, cataclasis. The strata affected by the structure include Cenomanian sandstones and Cenomanian to middle Eocene limestones, dolomite, marls, shales, sandstone and cherts. Well-developed shatter cones occur on numerous locations within the central zone. Cataclasis is common on a microscale in chert and limestones. Only one quartz grain in a sandstone yielded 2 sets of PDFs and 2 sets of planar fractures out of 70 studied samples of various lithologies (Salameh et al., 2008). 

Age:
Salameh et al. (2008) noted that the structure encompasses middle Eocene strata and thus derived maximum age of the structure. They however quote this age inconsistently as “post-Paleogene”, “about 30 Ma or younger” and “Miocene or Pleistocene”. None of these ages is consistent with the latest preserved affected strata being middle Eocene. Although the structure appears deeply eroded and much younger strata could have been affected by the impact, the age estimate of the structure can only be limited to middle Miocene after the deposition of the youngest preserved layers. In the absence of a more precise age for the youngest preserved strata this database adopts the maximum age at the base of middle Eocene, calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2006) at 48.6 Ma.

Kamensk structure is a buried depression defined by a 2D seismic data, multiple boreholes. The structure is not associated with any gravity, magnetic or resistivity signature. The expression of the structure on satellite and aerial images is ambiguous.
The target rocks consist of siliciclastics, limestone and minor coal of the Middle to Upper Carboniferous, plus some Lower Permian and Lower Triassic. These rocks were tectonically deformed and thrusted. The structure is filled with authigenic (Carboniferous and Triassic rock fragments) and allogenic (Carboniferous, Triassic and Upper Cretaceous rock fragments) breccias. The structure rim is irregular, nearly circular, 20-22 km in diameter. Steep sides of the structure, annular depression and a central uplift could be distinguished.
Shock indicators include shatter cones, fragments of vesicular glass with rock fragments in the allogenic breccia, coesite in redeposited sediments. Quartz grains in the alogenic breccia also contain up to three sets of rare poorly defined planar elements.
Stratigraphically above the allogenic breccia lies a crater fill sequence containing redeposited breccia material. The redeposited material (Glubokaya Fm.) extends far beyond the structure rim coinciding with the extend of the ejecta and contains abundant Upper Cretaceous rock fragments. (Movshovich and Milyanskiy, 1991 and references within).
The Upper Maastrichtian foraminifera in the rock fragments of the allogenic breccia define the older limit on the impact age. The Glubokaya Fm. represents nearly whole Danian based on its foraminifera and nanoplankton. This indicates the structure formed within a shallow sea of late Maastrichtian to early Danian (Movshovich et al., 1991) or ~62-68 Ma. Total-fusion 40Ar-39Ar analysis yielded the weighted-mean age 49.15 ± 0.18 Ma or 49.84 ± 0.18 Ma (using two different calibrations) for six impact glass fragments recovered from a drill hole within the Kamensk structure. The older age falls within magnetic chron 22R consistent with the glass reversed magnetization (Izett et al., 1994). Jourdan et al. (2009) considered the Ar isotopic data reliable and preferred the recalculated age 49.15 ± 0.27 Ma based on a more recent calibration. The discussion of the biostraphic constraints (Movshovich et al., 1991) give an impression of a significant uncertainty in the biostratigraphic interpretation. For example the Danian fauna could be redeposited, the foraminifera in the target lithologies are once described as Santonian-Maastrichtian and once as typical late Maastrichtian (Movshovich et al., 1991) within the same sentence. 
The structure center lat, lon 48.37, 40.49 was located on the Google Earth by comparison with Fig.1 in Movshovich and Milyansky (1991).

Coordinates read from Google Earth based on comparison with a map in (Masaitis, 1999). Diameter from (Masaitis, 1999). Assumed to have a twin crater  Ust'-Kara (Masaytis et al., 1991). It has also been called Karskiy crater (Kolesnikov et al., 1988).
Age:
Early K-Ar data for tagamites and suevites of the Kara structure indicated 50-70 Ma age (Masaitis and Mashchak, 1982; Badjukov et al., 1987 and references within). More precise K-Ar measurements from both Kara structures later yielded 65.8 - 67.6 Ma age for glass, 68.5-73.9 Ma for melt rocks (interpreted as a result of Ar excess), preferred isochron age 66.1 ± 0.8 Ma (Kolesnikov et al., 1988; Kolesnikov et al., 1990a; Kolesnikov et al., 1990b). Step-heating Ar-Ar data from melt rock and glass samples from Kara and a melt rock from shore impactite deposits attributed to Ust'-Kara yielded 71-81 (most probably 73-74) Ma age (Koeberl et al., 1990). Fission track measurements yielded 61-72 Ma (99% confidence) (Kashkarov et al., 1992). Detailed Ar-Ar step-heating analysis of three Kara impact melt rocks supported by detailed data analysis and modeling established 70.3 ± 2.2(2σ) Ma plateau age (Trieloff et al., 1998). Rampino and Schwindt (1999) suggested that the 70.3 Ma age allows overlap with the more recent 71.3  ± 0.5(2σ) Ma Campanian boundary. Trieloff et al. (1999) argued that the statistical is invalid and that the hydrogene isotopes indicate impact on land whereas the region was covered by epicontinental sea during Camp/Maast transition. Trieloff et al. (1999) further pointed out that most of the Maastrichtian was dominated by marine sedimentation and thus the most probable age of Kara is at the lower range of their Ar-Ar age, i.e. 68-70 Ma). Gradstein et al. (2004) list even younger Camp/Maast age 70.6 ± 0.6(2σ) Ma. The age accepted here is thus 69 Ma (Trieloff et al., 1999) within the Ar-Ar uncertainty range (Trieloff et al., 1998).

Documented impact induced hydrothermal alteration (Naumov, 2002).

Buried impact structure with only central uplift exposed at the surface. Target exposed in the 2 km diameter area of central uplift includes quarzitic sandstone of the Paleo- to Mesoproterozoic Hatches group. Dacites near the base of this formation yielded 1862 ± 45 Ma U-Pb age. The uplifted target is overlain by an ancient coluvial deposit that includes clast of intensely shocked sandstone and impact breccia. The colluvium is overlain by early Middle Cambrian marine deposits. The target Hatches group reached over 5 km thickness. It experienced deformation and erosion of ~5 km thicknes during Precambrian. The crater formed after the folding period and likely after this erosion was nearly completed (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996). Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1996) further speculated that the impact occured during Neoproterozoic without additional arguments. The folding occured during ~1700-1600 (reference in Haines, 2005). Haines (2005) quotted 1640-550 Ma age, without clear derivation of the older age limit. EID (2004, 2009) lists >550 Ma age without reference. This works uses the conservative older age limit established by the folding event and the age of the overlying sediments for the younger age limit, i.e. mid of Middle Cambrian at ~507 Ma calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

The size of the uplift suggests original 8-20 km diameter (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996).

Shatter cones are abundant in the central uplift (Tonkin, 1973; Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996). Shock evidence include abundant plannar microstructures in quartz (unpublished reference in Haines, 2005). Besides shatter cone photographs no data on other shock evidence has been published.

A ring of low hills 18 km in external diameter composed of brecciated Cambrian limestone and chert. Central plain ~8 km exposes fractured Proterozoic siltstone, sandstone and a central ring of folded igneous rock with abundant devitrified glass. These Proterozoic rocks were uplifted ~2 km. Well developed shatter cones and "planar lamellae" in quartz occur in Proterozoic siltstone and sandstone (Stewart and Mitchell, 1987). Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1996) confirmed the presence of shatter cones and suevite in the central uplift. The target rocks were folded (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996) during the Isa orogeny, which dates at 1540 Ma in the Western fold Belt (Giles and Nutman, 2002). Middle Cambrian beds are preserved inside the crater (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996). The structure is, therefore, younger that Middle/Upper (Furongian) Cambrian boundary at 501 Ma (Gradstein et al., 2004) and older than 1540 Ma. Glikson (1996) listed pre-middle Cambrian age referring to (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996), EID (2009) listed >515 Ma and Haines (2005) listed Late Neoproterozoic to Early Cambrian?. All of these dates ignore that the published stratigraphic relationships allow Middle Cambrian age. Further, M. Dence (in Haines, 2005) speculated that breccias within the middle Cambrian carbonates could have formed during the impact.  
Considering the extend of the rock deformation, Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1996) estimated the original rim diameter was ~20 km.

The Marquez Dome is located in Leon County, Texas, 190 km NNW of Houston. It is characterized by an anomalous 1.2-km diameter outcrop of Upper Cretaceous rocks in an area where sub-horizontal Upper Paleocene Calvert Bluff sandstone of the Wilcox Group is otherwise at the earth surface. The structure was considered a salt dome in the 1930’s and became a subject of exploration for hydrocarbons. Drilling did not find any salt and in 1989-1990, the well and seismic data led to a reinterpretation of the dome as a central uplift of a complex impact crater (Wong et al., 2001 and references within). Evidence for impact origin of the structure includes shatter cones in Pecan Gap limestone and PDFs and glass in breccias in the central uplift (Gibson, 1990; Sharpton and Gibson, 1990). 
Initial seismic interpretation estimated the structure diameter at minimum 15 km and probably over 20 km (Sharpton and Gibson, 1990). Later seismic and gravity data study refined this estimate at ~13 km (Wong et al., 2001). 

The structure formed during the deposition of Calvert Bluff Fm. characterized by coastal swamp, lacustrine, crevasse-splay and channel-fill environments with siliciclastic deposition [Buchanan, 1998 #3444 and references within]. The deformation of rocks is essentially limited to the central uplift, whereas the surrounding layers are nearly planar, dipping ~1º to the southeast, possibly slightly offset by listric faults. The Senonian Pecan Gap limestone at the surface of the central uplift is >1120 m above its regional position. The amount of uplift decreases in deeper beds and no uplift can be detected on top of the Buda Fm. at 1630 m below sea level. The Marquez structure is associated with +2.2 mGal residual gravity anomaly 1.7 km in diameter over the central uplift. The anomaly decreases to 1.8 mGal in its very center. There is no detectable magnetic anomaly (Wong et al., 2001 and references within).

Stratigraphy indicated 58.8 ± 2 Ma age of the structure (Sharpton and Gibson, 1990). Apatite fission-track data on rocks from the central uplift indicated 58.3 ± 3.1 Ma age (McHone and Sorkhabi, 1994).

The Montagnais structure, near the shelf edge offshore Nova Scotia, was discovered on multichannel seismic data in the early 1970’s. The seismic shows a central uplift surrounded by an annular depression. The base of the central uplift is 17.5 km in diameter and the top is 11.5 km in diameter. The structural uplift appears to be ~2.3 km (1250-2900 m). The top of the uplift is flat with a central depression 3.5 km in diameter and 200 m deep. The uplift is covered  by 552 m of breccia, 653 m of Cenozoic sediments and 113 m of water. The erosion, downwarping and faulting of the pre-impact horizons establishes ~45 km diameter (Jansa and Pe-Piper, 1987; Jansa et al., 1989). More pronounced faulting in the northwest and a slight structure elongation in the NW-SE direction (Jansa et al., 1989) indicates a partial collapse of the shelf edge. A dry exploratory well (Montagnais I-94, Union Oil) was drilled in the central uplift and recovered intensely deformed and shocked material, including breccias, impact melt (initially interpreted to be basalt) suevite, mineral grains with PDFs, diaplectic glass and high pressure mineral polymorphs. The target consists of clastic sediments, evaporites and a metamorphic basement including chloritic metasubgraywackes and phyllites locally intercalated with quartzites and metavolcanics (Jansa and Pe-Piper, 1987; Jansa et al., 1989). 
Gravity data revealed positive 8 mGal anomaly coinciding with the central uplift but showed only weak negative gravity anomaly. The lack of the expected pronounced negative anomaly may be due to weak nature of unconsolidated sediments that prevented extensive fracturing of the target and preservation of the impact induced porosity. Magnetic data do not show any well-defined impact-related signature (Pilkington et al., 1995). 

Major, siderophile and rare earth element compositions of the basement and the melt rocks are nearly identical. Only iridum is enriched in the impact melt relative to the basement by an order of magnitude (Jansa et al., 1989). The impactor was, therefore, most probably a comet (Jansa et al., 1989) or an achondrite. The impact occurred in 200-600 m of water depth (Jansa, 1993).

Age:
K-Ar ages on two impact melt rock samples yielded 55.8 ± 0.9 Ma (Geol.Surv.Canada in Jansa et al., 1989) and 49.9 ± 2.1 Ma (Geochron Lab. in Jansa et al., 1989)
Bottomley and York (1988) analyzed seven melt samples from three different melt horizons in the polymict breccia overlying the central uplift in a laser step-heating 40Ar/39Ar experiment. One sample yielded erratic age spectrum. Three samples yielded 56-57.5 Ma bulk ages. Their age spectra had elevated ages (up to 69 Ma) over the first 20 % of the cumulative Ar released and a tilted plateaux with ages decreasing with progressive degassing from ~57 to ~52 Ma. Three other samples yielded 49-52 Ma bulk ages. Age spectra of two of the samples (from the lowest melt layer) display a classical shape of increasing ages over the low-temperature steps and a plateau at higher temperature steps. The third sample spectrum shows increased ages (up to ~61 Ma) at the low-temperature steps and a slightly tilted plateau with ages decreasing with progressive degassing from ~53 to ~51 Ma. The three plateaux overlapped between 45 and 95 % of the cumulative Ar released. Summed and weighted these overlapping ages yielded 50.5 ± 0.8 (1σ) Ma. 
The sediments immediatelly overlaying the impact structure belong to foraminiferal zone P9 and nanofossil zones NP12-NP13. These, as well as palynological and dinoflagellate data consistent with the radiometric age determination (Jansa et al., 1989, Aubry et al., 1990).

Buried circular structure defined by circular aeromagnetic anomaly ~70 km in diameter. Surrounding concentric structural features in the gravity and magnetic data reach up to 340 km in diameter (Corner et al., 1997; Hart et al., 1997). Petrologic, geochemical and U/Pb geochronologic results from the borehole located 40 from the center of the structure indicate that the borehole is located outside the structure. This constraints the structure diameter to <80 km (Reimold et al., 2002). Gravity and magnetic modeling is consistent with the present day diameter of 65-70 km (Henkel et al., 2002). Target includes Archaean granites and rocks of the Archaean Kraaipan Group, composed of banded ironstones, metavolcanics and minor ultramafics. Possibly also by Proterozoic sediments at the time of impact. Drilling documented granite basement with pseudotachylytes, impact meltsheet enriched in siderofile (Ir) elements and Kalahari sedimentary cover. Quartz in the conglomerate overlaying the meltsheet contains multiple sets of PDFs. Basement is recrystalized with fluid inclusion trails in quartz (likely decorated PDFs) and with silica glass (Corner et al., 1997; Hart et al., 1997). Outcrops of impact rocks are rare and the sedimentary cover reaches up to ~100 m (Koeberl et al., 1997; Corner et al., 1997; Hart et al., 1997).

Age:
Recrystallized zircons from impact melt yielded concordant U/Pb age of 145.2 ± 0.8 (2σ) and biotites yielded Ar-Ar plateau age of 143.5 ± 3.6 Ma (Hart et al., 1997). Separate zircon analyses yielded a 206Pb/238U age of 146.2 ± 1.5 Ma and a 208Pb/232Th age of 144.7 ± 1.9 Ma (Koeberl et al., 1997).
Meteorite from the melt sheet was analyzed with 40Ar/39Ar method. The low-retentivity sites of the meteorite plagioclase grains yielded a composite inverse isochron age of 141 ± 15 Ma (2σ) (Jourdan et al., 2010). Jourdan et al. (2009) prefered the U/Pb age of 145.2 ± 0.8 (2σ) of Hart et al. (1997).

Platinum group elements and Cr isotopes in the impact melt indicate ordinary L-LL chondrite projectile (Koeberl et al., 1997; McDonald et al., 2001; Koeberl and Reimold, 2003). Silicate inclusions in the melt sheet appear to be the fragments of the ordinary chondritic projectile based on petrography and PGE, Re-Os characteristics (Hart et al., 2002). 25cm fragment of unaltered meteorite recovered from the impact melt is LL ordinary chondrite, most similar to LL6 (Maier et al, 2006).

Buried structure that appears on seismic as a circular depression with an elevated rim 3.2 km in diameter. It is a simple structure, i.e., without a central uplift. The target includes Precambrian granite and gneiss, with lesser amounts of schist, amphibolite, and greenstone, and Upper Cambrian to Lower Ordovician Deadwood sandstone with some shale. Drilling through the rim documented that these rocks are fractured and brecciated. These are overlain by unaffected Black Island Fm. sandstones of the lower Winnipeg Group (Ordovician). The post-impact sediments are ~2800 m thick. Thin sections of the breccias revealed planar fractures, planar deformation features (PDFs) in quartz and feldspar (mostly single but also up to five sets), offset twinning in feldspar, and kink bands in biotite (Koeberl and Reimold, 1995; Forsman et al., 1996)

Coordinates are derived from a map in Forsman et al. (1996) and from the position of wells (IHSE, 2005). Stratigraphy constrains the structure age to Upper Cambrian - Lower Ordovician, i.e. 472-501 Ma (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2006). The target Deadwood sandstone was deposited in a shallow marine environment and lithologies in the well indicate part of the crater may have stood above the water (Forsman et al., 1996); indicating a target water depth of ~10-100 m.
