A structure defined by irregular to triangular -10 mGal Bouguer gravity anomaly and three bore holes - two between the interpretted rim and a center of the structure, and one in the rim. The anomaly shows a relative rise to -4 mGal, interpretted to correspond to the central uplift. The negative anomaly is surrounded by arcuate positive anomalies up to +8 mGal thought to correspond to uplifted basement in the rim. Several bore holes in the vicinity of the structure defined regional stratigraphy. The structure formed in Precambrian granites and gneisses covered by ~300 m of predominantly siliciclastic and minor carbonate sediments of Bashkirian Stg. (Carboniferous) and Lower Triassic continental siliciclastics. All of these target lithologies are represented in the breccias filling the structure. The structure was filled and covered by late Bajocian (Middle Jurassic) marine siliciclastics and Bathonian siliciclastics with interbeded limestones. These sequences are thicker in the structure. These are followed by Callovian marine siliciclastics and Oxfordian regressive marine siliciclastics with interbeded limestones; platform Upper Cretaceous marls siliciclastics and chalks; Eocene-Oligocene siliciclastics and marls and loose Quaternary sediments. The rim od the structure is currently ~300 m below the surface. Ejecta occur in several boreholes surrounding the structure (Gurov et al., 2009 and references within).

The diameter of the structure has been variously quoted as 18 (Gurov et al., 2009) or 20 km (EID, 2009). The maxima of the positive anomalies define ~21 km diameter presumably corresponding to the preserved rim diameter.

The impact evidence includes polymict breccias with melt, multiple sets of PDFs in quartz, kinked biotite, diaplectic glasses, coesite, diamonds and shatter cones. Sandy deposits in the upper part of the impactites inside and outside the structure have been interpretted as tsunamites, surge and mass wasting deposits (Gurov et al., 2009 and references within).

The character of the crater fill and surrounding ejecta as well as lithologies represented in the impact breccias suggest the structure formed in a shallow marine environment during Middle Triassic to Bajocian (Middle Jurassic). Impact melt rocks yielded K/Ar ages ranging from 160 ± 30 Ma to 215 ± 25 Ma with the most recent ones being 169 ± 7 Ma. This latest age is consistent with Bajocian times (Gurov et al., 2009 and references within). The paleogeographic studies suggest that Obolon is younger than 185 Ma (Schmieder M. and Buchner E., 2008). The ejecta are overlain by Bajocian sediments and the 2004 geologic time scale (Gradstein et al., 2006) places the top of Bajocian at 167 ± 3.5 (2sigma) Ma therefore the younger age limit should be 163.5 Ma. The combined stratigraphic and paleogeographic constraint on the lower age limit at 185 Ma is taken for the older age limit. The K-Ar of 169 Ma is taken as the best age estimate because it falls in between the stratigraphically and paleogeographically established bounds, although the K-Ar ages are notorious for being inaccurate particularly for impact rocks.

The five Odessa meteorite craters have been known since the late 1920s. They formed in the target consisting of Lower Cretaceous limestone, shale and sandstone overlaid by Pleistocene eolian deposits. The main crater is 152-183 m in diameter defined by topographic high of upturned limestone beds. The erosion has been minimal and did not enlarge the structure by more then 30 m. Surrounding surface is still covered by ejecta that yielded thousands of iron meteorites. Mapping, trenching and coring of the main crater and one of the smaller craters, and excavation of a shaft through the crater fill and into the underlying bedrock showed that the crater cavity is 26 m deep relative to the pre-impact surface (30 m from the rim) and it is filled with 27 m of post impact debris (Holliday et al., 2005 and references within). 

Age:
"Previous investigators recovered remains of an ‘‘elephant tooth’’ and Equus between 6 and 3 m below the surface (Evans and Mear, 2000, p. 28, 38), indicating that the upper fill was late Pleistocene in age (Evans, 1961, p. D-6). Cosmogenic carbon extracted from meteorite fragments was dated to ca. 11,000 ka or older (Goel and Kohman, 1962) and cosmogenic 36Cl/10Be provided an upper age limit of 100 ka (Chang and Wa¨nke, 1969). Both dating methods were in their infancy, however, and the resulting ages are difficult to evaluate. Age estimates of 50 ka and younger were published (e.g., Grieve et al., 1995), based partly on a date of  49 ± 3 ka for the Barringer Meteorite Crater (also known as Meteor Crater) in Arizona (Sutton, 1985). Barringer (1967) proposed that both the Barringer and Odessa impact sites were produced by the same event, which is consistent with similarities between the meteoroids that produced the craters (both are Group IAB irons)." - (Holliday et al., 2005).  New age control for sediment in the main Odessa crater indicates that it filled episodically. Age of the impact is approximated by optically stimulated luminescence age 63.5 ± 0.45 of sediments deposited immediatelly after impact (Holliday et al., 2005).

Paasselkä structure is marked by oval Lake Paasselkä (also called Paasivesi) centered on lat 62.15, lon 29.41 with a shoreline diameter of 9x12 km (Google Earth). The bedrock in the area is mainly ~1.9 Ga micaschist with minor mafic intrusives, numerous granitic and pegmatitic dykes, and some sedimentary rock of the Karelian Supergroup. The structure was heavily eroded by continental glacier (Schmieder et al., 2008 and references within). The impact origin of the structure was proposed on the basis of round topography, -8 mGal gravity anomaly and ≤ 300 nT magnetic anomaly (Henkel and Pesonen, 1992; Pesonen et al., 1999). Drilling on top of the negative magnetic anomaly in the center of the structure recorded 48 m deep water, 20 m of Quaternary deposits and fractured mica schist down to the bottom of the drill hole at 252 m. The breccia includes sparse clasts of pre-impact unmetamorphosed sedimentary rocks (Pesonen et al., 1999). Pesonen et al. (1999) reported 2-3 sets of PDFs in quartz from the breccia but did not provide any data. Another report of shock evidence was presented by (Kuivasaari et al., 2000 in Schmieder et al., 2008). Öhman et al. (2003) reported PDFs, mosaicism and planar cleavage in quartz, strong biotite kinking, melted areas in mica and presented frequency distribution of measured PDF orientations. Badjukov and Raitala (2006) reported Ni-Co-rich sulfides from recrystallized melt rocks. Schmieder et al. (2008) analyzed rock samples collected 1 km SE of the lake shore and documented melt flow texture, PDFs in in quartz, “toasted” and recrystallized quartz, fresh and recrystallized plagioclase melt and Fe-Mg rich melt.

Popigai structure is located at the northeastern margin of the Anabar shield. The target rocks include Archean gneisses and schists, minor Lower Proterozoic igneous rocks, 1-1.5 km of siliciclastic and carbonate sedimentary rocks of Upper Proterozoic, Cambrian, Permian and Cretaceous partially covering the older rocks. Triassic dolerite sills and dykes that are part of the Siberian traps are present mainly to the north of the structure (Masaitis, 2002).

The structure comprises a central depression 45 km in diameter, surrounded by a peak ring 45 km in diameter, annular trough with an outer diameter ~72 km and a flat 20 km wide annular terrace (Masaitis, 2002; Masaitis et al., 2005). Topographic rim of the overall 150 m depression defines 90-100 km diameter (Pilkington et al., 2002). The structure is associated with –35 mGal gravity anomaly and –300 nT magnetic anomaly (Pilkington et al., 2002). A combination of topography, gravity data, impact lithologies distribution and preserved structural rim indicate original rim-to-rim diameter of 100 km, possibly up to 103 km (Masaitis et al., 2005).

The magnitude of erosion varied from 50-150 m in he central depression to 100-250 m on the NW structural rim to 300 in the southern outer zone (Masaitis et al., 2005). Large volumes of impact lithologies have been documented inside and outside the structure including breccias and impact melt (Masaitis, 2002). A documentation of a range of shock indicators in impact melt samples from drill holes can be found in, e.g., Whitehead et al. (2002) and Kettrup et al. (2003). The structure is partially covered by Neogene and Quaternary lacustrine, fluvial and fluvio-glacial gavels and sands locally reaching 200 m thickness (Masaitis et al., 2005). 

Elemental ratios such as Ru/Rh vs. Pt/Pd or Ru/Rh vs. Pd/Ir indicate the Popigai impactor is clearly an ordinary chondrite and most likely L-chondrite (Tagle and Claeys, 2005).
Impact diamonds have been documented and mined in Popigai impactites (Koeberl et al., 1997; Deutsch et al., 2000; Masaitis, 2002).

Age:
40Ar-39Ar step heating technique on impact melt yielded an age 35.7 ± 0.2 Myr (2σ) (Bottomley et al., 1997). Bottomley et al. (1997) summarized previous dating attempts: 
“The stratigraphic age of Popigai is between the end of the Cretaceous (~65 Myr) and the beginning of the Pliocene (~5 Myr). … previous attempts to date the Popigai impact have given age estimates that range from Late Cretaceous to Oligocene. Earlier whole-rock K–Ar age estimates include: 40– 45 Myr (mean 42.5 Myr, Firsov, 1970) for four tagamites and 29–46 Myr (mean 38.7 Myr, Komarov and Raykhlin, 1976) for five tagamites and one glass fragment from a suevite breccia. Fission track analyses of six glass fragments from suevite breccia yielded 32.4–44.0 Myr (mean 38.9Myr, Masaitis et al., 1975). An additional fission track analysis gave 30.5 ± 1.2 Myr (Storzer and Wagner, 1979). Deino et al. (1991) reported five total fusion 40Ar–39Ar ages ranging from 52.2 to 65.9 Myr on glass from suevite breccia, and plateau ages of 65.5 ± 5 Myr and 65.4 ± 0.3 Myr, that is, a Cretaceous/Tertiary (K/T) age. Most recently, Deino et al. (1995) failed to reproduce a K/T age from additional samples. They obtained a highly discordant 40Ar-39Ar spectrum from a fused gneiss fragment and an integrated age of 37.7 ± 0.3 Myr from four impact melt glasses, which they considered to be a maximum for the Popigai impact event. An age for Popigai of 39 ± 9 Myr, consistent with both the whole rock K–Ar and most of the fission track ages, has been generally quoted (Grieve, 1987).”

Roter Kamm is a simple, 2.5-km diameter crater located in southwestern Namibia. Cordinates are based on sample GPS data (Rajmon, 2003). Its impact origin has been established by a number of geological, petrological (Miller and Reimold, 1986; Reimold and Miller, 1989; Reimold et al., 1997) and geophysical (Fudali, 1973; Brandt et al., 1998) studies. Erosion has lowered the crater rim by 40-130 m and most of the ejecta, apart from a few patchy occurrences, have been stripped away (Grant et al., 1997). 40Ar/39Ar analysis of an impactite sample provided a plateau age for the impact event of 3.7 ± 0.3 (1σ) Ma (Hartung et al., 1991; Koeberl et al., 1993). More recent laser probe 40Ar/39Ar analysis of two other impact glass samples yielded a discordant step-heating age spectra and isochrone intercept ages of 5.06 ± 0.44 Ma (possibly affected by minor excess 40Ar) and 4.69 ± 0.31 Ma. The weighted mean of these ages is 4.81 ± 0.5 Ma (MSWD = 0.47) and could approximate the upper age limit of the impact event. Considering the high radiogenic Ar content in the new samples compared to low content in the samples that yielded 3.7 ± 0.3 Ma age the true age of Roter Kamm is likely around 4-5 Ma (Hecht et al., 2008).

The rocks exposed at the crater rim are gneisses and granites belonging to the Namaqualand Metamorphic Complex with a metamorphic age of 900-1,200 Ma (Reimold and Miller, 1989). At the time of impact, the Namaqualand gneisses were probably covered by a thin layer of late Proterozoic Gariep metasedimentary rocks, ~700 Ma. The geochemistry of the rocks at Rotter Kamm was described by Bishop et al. (1989), Koeberl et al. (1990) and Reimold et al. (1994). Platinum group elements in impact melt indicates small contamination with, most likely, non-carbonaceous chondrite (Hecht et al., 2008).

Breccia veins occurring in the Roter Kamm crater of SW Namibia were originally described as pseudotachylytes (Reimold and Miller, 1989). The breccias occur as numerous fine-grained dark-colored veins and dykes of submillimeter to meter widths. The larger veins appear to extend radially from the crater, whereas the fine veinlets may form networks without preferred orientation. The rocks show rare evidence for shock metamorphism. Planar deformation features (w and p in quartz), together indicating maximum shock pressures of 20 to about 35 GPa (Huffman and Reimold, 1996; French, 1998), were reported by Reimold and Miller (1989) and Degenhardt et al. (1994). Multiple sets of PDFs in quartz within suevite were also reported by Reimold et al. (1997). Shock features, reported from a single impact melt rock sample (Reimold and Miller, 1989), include diaplectic quartz (corresponding to 35-45 GPa according to compilation in French, 1998, or >27 GPa according to Huffman and Reimold, 1996) and vesicular glass (~45-50 GPa, French, 1998). Besides the dated impact melt rock, melt was reported only in the form of several fragments in suevite (Reimold et al., 1997). Degenhardt et al. (1994) found that the pseutotachylyte-like breccias contained irregular clasts of the host rock displaying a wide range of grain sizes from several millimeters to about 10 mm. They concluded that the breccias were formed by local comminution followed by recrystallization of mainly fine-grained material and that the heat generated during this process was insufficient to melt the rock. Degenhardt et al. (1996) reached similar conclusion for breccias from Rotter Kamm resembling melt bombs. Investigation of 40Ar/39Ar isotopic system of breccia veins and basement rocks from Roter Kamm crater revealed no influence of frictional heating on the veins and indicated that the highest temperatures both veins and basement rocks experienced as a result of the impact event were 230-290 ºC and were induced by shock heating (Rajmon et al., 1999; Rajmon et al., 2002; Rajmon, 2003; Rajmon et al., 2005). Koeberl et al. (1989) reported post-impact hydrothermal quartz from the crater. 
Demagnetization experiments (Rajmon, 2003; Rajmon et al., 2004) suggest that the major magnetic carriers in the vein breccias and basement rocks are magnetite and hematite. Essentially all isolated NRM components can be best related to the earlier tectono-metamorphic events. There is no evidence for re-magnetization of the Roter Kamm samples due to recent impact. The AMS experiment demonstrated that the formation of the vein breccias led to a decreased magnetic susceptibility, increased anisotropy of magnetic susceptibility and disruption of the regional AMS pattern.

Roter Kamm crater was also mentioned in several reviews and abstracts on radar imaging (Dietz, 1965, 1966; Grieve, 1993; Blumberg et al., 1995; McHone et al., 1995; Trenc et al., 1999).

Simple impact crater with a present day diameter ~3 km and depth to basement 400 m. Fractured granite basement is covered with up to 70 m of lithic breccias and suevites. Post-impact deposits include 120 m of sandstones, siltstones and oil shales with rare layers of sedimentary breccia of Aptian-Albian and marls and chalks of Cenomanian-Turonian age filling up the rest of the crater. 15-18 m of Boltysh ejecta lay on top of the Cen-Tur sediments within the Rotmistrovka crater. The Boltysh ejecta and whole crater is overlain by ~100 m of post-Turonian and Cenozoic clay, sand and loess. The target was exposed at the time of impact. Numerous shock effects documented in drill cores (Masaitis, 1999 and references within; Gurov et al., 2003 and references within). 

Grieve Robertson (1979) listed 70 Ma age for Rotmistrovka in their compilation without explanation. Masaitis at al. (1980) in Gurov et al. (1993) estimated the age of the crater at Late Jurassic-Early Cretaceous, which Grieve and Masaitis (1994) presented as 140 ± 20 Ma. Later compilations (e.g. Masaitis, 1999; EID, 2007) listed 120 ± 10 Ma age. Although the compilations do not explain the origin of their numerical age, the numbers apparently derive from the age of the earliest sediments in the crater and an assumption that the crater could not form much earlier before the earliest sediments deposited. Following this logic and a more recent stratigraphic calibration of Gradstein et al. (2006) this database uses the age is around the base of Aptian at 125 Ma and the uncertainty ± 20 Ma spans from near the top of Aptian to the base of Cretataceous. 

Coordinates lat/lon 49.192/31.750 read from a map in Gurov et al. (2003) and consulted on Google Earth, although Gurov et al. (2003) quoted 49.13/31.73 in the text.

Santa Fe structure is a remnant of an impact structure northeast of Santa Fe, New Mexico, USA. Tim McElvain (2006) was the first one to report the occurrence of possible shatter cones and anomalous megabreccia in the area, followed by McElvain et al. (2006), Fackelman et al. (2006; 2007). The detailed study of Fackelman (2008) confirmed that unusually large shatter cones (up to 2 m long and 0.5 m wide at the base) occur within Paleoproterozoic granitoids and supracrustal metamorphic rocks over an 5.5 km2 area. The study further described random fractures, fluid micro-inclusions, sericite replacement in feldspar, rare kink bands in mica, optical mosaicism, decorated planar fractures (PFs) and planar deformation features (PDFs) in quartz, and probable melt pockets within the surface layer of the shatter cones. The PFs and PDFs (shown on good quality photographs but no data histogram or SEM images presented) are dominated by a basal (0001) crystallographic orientation indicating a peak shock pressure of ~5–10 GPa that is consistent with shatter cone formation. 
Fackelman (2008) estimated that the Santa Fe structure formed after the ~1.2-0.9 Grenville orogeny, which metamorphosed the target rocks, and substantially before recent because the structure is strongly eroded, buried or tectonically dismembered. 
The breccia overlying the crystalline basement, is post-Proterozoic to pre-Pennsylvanian in age, and may be intercalated with Mississippian rocks. If it were related to the impact it would indicate that age (Fackelman et al., 2008). 
The 3 km diameter area with the shatter cones indicates original rim-rim diameter 6-13 km (Fackelman et al., 2008).

Observed fall of iron meteorite in the evening of 17th May 1990, 20 km west from Sterlitamak city, Russia (Petaev, 1992b). A 315 kg meteorite was recovered from ~12 meter below surface plus small pieces around (Petaev, 1992b). Main paper (Petaev, 1992a). Original mass >1500 kg and impact velocity 2-3 km/s (Petaev et al., 1991; Ivanov and Petaev, 1992). Diameter from (Ivanov and Petaev, 1992). The meteorite is iron IIIAB medium octahedrite (Meteoritical Bulletin Database). Coordinates from Google Earth.

Circular feature with limited outcropings first described as a volcanic colapse feature (Dunn, 1963). Guppy et al., (1971) suggested impact origin based on the presence of shatter cones, melt breccias, central uplift, shocked minerals and radially and concentrically faulted target rocks. 
Ferguson (1978) described granitic gneiss core 10 km in diameter surrounded by 5 km wide collar of upturned and overturned quartzite (in fact sandstone, see Spray et al. (1999)) and siltstone Proterozoic Roper group and  circular area with mildly deformed mid proterozoic strata 20-25 km in diameter. Described outcrops of breccia, commonly highly shocked, megabreccia, melt rock but no evidence presented (Ferguson et al., 1978). Shatter fracturing forms striated sets of cleavages more commonly than well developed shatter cones (Ferguson et al., 1978).  Morgan and Wandless (1983) investigated samples of various shocked lithologies and found significant enrichment in siderophile elements relative to country rocks. The data could not be reproduced by mixing of country rocks or by selective fractionation by shock melting. The samples appeared to contain ~3 wt.% of olivine-rich achondrite (Morgan and Wandless, 1983). Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1988; 1990) listed 26 km diameter. Shoemaker and Shoemaker (1996) described the results of their own mapping, mentioned occurence of suevites and concluded that the diameter of impact deformed beds was 40 or more km; they too did not present any data documenting shock evidence. Spray et al. (1999) summarized the main target lithologies of the McArthur sedimentary basin as faulted and gently folded, but not metamorphosed, quartzite-dominated shale–siltstone–sandstone sequences (locally carbonaceous) of the Mesoproterozoic Roper Group and underlying granitic gneiss. Spray et al. (1999) also described various breccias, poorly developped shatter cones and shocked material but did not present any data supporting their interpretation. Spray et al. (1999) argued that the crater diameter is ~26 km, based on observed rock deformation beyond 26 km diameter and considering the amount of central structural uplift. 
Age:
Stratigraphy constraints the age between post-Roper Group (<1370 Ma) and pre-Cretaceous (>145 Ma) (Spray et al., 1999). Initial attempt of step-heating Ar/Ar nalysis suggested ~470 Ma on the basis of the youngest Ar-release ages (Bottomley et al., 1990) but that interpretation was probably influenced by the (now rejected) belief that mid-Cambrian limestones were deformed by the impact (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1996). Analysis of impact melt samples yielded Ar/Ar isochron age 646 ± 42 Ma based on a number of laser ablation data points from two samples (Spray et al., 1999). The quoted uncertainty is an "error" multiplied by square root of MSWD (Spray et al., 1999); it is not clear, however, how the "error" was calculated. 
Mentioned in (Kelley, 2003), listed at numerous compilations as a confirmed impact structure with lat. 15º12'S, long. 133º35'E (e.g., Glikson, 1996; Glikson and Haines, 2005; EID, 2006). Coordinate refined on Google Earth.

Diameters: Transient crater  90-130 km, Final rim 130-180, Central uplift <-90 km, External rings 180 and 260 km, Outer limit of deformation ~260 km (Turtle et al., 2005).
Impact evidence: PDFs, shatter cones, impact melt (references in Turtle et al., 2005).
Target: Levack Gneiss of Superior province (Ames et al., 1998 and references within).
Conventional U-Pb data for hydrothermal titanites yielded 1848.4 +3.8/–1.8 Ma (Ames et al., 1998). U-Pb data for shocked zircons from the Onaping Formation yielded ~1850 Ma age and together with field data indicate that the Onaping Formation was emplaced at 1851–1847 Ma (Krogh et al., 1996 in Ames et al., 1998). Combining the two sources the Sudbury age is about 1847-1852 Ma.
PGE data from ejecta in DL-4B and DL-5 cores in Michigan indiate meteorite impactor as opposed to comet Pufahl et al. (2007).
Seismic data in (Wu et al., 1995).

Tookoonooka impact structure lies in the Eromanga Basin of SW Queensland, Australia. It was discovered on seismic data as a complex circular feature that truncates normal Eromanga stratigraphy. The structure has elevated core and is surrounded by concentric synclines and anticlines in the basement. The reflections inside the structure are heavily disturbed and chaotic. Strong regional reflector “C”, which marks regional transgression in the Eromanga Basin is missing or severely disrupted. Instead, the first strong and continuous seismic reflector (the Intra-Wallumbila) overlying the chaotic zone developed stratigraphically higher inside the structure over an area ~55 km in diameter. The Intra-Wallumbila horizon occurs 882 m below surface in Tookoonooka-1 well. Overlying reflectors are heavily faulted. The structure is concentric with a negative gravity anomaly (Gorter et al., 1989). The target includes pre- Jurassic basement made of chlorite mica schist, phyllitic schist, quartzite and early Jurassic to early Cretaceous sandstones, mudstones and shales. There is no evidence for igneous rocks or evaporites. Drilling encountered breccias, impact melt and shocked material with PDFs (Gorter et al., 1989; Gostin and Therriault, 1997). Surrounding wells encountered anomalous log responses indicating the presence of coarsening upward sediment package over an annular area between ~55 and ~130 km diameter, which could represent reworked material from elevated rims and central uplift. A network of predominantly concentric channel and faulted trough fills developed during this period out to a diameter of at least 100 km (Gorter et al., 1989; Young et al., 1989). The gravity anomaly suggests 30-150 km diameter of the structure (Gostin and Therriault, 1997). While Gostin and Therriault (1997) considered the above diameter constraints, they eventually favoured ~66 km diameter without an explanation. Recent 3D seismic data show concentric faulting within the zone with circular troughs. Following the terminology of Turttle et al (2005), the outer limit of structural disturbance thus appears to have a diameter of 100-150 km and the final rim diameter was 55-100 km. Palynological analyses and well correlations place the impact on the boundary of the palynological zones PK2.1 and PK2.2 of Price et al. (1985) in Gorter et al. (1989), which Gorter et al. (1989) correlated to the latest Barremian to early Aptian age and asigned it 128 Ma age. Calibrated to the 2004 International Stratigraphic Chart  (Gradstein et al., 2004), the base of PK2.1 is at 137Ma, base of PK2.2 at approx 133Ma and top of PK2.2 at 125Ma (Geof Wood, Santos Ltd., 2007, per.comm.). The age adopted in this database is thus 133 Ma with an uncertainty of 5 Ma (estimated based on the extend of the PK2.1 and PK2.2 zones and the difference between the original and the current calibration). The structure formed in a shallow sea. It formed positive morphological feature that remained elevated above sea level for another ~10 Ma and was exposed to erosion (Gorter et al., 1989).  Coordinates derived from a map in Gorter (1998) and IHSE well database. The development of the channel and trough fill in the crater and an indication of elevated rims indicates rather shallow target water depth that allowed the crater to remain essentially subarialy exposed for some period of time. The target water depth is thus loosely estimated at <200 m (D. Rajmon).

“Upheaval Dome is an unusual structural feature on the largely undeformed Colorado Plateau in Canyonlands National Park, southeastern Utah, USA. … Upheaval Dome consists of a deeply eroded sequence of faulted and uplifted rocks surrounded by a structurally depressed ring syncline , which also shows intricate faulting. Rocks exposed at Upheaval Dome are mainly sandstones and siltstones. The exposed strata consist of rocks of uppermost Permian age in the very center (White Rim Sandstone) to strata of Triassic (Moenkopi, Chinle Formation) and Jurassic age (Wingate Sandstone, Kayenta Formation, Navajo Sandstone) located at progressively increasing distances from the center (Kriens et al., 1999; Huntoon, 2000). Structurally, the feature exhibits an outer annular, inward-dipping monocline with a diameter of 5.2 km that defines the extent of the structure. Inside this monocline, there is a 3.6-km-diameter circular syncline surrounding a central uplifted area with a stratigraphic rise of ~250 m (Kenkmann et al., 2005). The inner part of the central uplift forms a morphological depression that is ~1.4 km wide and 300 m deep. The central depression plays a key role for the understanding of the structure of Upheaval Dome; it exposes radial folds and a complex sequence of folded and faulted strata. A characteristic imbrication of thrust slices, roughly toward the southeast, is preserved in the internal structure of the central uplifted area and has been interpreted as the result of an oblique impact from the northwest (Scherler et al., 2006).” - (Buchner and Kenkmann, 2008)  

“The very controversial debate about Upheaval Dome’s origin has lasted nearly a century, over the course of which extremely different hypotheses (gradualism versus catastrophism) have been proposed. Bucher (1936) postulated a crypto volcanic origin. Mattox (1968) favored the hypothesis that the central uplift and surrounding structural depression were the result of salt flow in the underlying Paradox Formation. An impact origin for Upheaval Dome was then proposed on the basis of faulting and the inward and upward motion of rocks that is typical for central uplifts of complex impact craters (Shoemaker and Herkenhoff, 1983). Jackson et al. (1998), however, interpreted these faults to record motion of rocks into a cavity left behind by the upward passage of a salt diapir, now eroded away. The explanation of Upheaval Dome as a remnant of a pinched-off salt dome has been questioned (e.g., Huntoon, 2000) due to the fact that there is no evidence that salt moved through the core of the structure. Additionally, no relict fragments of the Paradox or hanging-wall formations have been documented (Huntoon, 2000; Kenkmann et al., 2005), although these should be found within the throat of a salt passage. Seismic reflection studies by Kanbur et al. (2000) have shown that the Paradox salt layer underneath Upheaval Dome has a relief of <100 m and shows no evidence for a pinched-off salt diapir. Detailed mapping and structural analysis have been conducted in the last decade (Kriens et al., 1997, 1999; Huntoon, 2000; Scherler et al., 2003; Kenkmann, 2003; Kenkmann et al., 2005). The deformation inventory has been shown to be compatible with the formation and collapse of an impact crater, and a good match between the structurally gained data and results from a numerical simulation of impact crater formation has also been achieved (Kenkmann et al., 2005). … Kriens et al. (1997) described some shatter cone–like features in the center of the structure, but they did not fulfill the strict diagnostic criteria of shock-produced shatter cones (Kenkmann, 2003). Likewise, vesicle-rich nodules, interpreted as ballistic, once molten ejecta (Kriens et al., 1999), have been proven to be unrelated to the impact (Koeberl et al., 1999). Kriens et al. (1999) and Kenkmann and Scherler (2002) presented planar microstructures in quartz of the White Rim Sandstone. However, subsequent analysis on these rocks using transmission electron microscopy (Kenkmann, 2003) showed that they represent thin deformation bands (Boehm lamellae). Kenkmann (2003) and Okubo and Schultz (2007) inferred deformation mechanisms from microstructures in sandstones of Upheaval Dome and estimated stresses that are incompatible with lithostatic pressures for the region and that could have resulted from salt diapirism but that might also be consistent with attenuated shock waves caused by an impact.” - (Buchner and Kenkmann, 2008)  

Using optical microscopy, SEM and TEM, Buchner and Kenkmann  (2008) documented multiple sets of planar deformation features in quartz grains in sandstone samples from the Kayenta Formation at the NE flank of the central uplift.   

The Upheaval Dome could have formed during Jurassic shortly after the deposition of the Navajo sandstone (consistent with reported soft sediment deformation in Jurassic rocks directly overlying Navajo ss. 30-40 km NE of the structure) or as late as a few million years ago during the late stage of the Colorado plateau denudation. Reported middle Jurassic vertical cylindrical sandstone structures in south Utah have been interpreted as a result of liquefaction due to rapid overloading or seismic shock. The lack of deformation of the regional joint system is also consistent with Mesozoic impact (Kriens et al., 1999 and references within). The age of the Navajo sandstone is likely early Pliensbachian to late Toarcian (USGS, 2007), thus base of late Toarcian calibrated at 183 Ma (Gradstein et al., 2006) can be taken as the lower age limit of the Upheaval Dome.

Magnetic survey did not resolve any substantial meteorite mass in the floor of the crater. Small fragments of iron IIAB are scattered in breccia lining the crater floor (Shoemaker et al., 2005). Target: metamorphic, igneous, siliciclastic sediments and dolomites (Gibson and Reimold, 1999)
Erosion ~5-11 km.

Age: 2023 ± 4 Ma (2σ) U-Pb age on shocked zircons (Kamo et al., 1996).
Impact evidence: PDFs in quartz, shocked zircon, coesite, stishovite, shatter cones, melting… (Kamo et al., 1996; Turtle et al., 2005).

Two craters Philby A (64 m), and Philby B (116 m) discovered by J. Philby in 1932 and a third crater the 11-m discovered by J. Wynn in 1994 (Shoemaker and Wynn, 1997). The field work suggests existence of more craters.The craters are located in the north-central core of the Ar-Rub’ Al-Khali (Empty Quarter) desert region of Saudi Arabia. The impact site is known as ‘‘Al Hadida,’’ Arabic for ‘‘the iron’’ or ‘‘the iron thing(s).’’ (Prescott et al., 2004). The site contains fragments of iron IIIA meteorite medium octahedrite (See et al., 1990, Wynn and Shoemaker, 2004).  Documented shock features include white and black glasses with schlieren and metal spherules derived from projectile (Gibbons et al, 1976; See et al., 1988; Mittlefehldt et al., 1992), impact breccias (Shoemaker and Wynn, 1997) and coesite (Chao et al., 1961).

Age:
Fission track dating yielded an age 6400 ± 1900 (1σ) years (Storzer and Wagner, 1977). Luminescence dating of impactite and an underlying sand indicated an age 290 ± 38 years (Prescott et al., 2004). The confidence level of the uncertainty was not provided and is assumed here to be 2σ. Two Arabic poems that can be interpreted as a description of a meteorite fall from Tarim, Yemen indicate date 1 September 1704 (Basurah, 2003). The sand filling history during the 20th century also suggests a couple hundred years age. Wynn and Schoemaker (1998) proposed an age of 135 years based on recovery of the Nejd meteorites with composition identical to Wabar iron. These meteorites were recovered after a meteor observed in Riyadh in 1963 or 1891 (Wynn and Schoemaker, 1998). Prescott et al. (2004) discussed the report of 1863 impact and a meteorite put for sale in 1885 that had composition identical to Wabar iron. Prescott et al. (2004) wrote that the 1863 impact was said to have occured in Wadi Bani Khaled. They found such place in Oman and argued that it was too far from Wabar impact trajectory to represent the same impact.

A 36-m-diameter impact crater located in a forested area near the town of Whitecourt, Alberta, Canada. Identified in a digital elevation model based on airborne light detection and ranging (LiDAR) data. The target material is deglacial Quaternary sands and gravel. Impact ejecta buried a late Holocene soil dated to 1130 ± 25 and 1080 ± 25 14C years B.P., consistent with the crater being situated on a young geomorphologic feature - a surface sloping toward an ephemeral stream ~15 m away.  74 iron IIIAB meteorites (0.1-1196 g, <1-12.5 cm, total 5.4 kg) have been recovered in the area buried at depths <25 cm; most of them have an angular exterior morphology (Herd et al., 2008). 

The lower age limit appears to be defined by the uncertainty on the older 14C date 1155 years B.P. The upper limit is constrained by he age of the vegetation overgrowing the crater on the order of half a century and the weathering of the meteorites. The abrupt juxtaposition of the ejecta over the ~1.1 ka soil suggest that impact occurred close to that age. This also seems consistent with the appreciable weathering of the meteorites.

"The site (over an area of 200 x 200 m, centered on the crater) is protected by the Alberta Provincial Historic Resource Act, and any unauthorized excavation is punishable by a fine up to $50,000 and/or 1 year imprisonment. This is meant to deter meteorite hunters from digging at the site and thereby degrading the crater over time.  This does not preclude field trips to the site; it simply requires coordination with the Historic Resource
Directorate, and I can provide that contact information to any researchers that might be interested in a visit, and assist in coordination." (C.D.K. Herd, 2009 - pers. communication).

Simple crater 935 x 825 m (average 880 m) in diameter. Gravity data suggest an original crater depth of ~150 m with no large meteoritic mass preserved in the floor. Sediiment fill the crater to a current rim-to-floor depth of ~50 m. Magnetic data show two concentric anomalies correlating to the rim and to the base of the inner crater wall. The target includes gently dipping Devonian sandstones topped with Miocene 0.3-2.5 m thick laterites. Ejecta are preserved around the crater and include glass. "Shale balls" - a completely weathered meteoritic iron - is scattered arround the crater and welded on the laterite surface at some places. Crater filll consists of apparently holocene talus onlapped by eolian sand and playa deposit of sand cemented with gypsum and calcite in the center of the crater. The crater is surrounded by quaternary eolian sand and <1 m thick fluvial unit of reworked eolian sand (Shoemaker et al., 2005). Coordinates from Google Earth. 36Cl-10Be and 41Ca-36Cl systematics indicated ~300 ka meteorite terrestrial age (Shoemaker et al., 1990). 10Be-26Al dating od the crater walls yielded exposure age ~30 ka and indicated erosion rate 0.002 cm/year (Shoemaker et al., 1990). preferred the 30 ka age. (EID, 2006) gives <0.3 Ma age, I assume derived from the same source. Iron IIIB projectile (ref in Tagle and Hecht, 2006).
Early reports spelled the name "Wolf Creek".

A crater with a poorly defined present day diameter 3.5 km, buried under ~50 m of recent sediments. Discovered by a circular negative gravity anomaly and subsequent study of core samples. The target includes Archean granites, migmatites and gneisses. Central uplift may exist. The drill hole near the center encountered 58 m of recent Cenozoic sands and clays, and 150 m of sandy-argillaceous Paleogene lake deposits with redeposited shocked crystalline gravels and boulders. Below it is 120 m of polymict allogenic breccia with shocked minerals and melt. Further below is cataclased granite with shatter cones and shock features. The shock transformations attenuate by the bottom of the drillhole at 380 m depth (Masaitis, 1999 and references within).
Masaitis (1999) and (EID, 2009) quote 80 ± 20 Ma age without further explanation.
Coordinates lat/lon 48.888/32.803 read from a map in Gurov et al. (2003). Masaitis (1999) and (EID, 2009) lists lat/lon 48.07/32.75.

Gusev structure is a buried elliptic depression defined by a 2D seismic data, multiple boreholes and is associated with a negative gravity and resistivity anomaly but no magnetic anomaly. The expression of the structure on satellite and aerial images is ambiguous. The structure is located immediately outside the northern rim of the Kamensk structure. The target rocks consist of tectonically deformed Middle to Upper Carboniferous limestones. The structure is filled with authigenic (Carboniferous and Triassic rock fragments) and allogenic (Carboniferous, Triassic and Upper Cretaceous rock fagments) breccias.
The structure has a simple bowl shape, with a rim 4x2.5km in diameter elongated east-west (Movshovich and Milyanskiy, 1991 and references within). Shock indicators where found within and around the Kamensk structure (Movshovich and Milyanskiy, 1991 and references within) and the impact origin is thus assumed for Gusev too. Biostratigraphic work indicated the structure formed within a shallow sea of late Maastrichtian to early Danian (Movshovich et al., 1991) or ~62-68 Ma. Ar isotopic age of impact glass from a borehole within the Kamensk structure (Izett et al., 1994) recalculated using a more recent calibration (Jourdan et al., 2009) is 49.15 ± 0.27 Ma. Jourdan et al. (2009) preferred the biostratigraphic age for Gusev calibrated at ~62-66 Ma; apparently because, strictly speaking, the Ar isotopic age applies to Kamensk only. However, the biostratigraphic age is also based on Kamensk breccias and crater fill primarily and it is apparently incorrect. The Gusev and Kamensk structures are assumed contemporaneous because the existing data cannot resolve any temporal difference and an occurrence of two impacts so close in space and time appears an unlikely coincidence. Therefore the accepted age for Kamensk is a good estimate for Gusev. The uncertainty in this estimate is difficult to assess but ±10 % seems like a reasonable indication used also for other structures.
The structure center lat, lon 48.472, 40.549 was located on the Google Earth by comparison with Fig.1 in Movshovich and Milyansky (1991).

Simple structure in flat-lying Paleoproterozoic and Neoproterozoic sandstones in a swampy flood plain of the Liverpool river. It is marked by a ring of breccia rising up to 50 m above terrain (Guppy et al., 1971; Shoemaker et al., 2005). Present day (apparent) diameter of 1.6 km is defined by the contact of the allogenic breccia with the target rock. Erosion removed the original estimated 100-200 m high and ~2 km diameter rim (Shoemaker et al., 2005). Guppy et al. (1971) noted that the sandstone filling the structure is similar to the Cretaceous sandstone occuring widely in the area and suggested that the age of the structure was between Proterozoic and Cretaceous. Shoemaker et al. (2005) pointed out that the crater-fill units at Liverpool appear similar to the basal units of the Late Neoproterozoic Buckingham Bay Sandstone. This sandstone appears in outcrops ~2 km from the structure and directly overlies the target Neoproterozoic sandstones. Considering fairly good preservation of the structure, Shoemaker et al. (2005) prefferred Neoproterozoic age for the structure. EID (2009) listed 150 ± 70 Ma age without a reference. Guppy et al. (1971) reported quartz from the allogenic breccias with mosaicism and planar elements decorated with fluid inclusions but showed no data to support the shock origin and did not mention whether the orientation of the planar features was measured or any other description.  Although the overall geologic character strongly indicates impact origin, the shock evidence have not been documented in peer-reviewed literature and the structure is classified accordingly. Neoproterozoic age is calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2006). Aboriginal name for the structure is Yingundji (Shoemaker and Shoemaker, 1997).

A circular structure within Proterozoic flat and nearly horizontal siliciclastic sediments (shale to sand). It is defined by an area of intese rock deformation bounded by outer ring syncline with a diameter of ~5.5 km at the outer fold limb extension. Annular zone is gently folded and faulted. The central ~1.5 km wide zone is intensely faulted, has steeply dipping fractured strata uplifted 300-500 m. Joint and fracture surfaces within the central zone are undulating and striated with slightly divergent striae - different from slickensides but not quite shatter cones. These "shatter cleavag" surfaces were steeply dipping in a restored position. Rocks the central area show zones of intense microbrecciation and irregular and planar fractures in quartz (mostly single orientation, in some grains multiple intersecting sets close to crystallographic orientations of impact induced PFs). Some PFs show feathering. Annular magnetic anomaly roughly coincides with the outer syncline. Possible examples but no unequivocal PDFs found. Non-impact origin considered and rejected: anticline, carbonate sinkhole, salt tectonics, igneous. Lateral shortenning inside the structure and a lack of deformation outside implies outward deformation stress. The structure appears to be eroded below the crater floor. Up to 1 km of overburden including up to 150 m of volcanics was likelly part of the target. The youngest exposed target strata are either Mesoproterozoic (somewhat less than 1500 Ma) or Neoproterozoic (~820 Ma). The widespread softsediment deformation in Saddle Creek Formation in outcrops 70 and 200 km away suggest an impact at ~1490 Ma. The lack of extensive breccias or melt rocks, and of any evidence of fracturing in the closest outcrop of Antrim Plateau Volcanics, suggests a Proterozoic rather than
Phanerozoic impact. The original rim diameter was likely 5-10 km (Sweet et al., 2005).

 Age calibrater with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

Ilumetsa craters are circular depressions with elevated rims. Raukas et al. (2001) summarized previous work published almost entirely in Estonian or Russian. The early work during 1938-1979 (Aaloe, 1960, 1961, 1963, 1979) observed morphology and geology revealed through excavation. Numerous small magnetic anomalies were mapped around the craters but no iron meteorites were found. Pirrus (1995) analyzed the morphology of the depressions and the volume of assumed ejecta and concluded that they were consistent with impact origin.

The target rocks include Middle Devonian Givetian siltstones and sandstones and several meters of basal till of the last Weichselian glaciation (Raukas et al., 2001). 

The largest depression Põrguhaud (lat, lon 57.96003, 27.40297 – Plado, 2009, pers. comm.) has a rim diameter 75-80 m and is 12.5 m deep. Põrguhaud depression is partly filled with terrigenous and organic sediment and is occasionally filled with water. The bedrock is uplifted in the rim and diamicton has been locally pushed into the bedrocks at steep angles. Autochtonous breccia consisting of the target lithologies is at least 8 m thick (Raukas et al., 2001 and references within). Radargrams at the crater show numerous small dislocations under the elevated rim and termination of Devonian/Quaternary interface under the rim (Plado et al., 2000). Early biostratigraphic work dated the oldest filling sediments to 8-8.5 ka (Laasi in Raukas et al., 2001). Later palynological and 14C dating of the oldest filling sediments estimated the age of Põrguhaud at ~6 ± ~0.1 ka (Liiva et al., 1972; Liiva et al., 1979).

The smaller depression Sügavhaud (lat, lon 57.95381, 27.39992 – Plado, 2009, pers. comm.) is located 900 m south of Põrguhaud. Its rim diameter is ~50 m and the depth is 4.5 m. Elevated rim 1.5 m high is preserved in the east. Three other strongly degraded depressions have been mentioned in the literature but not studied in detail and not localized reliably: Kuradihaud – 24 m diameter, ~400 m west of  Põrguhaud; Tondihaud – 20 m diameter, 1.5 depth, ~1000 m west of Põrguhaud; 5th depression (Raukas et al., 2001). Approximate coordinates for Kuradihaud and Tondihaud derived from the information and maps (Aaloe, 1961, 1979) using Google Earth.

Raukas et al. (2000; 2001) analyzed sediments from a bog lake located ~6 km SW of the two largest depressions. They found Si-Ca glass spherules with admixture of Fe and Ni, which they assumed to be of impact origin and related to Illumetsa craters. They did not present any data on these spherules. Palynological analysis and 14C dating of the material surrounding the spherules indicates ~6.6 ka age, which the authors assumed to represent the age of the Ilumetsa depressions. The uncertainty derived from presented information appears to be ±~0.1 ka.

Raukas et al. (2001) accepted the conclusion of the previous work that the two of the five known depressions are of confirmed impact origin because of “the presence of circular rim and its composition, the presence of horizontal and vertical deformations and the approximate correspondence of the rim and depression volumes”. 

The classification in this database acknowledges the overall geologic support for impact origin but also the lack of definite shock, meteorite or chemical evidence clearly linked to the depressions.

Well preserved circular structure with central uplift, ring syncline and a series of concentric normal faults identified on 3D seismic on Brazilian Atlantic shelf (Santos Basin).  Gravity data inconsistent with volcanic interpretation of the structure (data not shown but discussed). Seismic does not indicate salt diapirism or volcanism. Seismic data cover the structure fully and indicate central structural uplift of ~2 km and a diameter of outer concentric faults ~20 km. No shock features reported. The structure is well preserved and overlain by ~4 km of sediments (Correia et al., 2005). Stratigraphic age calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004). One well (1-SPS-31) drilled into post-impact sediments did not reach the depth were impact rocks could be encountered (D.Rajmon). Another well is being planed by Petrobras (Petrobras geologist, 2006 - pers. comm. at AAPG annual meeting). 2D seismic sections in Santos basin show numerous volcanic deposits, which form either a seismic loop scale layers or distinct cones max hundreds of meters tall/wide. No other even remotely similar structure known within the basin. Various bathymetry maps show ~200 m present day water depth (D. Rajmon).

A circular structure with a number of ring grabens found on 3D seismic. Inner bowl-shaped crater has a rim-rim diameter of ~3 km and a depth of ~200 m and has a buried central peak 750 m in diameter and 250 m tall. The crater is surrounded by an area with a set of normal dipping concetric faults ~8 km in diameter and an outer zone of at least 10 ring grabens defining a total structure diameter of ~20 km (Stewart and Allen, 2002). The structure occurs within Cretaceous chalk and underlying Jurassic shale and is overlain by ~300 m of Tertiary sediments and 40 m of water. Stewart and Allen (2002) suggested that the extensive faulting surrounding the structure may be due to the weakness of the overpressured chalk. Based on seismostratigraphy and stratigraphic ties to nearby well, Stewart and Allen (2002) argued that the age of the structure is 60-65 Ma. The sedimentary facies from this time period indicate target water depth 50-300 m (Stewart and Allen, 2002). Origin by transtensional tectonics and salt evacuation suggested by (Smith, 2004). Seismic data in both. (Koeberl and Reimold, 2004) looked for shocked effects in drill bits and did not find any in thousands of studied quartz grains and hundreds of lithic granitic and feldspar particles. Collins et al. (2003) modeled the structure with an impact into 1 km thick upper brittle layer and lower mobile layer forming a transient cavity 1 km deep and 3 km in diameter. The results indicated that the mobile layer was probably a part of the Jurassic shale unit below the Cretaceous chalk. Underhill (2004) argued for origin via salt withdrawal and Stewart and Allen (2004) defended their impact hypothesis. Stewart and Allen (2005) presented a detailed 3D seismic study of the structure and argued that the structure is older the regional folding due to salt withdrawal. They also reconsidered their earlier age interpretation and constrained the Silverpit age at 45-74 Ma using the same method. Conway and Haszeldine (2005) mapped three seismic horizons in 7000 km2 around Silverpit, found three synclinal structures similar to Silverpit in a large scale but not in small scale features, concluded that Silverpit is a unique structure in the area. Self-Trail and Jutson (2005) described unusual fracturing of nannofossils from Silverpit and Chesapeake Bay structures that cut across normal disintegration surfaces. Based on the Silverpit story, Stewart (2003) elaborated further on the issue of impact structures identification in soft sediments.

Diameter:
The above summary indicates the transient crater diameter of 3 km. The presence of central peak and slumping and normal faulting suggest that Silverpit is a complex structure and its final rim diameter was 5-8 km.

Data from (Ormö et al., 2002), except coordinates from Google Earth. Bowl shaped subcircular depresion in soft lacustrine sediments with raised rim 115x140 m in diameter. Acompanied by a number of smaller pits, of which 17 pits with 1.5-20-m rim-to-rim diameters were mapped. The shape and structure is comparable to impact craters in unconsolidated targets. Soil horizon below rim interpreted as the target surface has a radiocarbon age 412 ±40 A.D. Several craters in the field show magnetic anomalies consistent with the presence of buried remanently magnetized objects. No shocked material found. Rusty Fe,Mn crust samples, some magnetic with sporadic Ni-rich spherules, found in rim but not in reference soil sample. Other hypotheses considered and rejected: volcanic maar - no volcanism in the area, periglacial activity - structure is much younger than the last glaciation, karsting does not form upraised rim with material older than underlying soil horizon, artificial construction - too large, very different from small dams on creeks used in the area (Ormö et al., 2002). Santilli et al. (2003) reported a historical legend apparently describing a meteorite impact of an energy comparable to the size of Sirente and occurring at about the same time. (Speranza et al., 2004) argued for the depresions being artificial ponds. Stoppa (2006) observed mud flows and lobes around Sirente crater and noted that a couple of limestone blocks inside the crater were not karstified. He also observed grading of soil in the crater rim. Combined with morphology and presence of active faults nearby, (Stoppa, 2006) proposed the crater to be a mud volcano. (Stoppa, 2006) also analyzed soils from the structure rim and saw no evidence for iron meteorite contamination. (Stoppa, 2006) also did not observe balistic ejecta and any evidence for mineral shattering in soils. These observations led (Stoppa, 2006) to reject the impact hypothesis. (Stoppa, 2006) also found Roman coin from mid 1st century AD on the rim and some pottery, which he used to argue for older age than 412 AD provided by (Ormö et al., 2002). The coin could, however, be placed on the rim any time after it was made and it has no relevance to the crater age (D. Rajmon). (Stoppa, 2006) argued against artificial origin because there is no evidence for digging operations and there are easier ways to water stock in the area. A couple more abstracts (Ormö et al., 2001; Ormö et al., 2003) basically contained in the main paper (Ormö et al., 2002). Numerical modeling of Lepinette and Ormö (2006) indicates that heat from small impacts will not generate glass but will fire target clays and these fired clays will remain in the crater. Further field mapping, excavation and sample analyses showed that there is at least 30 satellite craters around the main crater (Ormö et al., 2006). Two studied craters have a funnel shape with paleosol dragged downward and structural disturbance dissappearing in depth. Numerous samples of heated clay were recovered from the studied craters but not from reference samples. Charcoal and heated clay samples were dated with radiocarbon and thermoluminiscence methods and together constrained the age of the structures at 1689-1418 years before present at 2σ uncertainty range. Although chemical traces of the projectile were improbable to find, chemical analyses were attempted with equivocal results (Ormö et al., 2006). Ormö et al. (2006) rejected the "artificial pond" interpretation of Speranza et al. (2004) based on the remoteness from any known shepperd's trail, lack of any evidence for digging and artifacts. Ormö et al. (2006) rejected the "mud volcano" interpretation of Stoppa (2006) based on remoteness of any recent or past volcanic activity, problematic placement of the "lobe flow" material, which had to flow upslope, and incorrectness of some observations and logic. Ormö et al. (2006) explained that the mud flow may in fact represent fluidized ejecta and that the non-karsted limestone boulders in the main crater, used by Speranza et al. (2004) and Stoppa (2006) as an argument against impact interpretation, are in fact consistent with late-stage slow-velocity pull of material from depth during an impact. Ormö et al. (2007) aquired magnetic data over an area with 4 of the smaller craters (~8 m diameter) and along crossing profiles over 2 larger craters (~22 m diameter). All of the smaller craters are associated with up to 22 nT anomalies and the larger craters with up to 100 nT anomalies. Forward modeling based on an impact scenario with buried iron meteorites reproduced the measured data accurately. The models based on a karst scenario could not reproduce the data. Ori et al. (2007) aquired two high-resolution reflection seismic lines and one refraction seismic line over the main crater. The seismic data clearly show a rootless, bowl-shaped structure with upturned strata below the rim. Despite the lack of shock evidence (not expected for a crater of this size) and unequivocal geochemical evidence, the many various observations, arguments and comparison with other crater fields constitute a compeling evidence for Sirente's impact origin.

Data from review paper by (Vasilyev, 1998). The coordinates are for epicenter where shockwave first reached ground. Observed event early morning on 30 June 1908. Strong optical and sound effects, regionally felt air blast, earthquake, magnetic storm and other physical effects observed. ~2000 km2 of forest was devastated with dead trees standing upright within 3-5 km around the epicenter and fallen radially away from the epicenter further away. Thermal damage found on plants farther away. The damage pattern and event observations are best explained with high altitude (9-8 km) disintegration and vaporization of a cosmic projectile. No craters generated on ground, no projectile fragments found, silicate and magnetic microspherules with high Ni content found in soils of the Tunguska area, increased iridium content in peat, shifts in C, H and Pb isotopic composition in peat, increase in chalcophile and REE elements, which is consistent with the hypothesis though not proving it. A number of other explanations of the event proposed, currently two are prefered - cometary or stony meteorite impact (Vasilyev, 1998). For more references see review by (Vasilyev, 1998) and proceedings of a conference on Tuguska event (Di Martino et al., 1998). Some other papers (Marshall, 1966; Lerman et al., 1967; Crannell, 1974; Brown and Hughes, 1977; Jones, 1977; Chyba et al., 1993; Svetsov, 1996, Artemieva and Shuvalov, 2007). Ol'khovatov (2003, 2005, 2006) argues for terrestrial origin of the event - more on Andrei O'lkovatov's website www.geocities.com/olkhov. Recent modeling results, however, explain even features long used as an evidence against the impact origin - butterfly-shaped damage zone and standing trees in the epicenter (Artemieva and Shuvalov, 2007). Gasperini et al. (2007) presented seismic, sonar, geomorphologic and shallow drilling data indicating that the Lake Cheko (lat,lon 60.9647, 101.8589, diameter 350x500 m) may be an impact site of one of the projectile fragments.

A  circular depression with well-developed crater rim of 11 m rim-rim diameter in Quaternary cobble beds. Cobbles of the crater walls are partially to completely molten, indicating temperatures > 1500 °C (Roesler et al., 2006). The fused cobbles show signs of extreme temperature but no signs of shock metamorphism (F. Langenhorst (2004) and A. Wittmann (2005)). However, Ernstson et al. (2004-2006) claim PDFs at glazed cobbles from the same structure (crater 004). Geophysical measurements indicate that the structure continues to depths of several meters,  that high temperture generated strong magnetic remanences (new magnetic phases? iron silicides?) and that this extreme heat was confined to an area of ca. 20 m diameter. A pre-industrial age of the structure is clearly demonstrated by old rotting tree trunks inside the crater. At present there is no natural or primitive industrial process known which can explain the observed effects. 
The crater-like structure may be in context with numerous small scale crater-like depressions nearby described by Fehr et al. (2005) and is also listed as a possible impact structure of the postulated "Chiemgau impact strewn field" by Ernstson et al.(2004-2006).

A 2 km circular depression, poorly preserved, with visible rim to floor depth of ~250 m in the Large Zelenchuk river valley. A left lateral strike fault cut the structure and displaced the two halfs by ~0.5 km. The structure is associated with -3 to -4 mgal gravity anomaly. Target includes conglomerate, sandstone, slate, phyllite, and gabbro. Autigenous and allogenic breccias and breccia veins with planar elements in quartz (mainly m, ω, π) reported (Hryanina and Vityasev, 1999). Impact glass with high Ni content reported by Khrjanina (2003). Considering the young age of the Caucasus Mts. and the tectonic and erosional/depositional activity and assuming exogenic (impact or other) origin of the structure the age of the structure can be conservatively estimated as Quaternary and probably holocene (D. Rajmon).

Coordinates from (Jurena, 2003); diameter based on a fit to an off-centered gravity profile (Jurena et al., 2003); age from Wilson and Wilson (1979) and calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004); drilling data from (LeVie, 1985). Bee Bluff is an exposed structure located in south Texas near the town Uvalde in Zavala County.  It was first described by Wilson and Wilson (1979). They observed deformed Eocene clastic sedimentary rocks in a sub-circular area 4 km in diameter but quoted 2.4 km diameter for preserved “primary impact area”. The area has thrust faults and blocks of folded and displaced blocks of rocks, some possibly overturned, and possible ejecta. A well was drilled in the center of the structure to a total depth of 356 m to test a strong gravity maximum. The well encountered a stratigraphic sequence, which was the same as the sequence drilled east of the structure but it was uplifted by 74 m. Based on stratigraphic considerations, Wilson and Wilson (1979) estimated that the structure was post-Eocene to pre-Pleistocene, most probably Oligocene to Miocene, and that it was substantially eroded. Apparently shallow character of the structure was attributed to the impact occurring in soft, water-saturated sediments. No melt was found. King et al. (1979) further speculated that the structure may be the source of the North American tektites. Single quartz grain with PDFs from the structure was mentioned by Robertson (1980). Sharpton and Nielsen (1988) found quartz grains with multiple sets of PDFs both inside, 15 km and 135 km away from the structure. The structure appeared inconsistent to them with then known impact structures and they concluded that the shocked quartz might have been re-deposited. Breyer (1996) studied two impact-related thrust faults described by Wilson and Wilson (1979) and reinterpreted them as an unconformity at a base of an incised valley and as a normal fault. Breyer (1996) found no evidence for impact. Jurena et al. (2001; 2003) reviewed the occurrence of PFs and PDFs within and outside of the structure and found that 10 % of the quartz grains within the structure contain PDFs with orientations typical for soft sedimentary targets. Those grains occur in various formations and tend to have sharp edges. Outside the structure, ~3 % grains display PDFs with orientations typical for crystalline targets and the grains tend to be rounded. Thus the grains inside the structure appear in-situ, whereas the grains outside the structure appear redeposited from other impact structure (Jurena et al., 2001, 2003). Jurena et al. (2003) also reported a gravity profile across the structure with a central high surrounded by troughs. The shape of the profile is consistent with 6.75-km impact structure. The magnitude of the gravity anomalies is less then would be expected but this may be a result of advanced erosion. 
Listed by (Grieve and Shoemaker, 1994) as a confirmed structure. Listed in (Hodge, 1994). (Fortes, 2000) listed 40 Ma referring to (Sharpton and Nielsen, 1988); (Sharpton and Nielsen, 1988), however, did not provide any age. Other ref. (Donofrio, 1997).

A circular structurally disturbed feature within flat lying strata of Michigan Basin buried under ~250 m of sediment. Well logs and seismic data define central dome ~4 km in diameter , with some strata anomalously thickened or missing and uplifted 415 m relative to the surrounding stratigraphy. The uplifted rocks are intensely faulted with steep faults near the top and with fault number and dip decreasing downward. The dome is surrounded by an annular trough and an outer anticlinal arc in the NW and SW quadrants. The top of this anticlinal feature defines 6-8 km diameter. Thin sections display a microbreccia of fractured and unfractured quartz grains in a carbonate matrix. The same microbreccia was identified in several different stratigraphic units. No volcanics were identified in thin sections and noindication of intrusive magmatic bodies was identified in seismic data. The structural characteristics of the feature are consistent with those of known impact structures. The middle and early Cincinnatian rocks are deformed in the rim and missing in the structure. The upper Cincinnatian are present inside and outside the structure and early Silurian strata appear structurally undisturbed although of uneven thickness, perhaps related to underlying morphology. The Cincinnatian corresponds to the Upper Ordovician (Milstein, 1988c). The structure thus appears to have formed in the middle of the Late Ordovician. Milstein (1988c) did not discuss the lithology of the target in detail except he mentioned a limestone unit and a sandstone unit and only mentioned sedimentary rocks in the target. 

Milstein (1994) reported metalic microspherules and PDFs from the structure.
Milstein (1997) modeled 0.7 mgal gravity anomaly with a model of impact structure.

The structural uplift beneath the Calvin 28 oil field was earlier documented by DeHaas (1983) in Milstein (1988c), who suggested cryptoexplosive origin. The geophysical study by Ghatge (1984) in Milstein (1988c) found no gravity or magnetic anomally of at least 1 mGal and gamma and favoured impact origin but conservativelly concluded cryptoexplosive origin. Mata and Myles (1985) in Milstein (1988c) interpretted the structure as a result of tectonic compression.

Coordinates are for the well located in the center of the structure (Milstein, 1997) and come from (IHSE, 2005). Late Ordovician age calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). The diameters quoted here were measured on the structural map in Milstein (1988c) and differ slightly from the unrealistically precise numbers given by Milstein (1988c).

Ca-Al rich glass scattered around tens of km. The composition of the glass is unlike any known volcanic glass and there are no volcanic features in the area. On the other hand Ca-rich glass has been reported from Chicxulub. Lechatelierite present. Fractured quartz grains found in Pleistocene lacustrine sediments but not in pre-Pleistocene rocks. The melt contains pyrrhotite and microcrystalline calcite spherules. The glass appears to be proximal impact ejecta but could also be a result of airbursts. Composition of the glass suggest that the impact target included sandstones, shales, dolomites, phosphates and halites. 40Ar/39Ar suggest age 100-200 ka, supported by stratigraphic and archeological constraints (Haldemann et al., 2005a; Osinski et al., 2007). Structural elements preserved at Dakhleh Bow Wave Structure ~400 m diameter suggests this may be the source impact structure but several other structures in the area may be impact structures too (Haldemann et al., 2005b).

Data and following summary from Haines (2005): "Darwin Crater is a rimless circular depression *1.2 km in diameter situated in Silurian low-grade metasediments of the Eldon Group in a mountainous and heavily forested region of western Tasmania. The crater was first identified by Ford (1972) after a search for the source of Darwin glass, a confirmed impact glass distributed over 4400 km2 of western Tasmania (Fudali & Ford 1979; Howard 2004; Howard & Haines 2003, 2004; see further discussion below). Gravity modelling suggests that the depression has a bowl-shaped basement topography, filled by a lens of lower density materials up to 230 m thick (Fudali & Ford 1979; Richardson 1991). Drilling has revealed up to 60 m of lacustrine sediments of mid-Pleistocene and younger age overlying matrixsupported polymict breccias containing rare Darwin glass fragments (Howard 2004; Howard & Haines 2004). The infilling deposits contain fractured and otherwise deformed mineral grains and rock fragments, but no definitive evidence of shock metamorphism (Howard & Haines 2004), which is not unusual for small craters in sedimentary targets. Despite this lack of definitive evidence, an impact origin for Darwin Crater is supported by a general trend of increasing size and abundance of glass fragment towards the crater (Fudali & Ford 1979; Howard & Haines 2003, 2004), although sampling in the vicinity of the crater is strictly limited to the few access tracks in the area. Geochemical and isotopic studies show a close affinity between the glass, the stratigraphic units that host the crater, and crater- fill breccia (Howard 2004; Howard & Haines 2004). However, the huge estimated volume of Darwin glass and its wide dispersal (discussed below under Darwin glass) appears highly excessive for a small simple crater. Howard (2004) and Howard and Haines (2003) argued that a solution to this dilemma may lie in the poorly understood effect of a volatile-rich (water-saturated) target. Assuming a genetic connection, the age of Darwin Crater is given by the 816 ± 7 ka 40Ar/39Ar age ascribed to Darwin glass (Lo et al. 2002)."  Glikson (1996) quoted age 0.74 ± 0.04 Ma.

Data from (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999). 30km long, northwards slightly concave formation consisting of suit of breccias, melt, pseudotachylites and sediments interpreted as impact in origin (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999). Circle around the preserved part of the structure has a diameter 80 km (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999). The age of the impact event might correspond to the U-Pb zircon age of about 1.80 Ga, which is the indicated age of the lithophysae-rich vitreous melt inbetween the breccia and the polymict conglomerate (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999 and references within). Listed by (Henkel and Pesonen, 1992) as occurrence of breccia (class F), with lat/lon 65.5/17.1. Longitude read from map in (Abels et al., 2002) is 16.9. Listed by (Moilanen, 2004) with coordinates 65.58/17.17 diameter 80 km and age 1800 with no referrence provided but appears to be based on (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999). Both sulphide mineralization in the brecciated granite and uranium mineralizations in the melt can be related to the possible impact event, probably formed by post-impact hydrothermal activity (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999). More references in (Abels et al., 2002) and (Lilljequist and Reimold, 1999).

Several abstracts describe a multiring impact structure ~200 km north of Beijing, China. These papers recognize inner structural ring 70 km in diameter marking occurrences of various breccias, middle ring 120 km in diameter and an outer ring 190 km in diameter. A range of various impact breccias and megabreccias, suevites, impact melt sheets with mineral fragments and microlites, aerodynamically shaped melt bombs with schlieren and fluidized ejecta have been reported but almost no data were presented to support these claims (Siben, 1987; Siben and Shuyuan, 1987; Wu and Zhang, 1987; Siben, 1989; Wu, 1989; Wu, 1990; Wu and Zhang, 1992). The target consists of granodiorite, shale siltstone, sandstone, limestone, and andesite; the andesites are of the Upper Jurasic age. Coal deposits found via drilling in the western peripheral trough (>600 m deep) is lower Cretaceous. K-Ar age of the interpreted impact melt is 129 ± 2 Ma (Siben, 1987). All data in the database are taken from (Siben, 1987). The significance of the K/Ar age is uncertain considering the lack of data on the structure. Also, if the melt sample is indeed from impact and contains fragments of minerals the K-Ar is almost certainly inaccurate. The uncertainty range listed in the database is therefore taken from the stratigraphic constraints (D. Rajmon). The base Upper Jurassic and top lower Cretaceous are calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004).

Schmieder and Buchner (2006) reported a nearly circular Faya basin with a raised rim ~2 km in diameter, central topographic high and concetric faults discovered on Landsat and Shuttle Radar Topographic Mission (SRTM) data. It formed in sandstones of most likely Late Devonian age (Schmieder and Buchner, 2006). "No volcanic features are known in this area. Eroded magmatic intrusions and volcanic calderas should usually be different in size and shape, and should show an inhomogenic rock distribution on satellite images. Further, no salt diapirs, sinkhole structures, or glacial erosion features have been reported in this region" - Schmieder and Buchner (2006). All data from Schmieder and Buchner (2006), lower age limit chosen at Mid/Late Devonian boundary and calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004), coordinates precision improved using Google Earth. Inspection of Landsat images on Google Earth also revealed that the crest to crest diameter of the raised rim is ~1.5 km and the ~2 km diameter marks the extend of the rim outer slope and the concetric faults beyond the rim (D. Rajmon).

Data from (Korpikiewicz, 1980a), except published coordinates lat54.33/lon19.68 have been corrected based on a map in (Korpikiewicz, 1980a) and Google Earth. A N-S elongated eliptic depression with a raised rim. The northern rim partly obliterated due to agricultural activity, southern edge affected by a gravel pit. Glacial origin of the structure morphology considered but the antropogenic modification prefered. Center filled with a swampy pond. Two chunks of iron reported in 1937-39 (supposedly meteorites) but later lost. Magnetic spherules distributed in soil around the crater interpreted as the iron impactor material. Their concentration exceeds the background values up to 5x (Korpikiewicz, 1980a). The above observations suggest post glacial age (D.Rajmon), Holocene age calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004). (Korpikiewicz, 1980b) is a shorter version of the Meteoritics paper (Korpikiewicz, 1980a). (Korpikiewicz, 1980c) describes concentrations of magnetic spherules in soil from several locations in Poland. Listed by (Moilanen, 2004) as verified structure.

Proposed impact origin by (Iasky and Glikson, 2005) based on major geophysical and morphometric signatures characteristic of impact deformation, and its remarkable similarities with the proven Woodleigh impact structure - circular Bouguer anomaly cutting accross pre-existing features, a 24-28 km diameter central structurally uplifted area comprising a buried dome with a central uplifted plug (from seismic data), no significant magnetic anomaly. Volcanic and salt tectonic origin considered and rejected. Morphometric parameters correspond to known impact structures. Outer rim of gravity low is ~75 km in diameter consistent with 74-83 km diameter derived from scaling relative to central structural uplift. Age stratigraphically constrained between Tastubian to Asselian (Early Permian) and Early Cretaceous Winning Group -(Iasky and Glikson, 2005). Age calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

A circular structure consisting of the central Teniz Basin surrounded by North Kazakhstan Arch in the northern half-space and Sarysu-Teniz Arch in the southern half-space. The circular character is accentuated by concentric and radial fault pattern (geological map presented). The Teniz basin is filled with Permo-carboniferrous sediments and is associated with a pronounced negative gravity and magnetic anomaly.The granitic-metamorphic crust is 12km thick under the Teniz basin whereas it is 24 km thick at the eastern and western rims. This has traditionally been explained with uplift and erosion in Proterozoic to Mid Devonian followed by subsidence. The deep seismic sounding, however does not reveal deap roots that should have formed in such a scenario. Termitau-Kuybyshev deep seismic sounding profile shows Moho and Konrad's discontinuities risen closer to the surface under the basin. This Moho buldge is about 200 km in diameter and reaches closest to the surface in the center of the basin (no data shown). Shattered rocks are widespread (Zeylik and Seytmuratova, 1974). Zeylik and Seytmuratova (1974) reported well preserved bodies of allochtonous breccia composed of 1-1.5 m blocks of Ordovician sedimentary rocks and matrix of the same finelly shattered rocks at a location 15 km east of the town of Pervomayka (lat,lon cca 51.53, 70.73, no picture presented). Zeylik and Seytmuratova (1974) also reported shattercones in Proterozoic microquartzite east of the village of Novocherkasskoe (no picture presented). They also observed plannar features in quartz in rock samples collected from the central Teniz Basin over a distance of 100 km. The samples were collected away from any contact with Silurian and later magmatic rocks. One photomicrograph presented in the paper shows two sets of planar and parallel features with 10-20 µm spacing. No orientation measurements were presented. Zeylik and Seytmuratova (1974) also presented a photomicrograph of partly isotropized quartz. Zeylik and Seytmuratova (1974) concluded that the Ishim structure was of impact origin and that the impact crater itself was only the central part of the structure surrounded by 150-200 km wide zone of arcuate faults. Referring to other geological work, Zeylik and Seytmuratova (1974) estimated that the structure formed at the end of the Ordovician or at the beginning of the Silurian. Age roughly calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). Zeylik and Seytmuratova (1974) noted  that the numerous igneous intrusions and ore mineralization is associated with the faults (and their intersections) defining the structure and suggested that the mineralization was predetermined by the impact structure.

Data from Talwani et al. (2003). Gravity and aeromagnetic data for northeastern South Carolina revealed coincident circular anomalies near Johnsonville. These ~11 km diameter circular lows meet the geophysical criteria for those associated with buried complex impact craters. Within the magnetic low is a northwest-southeast structure enclosed by two concentric "moat-like" lows to its northeast and southwest. The pattern of surface streams passing above the structure is also consistent with the interpretation of a buried impact crater. Fortuitously, a drill core was available from a borehole drilled within these lows. The core includes ~10 m of Paleozoic crystalline Piedmont basement. Petrographic analysis of basement samples from the core revealed indications of shock metamorphic textures, including ballen texture in quartz, and transformation of some feldspar grains to diaplectic glass, supporting the interpretation of the existence of a buried impact crater. Stratigraphic observations from the drilled well indicate 88-200 Ma age of the structure (Talwani et al., 2003).
