Intermontane depression with a circular overprint 21-22 km in diameter across contour line 2200 m. Central uplift reaches 1784 m. The bedrocks comprise a mixture of various igneous, metamorphic and carbonate and siliciclastic sedimentary rocks. The basin is filled with several hundred meters of loose sediments. The evidence for impact includes shock slickensides, deformation lamellae, PFs, PDFs with multiple orientations. The presence of Pre-Jurassic (?) weathering crust products in the target and the Oligocene and Neogene sediment fill suggests Jurassic to Eocene age of the structure  (Vishnevsky, 2007).

A circular depression noted on satellite images, with a steep eastern rim, subdued western rim and possible second crater partly overlapping the western rim of the structure. Hummocky deposits on the flanks of the crater rim contain finely laminated marly rocks with carbonate accretionary lapilli, carbonate spherules, fragments of altered impact melt breccias, shock-deformed minerals including quartz, plagioclase, and ilmenite, exquisite particles of lechatelierite. 1 milligal negative gravity anomaly is centered on, and has similar dimensions as, the crater. The target was a thick loess and loessoid sediments (Harris et al., 2007). The crater occurs near outcrops with impact glasses dated at 230 and 445 ka and Harris et al. (2007) associated the crater with the 445 ka event.

“Stratigraphically, the crater appears to be late to mid-Pleistocene. Unfortunately there are two mid-Pleistocene impact glass deposits that are found in proximity (~40-50 km) to the structure. So without a date yet from any materials at the crater, I can't say with absolute certainty that the crater is connected to the 445 (+/- 21 2σ) ka glasses or the 230 (+/- 40 2σ) ka glasses (Schultz et al., 2004, Ar/Ar stepheating) or neither. However, the compositions of the glasses both in terms of melt chemistry and unmelted clast assemblages are fairly distinct. The 445 ka glasses contain primary hydrous melts, vertebrate fragments, and a conspicuous population of highly fractured, rounded, water-rich quartz grains (Schultz et al., 2004; Harris et al., 2005; Harris and Schultz, 2006). It would make a lot of sense if these glasses were formed by the La Dulce event, which appears to have excavated a large, active river.  The 445 ka glasses are also found more or less right at the mouth of the same river that was diverted by the event and which subsequently seems to have eroded the northern rim and NE ejecta. There's also a sequence stratigraphic argument for why we expected to find the source of the 445 ka glasses more inland and above the last major highstand, whereas we believe the source of the 230 ka event is closer to or off the modern shoreline. The 445 ka glasses are actually found stratigraphically higher than the 230 ka glasses suggesting that rivers transported the older glasses to their current position from higher elevations during development of the last large Pleistocene HST. That's why you'll see in our papers and abstracts that we refer to the older glasses as "upper" Centinela del Mar (UCdM) and the younger glasses as "lower" Centinela del Mar (LCdM). All that combined is why, for now, 445 ka is our best guess.” – (R.S. Harris, 2007, pers. comm.)

"Geophysical measurements near a 79 meter deep borehole show that a crater, about 800 meters in diameter and over 80 meters deep, formed in the Lockport Dolomite (Silurian) prior to Wisconsinan glaciation. Drilling logs and cuttings indicate that till about 10 meters thick covers a carbonate-rich sediment very different from the surrounding Paleozoic strata. Electrical resistivity soundings and seismic refraction profiles show that the walls of this structure are steep. Anomalous gravity extends about 300 meters outside the crater rim, evidence of deformation similar to that observed near impact craters of like dimensions. Cuttings from a borehole drilled into the rim provide direct evidence that rim rocks were upturned, elevating them 45 to 65 meters above their expected stratigraphic location. The search for a valley or gorge associated with this feature found nothing. We think this crater, slightly smaller than Barringer crater, Arizona, is the result of a meteorite impact" (Stierman and Trytten, 1999-2006). Karst and volcanic origin considered and rejected (Stierman and Trytten, 1999-2006). Stierman and Trytten (1999-2006) propose Quaternary age although they presented no specific constraints on the lower age limit. Location determined combining the information in Stierman and Trytten (1999-2006) and Google Earth. More data and updates available at http://www.eeescience.utoledo.edu/Faculty/Stierman/RES/LibC/ix.htm.

A zone of breccias up to 3 km wide in the Upper Proterozoic folded meta-sediments prompted S. Vrána to revaluate the area with impact process in mind. The boundaries of the pre-Tertiary units tend to be oriented tangentially to the center of the circular structure, the fault pattern is dominated by a set of tagential faults located ~30 km away from the swamp. Some radial faults are also present (Vrána, 1985). Target rocks include granite gneiss, migmatite, schist, quartzite, limestone, dolomite, phyllite, and meta-sandstone. Vrána (1985) described 1-3 sets of decorated and non-decorated plannar elements in quartz from the breccia zone crystallographically oriented in the direction of PDFs and with the width and spacing consistent with PDFs. Some quartz grains display a mosaic extinction. The samples contain abundant hydrothermal quartz overgrowth. Vrána (1985) also described a fine grained (1-5 μm) quartz aggregate sample with a flow texture and interpreted it as a devitrified silica glass. The structure is associated with a subdued aeromagnetic anomaly intercepting magnetic anomalies outside the structure. An inner crater rim 52 km in diameter was tentativelly interpreted to include the breccias and an outer rim 110 km in diameter coincides with the tangetial faults. A circular plan is expressed by the distribution pattern of the permanent lakes. A northwest tillting of the whole crustal block is the only visible post-impact event. The structure is associated with weathering and alteration not present outside the structure. The age of the structure is constrained by the youngest Pan-African metamorphism at 500-450 Ma and Upper Cretaceous erosional surfaces in Central Zambia. The Upper Carboniferous and Jurassic of the Karoo system in downfaulted blocks further away from the structure seem to be free of impact ejecta. The terrigenous coarse, poorly sorted clastics of the Luiry Hill formation confined to the southwestern sector 12 km to 80 km from the swamp correspond to the to the folded and metamorphosed rocks of the target and are unknown elswehere in the country. Some clasts resemble devitrified felsic melt rocks. If the deposition of this formation was triggered by the impact the age of the structure can be bracketed by 500 and 300 Ma (Vrána, 1985). All data from Vrána (1985).

Proposed by Bodoky et al. (2006; 2008) based on round shaped ~6x8 km high amplitude telluric conductivity anomaly, low seismic velocity zone in the basement, 100 m deepening of high resistivity basement in deep electric sounding data, negative Bouguer anomaly and a structure with central uplift on seismic reflection profiles crossing the center of the telluric anomaly. The structure is placed in Paleozoic metamorphic basement (micaschist, phyllite, gneiss and marble) and Upper Carboniferous siliciclastic coal bearing sediments. Lower Permian is preserved SE of the structure. 1100 m of Neogene sediments overlay the structure (Bodoky et al., 2008). 
Bodoky et al. (2008) accepted previous interpretation of the telluric anomaly as being due to graphitization of the coal and they linked the graphitization with the crater formation. There is little information available on the nature and distribution of this graphitized coal with respect to the structure in the paper, however.
The presented information suggests post Carboniferous and pre Neogene age of the structure; 23-299 Ma calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). Several wells drilled near the eastern rim of the structure (Bodoky et al., 2008). Several figures shown in Mikheeva (2006). Coordinates from Bodoky (2006 - pers. comm.).

“A round depression 1.5 km across and entirely contained in Quaternary loess truncates both hillocks and hollows of an irregularly linear terrain formed during the final episode of upbuilding of a loess plateau. The flat floor of the hole, 20 m below a discontinuous rim that rises 3-6 m above a surrounding plateau, is a depositional surface topping about 10 m of black alluvial sediment (reworked loess) produced by intermittent centripetal gullies that end in the depression.” (Dort and Dreschhoff, 2002). The amount of sediment transported from the gullies into the depression suggest a minimum structure depth of 50 m (Dort et al., 1997). The target includes 300 m of loose clay, silt, sand, and fine gravel before reaching consolidated strata (Dort and Dreschhoff, 2002). Samples collected in and around the depression yielded 1) magnetic spherules made of Fe oxides or Fe+Ti oxides with traces of other elements, 2) glass plates pockmarked with micrometer sized pits, 3) rounded glass fragments with magnetic spherule inclusions, and 4) mm-sized aggregates of the above material. The geomorphology of the surrounding area suggest that it developed during the last ~3000 years. Radiocarbon age of 2,860 ±  50 years before present was obtained for paleosol directly overlain by a white horizon rich in glass fragments. Volcanic, glacial, solution, eolian and water piping origins where considered and rejected (Dort et al., 1997; Dort and Dreschhoff, 2002).
Povenmire (1995) mentions at least 12 smaller depressions up to 550 m in diameter within several km of the main depression and an H4 chondrite found in the proximity.

2 km wide and 350 m deep circular depression in the sub-Cambrian peneplain consisting of heterogeneous gneisses. Outside the crater, the peneplain surface is covered by less than 1 m thick sandstone bed, graphite rich phyllites and shales. The equivalent marine shales within the crater carry a Middle Cambrian fauna. These shales and overlying shallow marine sandstones were overridden by overthrust nappes of the frontal Caledonian thrusts. "Within the crater, the crushed basement rocks are covered by sedimentary, post-impact breccias with fragments reaching up to 2-3 m. In the deeper part of the crater depression, the sedimentary breccia is intercalated with crossbedded sandstones, deposited in water. The succeeding coarse-grained sedimentary fill forms wedges of variable thickness along the margin of the crater. The maximum stratigraphic thickness observed is almost 200 m along the rim of the crater. Following an ?early Cambrian marine transgression the crater was dominated by fine-grained sedimentation, to day seen as shales onlapping the crater walls. The level of erosion in the central part of the crater does not reach the basement, and about one third of the interior is covered by Cambrian shales and sandstones and overlying thrust nappes. The basement gneisses exposed along the crater walls are intensely fractured and brecciated, commonly with a characteristic dark grey to black fracture fill. The quartz and feldspar grains typically have dark grey to black colour and individual quartz grains commonly display a mosaic fracture pattern and strongly undulating extinction. ...samples taken in a small area of exposed basement rocks in the crater interior revealed outcrops of a fine-grained rock with suevitic texture containing quartz grains with good planar structures of two directions."(Riis et al., 2008).
Middle Cambrian fauna within the shales filling the crater defines Middle Cambrian or earlier age of the crater. Middle/Late Cambrian boundary calibrated at 501 Ma [Gradstein, 2006 #3027].

Semicircular northern shore of otherwise irregular lake partly outlines  a circular region 3.2 km in diameter, where water depths average 50 m. Breccias occur in outcrops of Precambrian rocks, no shock features, petrographic characteristics as expected at a low-shock rim position. Ordovician limestone float recovered from southern shore does not occurr in outcrops within ~65 km of the lake and may represent a portion of the Paleozoic sedimentary cover preserved in the crater. "The Tsenkher structure, in the Gobi-Altai region of Mongolia, was studied using a wide array of remote sensing data and field observations. The structure has a shallow, 3.6 km wide, central depression bordered by a near-circular ridge (putative crater rim) with breaches to the northwest. The central depression is obliterated partially by fluvial infill through these breaches. Outside the ridge, the western side is a rugged terrain, but the eastern half is characterized by a concentric outer ridge that occurs at about one radius distance from the inner ridge. Although intrusion, salt tectonics and maar crater hypotheses cannot be completely ruled out, its morphology strongly implies an impact origin for the Tsenkher structure. If of impact origin, it has a well-preserved morphology and its position in the basin fills indicates that the formation may have occurred relatively recently, sometime during the late Tertiary or Quaternary. The outer ridge morphology is similar to rampart craters on Mars, whose formation has been attributed to fluidization of a water-rich target layer and ejecta materials, or to atmospheric entrainment and deposition of ejected materials. However, other hypotheses including erosional remnant of ejecta blanket, erosional scarp of structural rim uplift, multi-ring or deeply eroded crater rim of a peak-ring crater are also possible at this stage. A complex fluvial and probable lacustrine history is envisaged within the Tsenkher structure. The structure is also associated with archaeology, including Paleolithic and Bronze Age remains." - Komatsu et al. (2006)

Data (except upper age limit) from (Rappenglück et al., 2005), coordinates read from map in Fig. 2, diameter is estimated original rim-rim. At least 81 craters 3-500 m in diameter with raised rims, found sand stone cobbles coated with silica glass, gupeiite (Fe3Si) and xifengite (Fe5Si3), Ti carbide, Al silicide reported, PDFs in quartz reported but not supported by data (Rappenglück et al., 2005). Scattering elipse 58x27 km, 47.8-48.4 dg.N and 12.3-13.0 dg.E (Rappenglück et al., 2005). Sharp-edged broken gravel inside the craters, round pebbles outside; splash-shaped glass and metalic objects (Rappenglück et al., 2005). First published article (Ernstson et al., 2004). (Fehr et al., 2005) studied 12 pits several meters to tens of meters in diameter from an area 48°11'-48°17′N latitude and 12°43′-12°49′E longitude - the Burghausen area. The description is rather consistent with that from (Rappenglück et al., 2005), except that the Si alloys are said to have typically man-made composition. (Fehr et al., 2005) reported a man-made charcoal from one of the pits dated with 14C at AD 134-202. Reported weak magnetic anomalies over the pits (Fehr et al., 2005; Rappenglück et al., 2005); found sub-0.5 mm magnetic particles in the gravel (magnetite) (Fehr et al., 2005); considered various archeological explanations and rejected them (Fehr et al., 2005; Rappenglück et al., 2005).

A circular structure with a concentric annular terraced rim and trough surrounding a central uplift imaged with a 3D seismic data. The seismic data demonstrate absence of any deep structural roots and suggest the presence of multiple concentric inward dipping normal faults. Well logs tied to seismic indicate middle Eocene age. The structure disturbed Crateceous to Eocene siliciclastic units and is overlain with 1490-1600 m of sediments. Quartz grains from well cuttings show up to 4 sets of plannar microstructures with spacing, thickness and orientations consistent with PDF. These observations and morphologic proportions strongly suggest impact origin (Spevack et al, 2007). Stratigraphic age calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004) to the top Bartonian and base Lutetian; coordinates are from a poster accompanying the abstract.

Viewfield is a circular structure buried within the sediments of the Williston Basin, Saskatchewan, Canada. The structure was mapped on 2-D seismic lines and several well logs and appears consistent with simple crater morphology with additional depression of the top of the underlying Devonian salt and the overlying layers attributed to plastic flow during the impact, post-impact salt dissolution and differential compaction. The rim is elevated 60 m above the surrounding and the wells in the center did not reach top of Mississippian indicating the minimum of ~180 m depth. Morphometric comparison of Viewfield to other known craters indicates that ~90 m of the rim height was eroded away (Sawatzky, 1972, 1974, 1975). Sawatzky (1972) considered the structure to be of Triassic-Jurassic age “because disturbed Mississippian limestone and dolomite are sandwiched between Lower Watrous redbeds on the periphery of the rim”. This quote referred to well-log-based cross section and there is no indication in the text this was also based on well samples. Sawatsky’s quote apparently refers to the observation that top of Mississippian is higher in the rim relative to outside the structure and the overlying Lower Watrous unit is missing on the rim. The section above Lower Watrous appears complete on the rim, resting directly on the Mississippian and also appears complete over the inner parts of the structure. Sawatzky (1972) also pointed out anomalous section between Birdbear (below the structure) and top of Mississippian. It, however, is not clear from the cross section what he had in mind. This section appears a bit different between the rim and the inner slope but it is possible to correlate. Instead, the log section above the top Mississippian appears featureless and much thicker than the Lower Watrous outside the structure. Nevertheless, the log-based cross section does indicate that the structure formed during the deposition of the Lower Watrous. The Lower Watrous is likely of Triassic to Middle Jurassic age (Edwards et al., 1994), corresponding to 245-161 Ma (Gradstein et al., 2006). The target included siliciclastics and carbonates. Evaporites are below the structure and anhydrite arecmixed also in the Triassic red beds (Edwards et al., 1994).

Sawatzky (1972) estimated the diameter of the structure at 1.5 miles, i.e. 2.4 km and this diameter has been commonly quoted. The top of the rim on the Sawatzky’s (1972) structure map, however, indicates a diameter of 3.2 km, consistent with the diameter of productive wells on Saskatchewan Oil and Gas map http://www.ir.gov.sk.ca/infomap. The map also provided coordinates for the well in the center of the structure.

Grieve et al. (1998) reported decorated PDFs in detrital quartz from the Lower Watrous within the structure. The report is supported by histogram of measured crystallographic indices but no optical or TEM images were shown.

Garwin and Blodgett (1986) described the structure based on stereo airphotos, Landsat images and a geologic map. The structure is located in flat-lying Ordovician and Devonian shales and sandstones of the Tabuk formation. Garwin and Blodgett (1986) a circular polygonal rim, inner rim-wall terraces, the drainage control around the feature, the hummocky region extending beyond the rim and the steeply dipping "slump terraces" within the oval central region. They proposed impact origin for the structure and estimated Cenozoic age based on the freshness of the rim. They saw no salt diapirs within 100s of km and saw young volcanics 45 km south of the structure. Grieve et al. (1988) noted upturned circular ridge with terraces and slumps on inner side, no central peak, different appearance from other volcanics in the area and noted that field inspection found no shock features. Grieve et al. (1988) listed an age < 360 Ma. Listed by (McHone and Dietz, 1988). More accurate coordinates from Google Earth.

Coordinates and rim-rim diameter from Google Earth (D.Rajmon). (McHone and Greeley, 1997) presented radar observation, lat/lon 32.60/39.42 and 2.75 km diameter, 42 km SW of El-Mirba structure. Structure occurs in Eocene marls and limestones (McHone and Dietz, 1988) therefore the age must be post Paleocene, which is <55.8 Ma calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004). Listed by (Dence, 1972) as a possible impact structure with coordinates lat 32.68, lon 39.58.  Mentioned by (Ibrahim, 1998) as Um Chaimin. Ibrahim (1998) also mentions a pre-Silurian structure 150 km in diameter, which at a first reading can be mistaken for Um Chaimin but more careful reading suggests it is a different structure. Apparently, Um Chaimin is the same structure as Tleachman described on Landsat and radar images by (Theilen-Willige, 1987) because coordinates and diameter are very similar. Tleachman also appears on the same radar frame with, and about 40 km from, Treibil (Theilen-Willige, 1987), which is another name for El-Mirba (McHone and Greeley, 1997). (Theilen-Willige, 1987) talks about obvious impact structure based on radar data and refers to LANDSAT-based map of (Kruck et al., 1981). Discussed by Underwood (1994) in Dressler et al. (1994). Reported by Merriam and Holwerda (1957).

Further discussed by (Sandberg et al., 2002; Morrow and Sandberg, 2005) in context of Late Devonian events. Other references (Ormö, 1994; Morrow et al., 1999). "A roughly circular depression, ~150 km in diameter, on the Bangweulu Block of Zambia. The basin, about 1148 m ASL, is occupied by Lakes Bangweulu (~85 km long) and Kampolombo (~20 km long) and the Bangweulu Swamps. ... Several elongate curved sliver-like islands, including Mbawala (~30 x 4 km) and Chisi, are present in Lake Bangweulu. The curvature of the islands follows the arcuate northwest boundary of the lake in a concentric manner. Unlike all the other major lakes in Zambia and surrounding areas (Mweru, Tanganyika, Rukwa, Malawi, and Kariba), which occupy seismically active rift structures, the Bangweulu Basin is generally aseismic, and is unrelated to rifting. There is a positive aeromagnetic intensity anomaly over the central Bangweulu depression, and there is also a magnetic anomaly density high over the central part of the BB, surrounded by a concentric low. A roughly circular anomaly, outlined by the -140 mgal contour, of the regional Bouguer gravity field is centerd on Lake Bangweulu, surrounded by an arcuate high south of the Luongo Fold Belt. There are few heat flow measurements in Zambia [9], but there is no indication that the Bangweulu Basin has abnormally high heat flow... Satellite imagery of Central Africa clearly shows a roughly circular outline of the Bangweulu Basin, including the lakes and swamps, surrounded by a concentric ring of uplifts. The concentric islands in Lake Bangweulu are reminiscent of the multiple concentric rings around impact basins. ... Any possible connection between the Bangweulu structure and the Lukanga swamp (a postulated astrobleme in central Zambia) is unknown at this stage." - Masters (1993). Coordinates from Master and Reimold (2000).

"The structure, here termed the “Belinga Structure”, is characterized by a distinct rim anticline, which is of annular geometry in three quadrants, but disturbed along the western edge of the structure, where a large slice appears to have slumped inwards. Enhanced imagery indicates numerous radial deformation features (faults?) associated with the structure, as well as an apparent fracture pattern that is very different from the regional lineament distribution and pattern. The central part of the structure (compare Fig. 1) appears fragmented into small, <500 m, blocks and hummocky, and leads to the tentative conclusion that this area could correspond to a ‘collapsed central uplift’ of an impact structure. Figure 2 shows the regional geology,
based on the work by Beaujour [3] and Thomas et al. [4], where the feature is prominent and appears to be made up of Archean granitoid, within the ca. 3.2 Ga greenstone belt. Due to
this dense vegetation, the structure only shows up rather vaguely on the available Landsat imagery. An aeromagnetic follow-up study showed parts of the rim as moderately positive anomalies. Unfortunately, the Belinga greenstone belt, with its associated banded iron formations, does represent a geophysically complex terrane, and the significance of these anomalies cannot be gauged without ground information." - Reimold et al. (2001).

Elliptic pattern of the surrounding mountains (tops originally defining a 48x64 km diameter)  (Kluft, 2007) surounded by a 87 km diameter circular pattern in the ridge geometry (Kluft, 2009). Multispectral satellite imagery shows that the inside of the structure stands out of the surrounding geology, indicating increased levels of mafic igneous rocks, Ni, Cu, Fe.  The central area of the structure (Black Rock Point) displays common centimeter to meter scaled features interpreted as possible eroded shatter cones ( Kluft, 2007). The rim of the proposed structure hosts 1) a 300 m thick red conglomerate with coarse volcanic clasts (many from basalt Kamma Mountains Group, 2) "Camel conglomerate" with slate, siltstone, milky quartz and occasional limestone fragments fining upward and containing more volcanic fragments upward, and 3) white breccia of mostly altered "volcanic" rocks (Wallace, 1980 in Kluft, 2007). Soldier Meadows Tuff surrounding the rim in the northwest to north was interpreted as a single-event deposit without know volcanic source (Stuart, 1980 in Kluft, 2007). These rocks could represent ejecta. Three sets of planar fractures in quartz with fracture spacing 0.5-1 mm were observed on photographs of a hand sample from Calico Range. Single sets of fractures in quartz are common. Melt lava-like rocks blend into unmelted rocks and could represent impact melt. Unnamed igneous rock formation at Black Rock Desert, Nevada between Trego and Sulphur with columnar jointing could represent impact melt sheet. Hycroft Mine at Sulphur shows normal faults dipping west, consistent with this being a possible impact structure eastern wall setting (Kluft, 2007). The Black Rock Range has been observed to have a persistent pattern of hundreds of feet of breccia overlying fractured and jointed rocks across an area of several square miles that were observed (Kluft, 2009).


Comment from D. Rajmon: Although the above observations are consistent with an impact scenario, they are also consistent with a volcanic scenario and the normal faulting could just be the result of the Basin and Range extension. The reported shatter cones do not appear convincing on the pictures. Nevertheless, if this is an impact site, there appears enough material preserved that should contain wide range of shock indicators.

In 1988, space scientists (Papagiannis and El Baz, 1988a,b; Papagiannis, 1989) suggested that the Bohemian Massif is an old impact crater (“The Praha Basin”), with an excentric central uplift in the SE part. Bouška (1990) discussed the proposed ~100-Ma age (Papagiannis oral comm. in Bouška, 1990) and pointed out that no major impact event occurred at least during the last 700 Ma (constrained by unaffected upper-Proterozoic sediments). Bouška (1990) however admitted that the structure is not inconsistent with gravimetric and MOHO-discontinuity depth profiles. 
Bouška (1990), Bouška and Skála (1992,1993), and Skála and Bouška (1992) listed several properties of diamonds from the "Pyrope gravels", which are typical for impact diamonds - mainly the unusual luminescence mentioned already by Kouřimský and Kutil (1959) and resembling diamonds from Popigai. However, only two diamonds were found in the gravels leaving the possibility of a contamination or even forgery. Silicon carbide (moissanite) was found not only in sediments but was also separated directly from volcanic breccia (Bauer et al., 1963), nevertheless, its origin from mantle is possible too.
Rajlich et al. (1996) showed that the present morphology of the Bohemian massif could be formed by a shear-dominated tectonics in lithosphere containing a resistant circular inclusion. Based on that and other indications, Rajlich (2004, 2005b, 2006b) concluded that the Bohemian massif evolved from an old impact structure, which appeared 1000-2000 Ma ago in a terrestrial target formed prevalently by sediments. This structure should have stiffened relatively to its surroundings due to the impact melt and intensive hydrothermal activity.
Occurrence of pseudotachylites was reported (Rajlich, 1992, 2005a). One of the suggested pseudotachylite breccias (Rajlich, 2005a) had been also explained by "dehydration metamorphism" due to thermal working of a pluton (Fediuková and Suk, 1979).
Numerous occurrences of VHP- and UHP-metamorphism have been documented (Becker and Altherr, 1992; Kotková et al., 1997; Nasdala and Massonne 2000) and were explained by deep Variscan subductions by these authors. Arguments against considered subductions include (Procházka, unpublished):
1. deep subduction of continental crust required,
2. no unequivocal relicts of prograde metamorphism before the peak metamorphism are preserved,
3. suggested exhumation of the subducted material leads to hardly explainable relative vertical movements with exaggeration >50 km on few-km distance in many areas.
Most recently, investigation of possible shocked minerals has started and first observations have been published in short reports (Rajlich, 2006a,b; Procházka, 2006a,b).
Erosion would probably remove most of the suevites and larger portion of the impact melt. The northern part is prevalently covered by Cretaceous sediments. In general the geological exploration in the Bohemian Massif has been very detailed, but most of relatively recent work was made for mineral deposits. Also boreholes are very abundant but in the crystalline units mostly until 100-200 m (the significant exception being KTB in Germany) and none of them were made for impact investigation. At present, Bohemian Massif is thought to have originated from Variscan amalgamation of several micro-continents earlier influenced by Cadomian and possible Cambro-Ordovician tectono-metamorphic events.

(Khryanina, 1985) described crater-like morphology, with consetric arcuate and radial faults defining central depression, surrounded by an arcuate ridge and outer grabens. Free air gravity anomalies are up to -40 mGal in the center, +40 mGal on the ridge and -50 mGal in the grabens. Seismic data indicate that the central depression is filled with 4 km of sediment, outer graben with 2 km and the ridge is covered with <0.5 km of sediment. Size and location of the structure is consistent with tektites, microtektites, apparently partially melted ilmenite and sylvite and increased sediment susceptivity in six cores from the Ross Sea reported by (Gerard-Little et al., 2006). The cores are located at lat -72 to -78 and lon 172 to -176 (Gerard-Little et al., 2006) just south of the structure. The abundance of tektites increases toward north (Gerard-Little et al., 2006), i.e. toward the structure. Biostratigraphic age of the tektites based on diatoms is Late Pliocene.

Data from Legg et al. (2004), coordinates from Google Earth and figures in Legg et al. (2004). Also see Emery Knoll and Navy structures. Abstract from Legg et al. (2004): "Digital mosaics of swath and conventional bathymetry data reveal large, distinct near-circular crater structures in the Inner Continental Borderland offshore southern California. Two have maximum crater diameters that exceed 30 km and a third has a crater diameter of approximately 12 km. All three features exhibit the morphology of large complex craters (raised outer rim, ring moat and central uplift) yet their exact origin remains a mystery. Preliminary analyses of available seismic, gravity and magnetic data over these structures reveal both similarities and distinct differences in geometry, structure and geophysical signature to known impact sites. All three crater structures, however, occur within the Catalina terrane, a highly extended volcanic and metamorphic province floored by Catalina schist basement. A likely alternative origin may thus involve explosive volcanism, caldera collapse and resurgent magmatism, and/or possibly plutonism and schist remobilization associated with the Catalina terrane. No single model for crater formation, whether impact, caldera or pluton, fully accounts for all of the present observations regarding the morphology, internal structure and known geology of these near-circular features. Timing of crater formation post-dates the initial rifting and rotation of the western Transverse Ranges, and appears to predate major right slip along the San Clemente and San Diego Trough fault systems—or approximately 18 to 16 Ma. Regardless of their origin, these complex craters represent some of the largest structures of their kind in western North America and provide a unique opportunity to better understand the development of unusual crater structures in a submarine environment."

Cerro Blanco suspected complex impact structure; disturbed sediments from the Triassic upper shale member of the Chinle Formation within the central uplift to Cretaceous Mesaverde Formation on the crater rim. I date the structure as Late Cretaceous to Tertiary because the only deposition on top of the structure is late Tertiary. The structure has been bisected by a north easterly trending high angle fault which destroyed part of the eastern side of the structure. Diameter of the structure is ~6km and the diameter of central uplift is ~2.5km based on aerial photos. There are faults radiating out from the central uplift and annular faults within the central uplift area that have removed some formations. I found clastic dikes extending from the base of the Triassic Entrada formation into the Chinle Formation. The dikes vary in width from a few centimeters up to 1 meter, and they projected down into the Carmel formation for at least 1.5 meters. Some of the larger dikes passed under the talus slope and I was unable to find out how deeply they penetrated the Chinle. I have found planar structures in some grains of porous and permeable sandstones ranging in age from Triassic to Cretaceous that do not show any evidence of either contact or regional metamorphism. The best examples of the planar elements are spaced less than 10 microns and the planar fractures are greater than 15 microns. The planar microstructures will probably be classified as low pressure or of tectonic origin. The fact that the PM’s are found in formations from Cretaceous to Triassic age and are localized in the structure would rule out the possibility that the grains with tectonic or low pressure PM’s are eroded from a metamorphosed rock. I separated grains with PM’s and mounted them on a spindle stage and using methods developed by F. Donald Bloss (Bloss, 1981). I measured the orientation of the planar features and plotted those angles against a quartz template to determine the frequency of uniquely indexed PM’s. A histogram of frequency of uniquely indexed planar microstructure orientations in quartz grains from sandstone within the structure gave the following results: C-axis angle to perpendicular to PM (degrees), 19 grains examined, 58 PM’s measured, 88% of PM’s were uniquely classified, 12% PM’s unclassified, plus or minus 5 degree margin of error, 3.44% @  0.0 degrees, 15.5% @ 22.95 degrees, 6.9% @ 32.42 degrees, 10.3% @ 47.72degrees, 12.1% @ 51.79 degrees, 8.6% @ 65.55 degrees, 10.3% @ 73.42 degrees, 13.8% @ 81.95 degrees, and 6.9% @ 90 degrees. The unusual frequency distribution of the measured PM’s is probably due to their being formed in a porous sedimentary rock at considerable depth. These PM’s probably do not fit the ridged PDF’s standard and therefore not definitive, but I believe they were caused by a shock wave and are significant when considering the entire body of evidence (Grieve et al., 1996; French et al., 2004). Other microscopic evidence includes what appear to be melted and quenched grains, partially melted grains, catastrophic brecciated sandstone with larger clasts of grains and material from several different formations disturbed by the impact that have been injected into clastic dikes at the base of the Triassic Entrada Formation in the Chinle formation. I have not shown this structure to any other geologists. Age calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

They are formed in basalts and sandstones of the Paraná Basin. The structure shows morphologic features of complex craters, with central uplift and annular graben. The apparent similar age of these three structures and their alignment along N30E led to a proposal that they could represent the scars of a multiple impact event. It is estimated that this occurred around 117 Ma ago. Unconfirmed reports of shocked rocks from the central uplift (Romano and Crósta, 2004 and references within). Impact structure first suspected from geological map patterns seen on Simkin et al. (2006) map. Crater diameter 400-800 km estimated from bedrock geological map patterns and digital elevation model for the basin (G. Herman, 2007, pers. comm., New Jersey Geological Survey). The current explanation for a tectonic origin of the Congo basin (Cuvette Cental) is thermal subsidence and associated sediment loading succeeding Late Proterozoic rifting and an early Paleozoic pan-African contractional event (Daly et al., 1992). Daly et al. (1992) based their stratigraphic sequence and structural interpretations on several drill holes, two seismic reflection cross sections and earlier geologic work. The data presented by Daly et al. (1992) do not preclude impact interpretation. Assuming impact origin of the structure, the Permian to  Triassic unconformity clearly constrains the upper age of the structure. Daly et al. (1992) does not provide a precise age of the overlying ~1 km of Triassic sediments; thus the limit chosen in the database is top Triassic calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). The lower age limit is difficult to constrain from the data and palinspastic reconstructions of Daly et al. (1992) and could be as old as Precambrian but probably post-Gondwana assembly, i.e. ~600 Ma. Some graphics outlining the proposed structure are available at http://www.impacttectonics.org/gondwana.html.

First studied by (Mitchum, 1951) and no other work was reported for long time. (Deane, 2004) looked at the structure again and cited (Mitchum, 1951) that he reported that the structure is a half-circle of Upper Ordovician carbonate strata with a radius of ~600 m. He (Mitchum) presumed that the missing half of the structure is buried under Lower Mississippian strata capping a hillside to the northeast. There was a small (90 m diameter) core of uplifted material near the center of the structure characterized by “high dips, tight folding, faulting, and shearing,” and surrounded by a depressed annular ring with “buckling and tight folding.” This in turn, is surrounded by a “gentle ring-shaped anticline.” There were faults and some minor occurrences of brecciation (Mitchum, 1951 in Deane, 2004). (Deane, 2004) noted that the structure coordinates were published incorrect in several lists of suspected impact structures and found the correct location. (Deane, 2004) also suggested that the diameter of the structure may be significantly greater. Age calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004). Coordinates from  (Deane, 2006). Two have maximum crater diameters that exceed 30 km and a third has a crater diameter of approximately 12 km. All three features exhibit the morphology of large complex craters (raised outer rim, ring moat and central uplift) yet their exact origin remains a mystery. Preliminary analyses of available seismic, gravity and magnetic data over these structures reveal both similarities and distinct differences in geometry, structure and geophysical signature to known impact sites. All three crater structures, however, occur within the Catalina terrane, a highly extended volcanic and metamorphic province floored by Catalina schist basement. A likely alternative origin may thus involve explosive volcanism, caldera collapse and resurgent magmatism, and/or possibly plutonism and schist remobilization associated with the Catalina terrane. No single model for crater formation, whether impact, caldera or pluton, fully accounts for all of the present observations regarding the morphology, internal structure and known geology of these near-circular features. Timing of crater formation post-dates the initial rifting and rotation of the western Transverse Ranges, and appears to predate major right slip along the San Clemente and San Diego Trough fault systems—or approximately 18 to 16 Ma. Regardless of their origin, these complex craters represent some of the largest structures of their kind in western North America and provide a unique opportunity to better understand the development of unusual crater structures in a submarine environment."

The Gunnison structure is a circular feature located in Southern Colorado, just SW of the town of Gunnison, lat. 38.48188º, lon -106.98386º. A prominent arcuate ridge of steeply dipping country rocks and an adjacent Gold Basin Creek valley define its geomorphological outline in the NE and a part of SE quadrant. More intermittent outcrops and an arcuate fabric extend this outline to the S and SE. The arc of the Gunnison river further defines the outline in the NW quadrant. This outline has a diameter of  ~8 km. The structure is known in the literature as the Gunnison Igneous Complex, GIC. Geological maps show the complex as a ring of intermediate to acidic plutonic rocks surrounding and surrounded by supracrustal rocks both belonging to Cochetopa succession. The rocks in the SW quadrant of the plutonic ring are referred to as the granite of the South Beaver Creek and the western part of the ring contains quartz diorite. The supracrustal rocks include tholeiitic metabasalts and metarhyolites intercalated with volcaniclastic metasediments. All of these rocks were multiply folded and metamorphosed to lower amphibolite facies (Shaw and Karlstrom, 1999; Hill and Bickford, 2001; Sims and Stein, 2003; Bickford et al., 2008). The Gunnison Igneous Complex is considered a part of the Salida-Gunnison magmatic arc complex with active magmatism during 1.70-1.77 Ga. This arc complex is in turn part of a larger Colorado province representing multiple Proterozoic orogenies (Hill and Bickford, 2001; Sims and Stein, 2003). Some of the geochronological work in this region included rocks specifically from the GIC. The granite of the South Beaver Creek yielded U-Pb zircon age of ~1.72 Ga and SHRIMP ages for overgrown zircon rims of ~1.70 Ga (Hill and Bickford, 2001 and ref. within). The quartz diorite of the South Beaver Creek yielded U-Pb zircon age ~1.73 Ga, the rhyolite and granite near Iris, about 8 km SE of GIC and representing rocks equivalent to those in GIC, yielded U-Pb zircon ages of ~1.73 and ~1.70 Ga, resp. (ref. in Reed et al., 1987).

J. Tonko proposed impact origin of the structure based on its circular shape and inclined layering in the rim. He further claimed the existence of impact breccia, impact melt (tektites) and metallic particles in the melt within “central uplift” (Tonko, 2007 and Tonko, pers. comm., 2006-2009). Presented photographs of inclined granite sheets from the rim of the structure and low magnification photographs of rocks (breccias?) do not constitute relevant evidence for these claims however.

Askvik (2000) described outcrops of granitic rocks with irrecular patches of dark breccia bodies and narrow dikes and brecciation arround these patches. The breccias contain fine grained carbon with δC-13 = -29 ‰. Askvik (2000) compared these rocks with those at Gardnos and proposed their impact origin. The age of the structure is between late Precambrian and Caledonian orogeny (Askvik, 2000). Based on this information the numerical age has been broadly asigned between the start of late Proterozoic and the end of Devonian, calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). The coordinates point to one studied outcrop. Moilanen (2004) listed the breccia occurences as the Hardangervidda structure asigning it a probable impact origin.

Reports of fullerenes occurrence in shungite (amorphous carbon) led J. Klokočník (2009, pers. comm.) to consider the possibility of extraterrestrial origin of the fullerenes and a possibility of an impact structure existence in the shungite occurrence area. J. Klokočník calculated second derivative of the gravity potential in the vertical direction according to EGM 08 and received a map with multiple anomalies. Some negative anomalies form weakly prominent round pattern ~50 km in diameter. It is concetric with, and has the extend of, a round pattern of the Zaonezhskiy zaliv and other smaller lakes. J. Klokočník further observed that these features are surrounded by a round morphological elevation rising ~100 m above the interior area and ~100 km in diameter. Shungite mined in the area is thought to represent metamorphosed and petrified hydrocarbon accumulation within Archean siliciclastics and volcaniclastics (Melezhik et al., 2004). Attempts to reproduce the initial reports of fullerenes in shungite were unsuccesful (Melezhik et al., 2004).

References:

Melezhik V. A., Filippov M. M. and Romashkin A. E. (2004) A giant Palaeoproterozoic deposit of shungite in NW Russia: genesis and practical applications. Ore Geology Reviews 24(1-2):135-154. http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.oregeorev.2003.08.003

Named after a nearby village.

A 4.67 km diameter structure found on satellite radar images. It is situated on Precambrian gneisses and is partly faulted away on its western side by Neocomian faults related to the openning of the Atlantic ocean; it is thus older than 145 Ma (Martinez-Torres, 1995 in Master, 1998). Master (1998) proposed this to be the source crater for Brazilian and African carbonados; a rather speculative proposal considering the small size of the structure (D. Rajmon). Data from Master and Reimold (2000).

"A circular feature near the village Luna, located in the northwestern part of Banni Plains. The site lies within extensively laid unconsolidated sediments, and the altitude of the region is scarcely around 3–5 m from the sea level. The inner part of the rim–crater junction is better defined than the outer rim due to vegetation. It measures 1.2 km E–W (~ 2.11 outer rim), 1.2 km N–S (~2.15 outer rim). The circular crater forms a shallow depression filled with sediments and the lowest point of the depression is hardly 2 m above the mean sea level. The rim of the crater rises about 2 m from the surroundings, which in turn averages to around 3.5 m. ... The effect of rapid siltation of the crater and erosion of the rim is such that conventionally measured depth to diameter ratio is dismally low. Rim and central part of almost 1 km wide depression hardly has 3–4 m of difference and from the surrounding plains is also negligible. ... Several lumps of dark and heavy objects measuring 2–6 cm were recovered from the rim part of the structure. Most lumps were of irregular shape consisting of numerous spherical cavities and some
were strongly attracted to hand-magnets. Based on the petrographic study of thin sections cut from the samples collected, they can be classified into three categories: (i) completely dark and opaque, (ii) completely transparent (in thin sections only, in hand specimens more or less opaque) and isotropic (under crossed nicols), and (iii) areas comprising both dark–opaque and transparent–isotropic materials. Those belonging to category-1 are found to be strongly attracted to the hand-magnet and those in category-2 have obsidian-like appearance with vitreous
lustre and conchoidal fracture. All the three are blackish and opaque in hand specimens; nonetheless category-2 samples are transparent only along thin edges. Category-1 samples are likely to be metallic meteorite fragments. Under microscope, polished samples belonging to category-1 exhibit thin shimmering lines that apparently resemble ‘Neumann lines’ (of kamacite) commonly observed in iron–nickel meteorites7,8. However, it is proposed to confirm the same by appropriate analysis. Specimens of category-2 can be compared to ‘tektites’ formed on account of melting of the material of the site of impact and immediate solidification into glass due to enormous heat generated by the impact. ... There is further scope for exploring the
possibility of correlation of this site with the impact site mentioned in ancient Sanskrit texts. According to Iyengar6, the Rann of Kachchh was referred to as ‘Irina’ in the Rgveda and a few other Sanskrit texts, where a fireball/meteorite had fallen. Perhaps dating of this event by modern methods could reveal the age of some of the Sanskrit texts that have described the incidence. The archaeological site mentioned above is located about 1 km southwest of the suspected crater. According to Rao, the ruins of the settlement belong to Harappan age (around 4000 years old)." - Karath et al. (2006). The age appears holocene based on the above description (D. Rajmon), calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004).

An impact structure proposal based on a circular pattern noticed on satellite image of Australia (Connelly, 2009 with associated slide presentation). Using satellite images and digital elevation model on Google Earth combined with geologic, magnetic and gravity maps, Connely (2009) argued for an existence of a central zone surrounded by two concentric ridges 500 and 2000 km in diameter coinciding with gravity and magnetic anomalies. Connely (2009) further noted occurence of pseudotachylites, interpretted some formations as ejecta and suggested oblique impact with multiple confirmed impact craters being part of the fall. Connely (2009) proposed ~545 Ma age based on some geologic considerations. 

The impact proposal is highly speculative with numerous unfounded interpretations, incl. impact origin of the pseudotachylites and "ejecta".

"The Mekambo structure, centred on 0°55’39” N, 13°40’25” E, is located in Ogooué- Ivindo province of Gabon, and its northern part extends into the Sangha province of the Republic of Congo (Brazzaville). It is defined by a 50 km diameter circular region of subdued magnetic relief marked by a central intense magnetic anomaly. It is surrounded by a concentric ring of high-relief magnetic anomalies, which extend a further 30 km beyond the structure. Topographically the structure is defined by a central plateau >500 m above sea level, which is surrounded by a concentric depression (<500m) occupied by the W-flowing Zadié and Liboumba rivers, which curve around the central plateau, and then by a doughnut-shaped outer ring between the Zadié and Djoua rivers in the N, and the Lodié and Bounandjié rivers in the S. The Mekambo structure is also situated mainly on Archean granite greenstone terrains of the North Gabon block. The target includes granite, gneiss, banded iron formation, amphibolite, and mica-schist. The surrounding concentric ring of high-relief magnetic anomalies is due to ferruginous greenstone belts. The northern part of the structure is covered by flat-lying sedimentary rocks of the Sembé-Ouesso Group, which is correlated with the ca. 2.1 Ga Francevillian of central Gabon. These rocks, in turn, are intruded by undeformed E-W trending magnetic dykes." Possibly double impact with Minkebe. "Minkebe must post-date the 3.1-2.8 Ga Archean basement, but the Mekambo structure appears to be covered by the Paleoproterozoic (c. 2.1 Ga) Sembé-Ouesso Group, and both structures are cut by the Paleoproterozoic Nkan-Mekogo strike-slip fault. It thus appears that these structures were formed between ca. 2.8 and 2.1 Ga." - Antoine et al. (2000). All data from Antoine et al. (2000).

An inferred impact structure within the Minch Basin based on the occurrence of proximal ejecta layer along the coast of Scotland - the Stac Fada Member (Amor et al., 2008). 

“The Stac Fada Member forms a distinctive unit within the Mesoproterozoic Stoer Group, the oldest sedimentary rocks of the Torridonian Supergroup in NW Scotland. It has previously been described as volcanic in origin and it can be traced for 50 km along a N-S–aligned outcrop. Bedding dips ~20° to the west, and the Stoer Group is assumed to underlie the Mesozoic Minch Basin. The group lies unconformably on the Archean Lewisian gneiss, and sediments were deposited in a semiarid environment, blanketing a paleolandscape with relief of <300 m. A Pb-Pb isochron for a stromatolitic limestone ~10 m above the Stac Fada Member at location 7 has provided an age for the Stoer Group of 1199 ± 70 Ma. At this same location, the Stac Fada Member is underlain by >500 m of interbedded fluviatile and alluvial sandstones, and ripple-marked lacustrine siltstones and mudstones.” - (Amor et al., 2008 and references within)
Using optical microscopy and SEM, Amor et al. (2008) documented multiple sets of PDFs in quartz grains within the suevite unit (fulfilling the morphology, spacing and measured crystallographic orientation criteria). The suevite unit grades into a fine-grained lapilli unit interpreted as air-fall. The Stac Fada Member enriched in Cr, Ni, and Co relative to underlying sandstone and gneiss. Ni/Co indicate contamination with chondritic material. Increased epsilon53Cr indicates meteoritic contamination. Enrichment in PGE has been documented at locations 6 and 7 (Amor et al., 2008). The projectile appears to be either chondrite or a comet.

The source crater was either east or west of the ejecta outcrops, likely within the Minch Basin to the west (Amor et al., 2008).
Approximate coordinates read from Google Earth.

References:

Amor K., Hesselbo S. P., Porcelli D., Thackrey S. and Parnell J. (2008) A Precambrian proximal ejecta blanket from Scotland. Geology 36(4):303-306. http://dx.doi.org/10.1130%2FG24454A.1

"Minkebe structure, which is ca. 90 km in diameter, is centred on 1°21’15” N, 12°24’29” E, and straddles the border between Woleu-Ntem and Ogooué-Ivindo provinces. It is distinguished by a circular rim and by structural fabrics that are discontinuous across the rim. Fabrics within the structure trend NW-SE, whereas they trend NE-SW and ENE-WSW to the west and north of the structure. The eastern half of the Minkebe structure is characterised by a subdued magnetic relief forming a contiguous, concentric belt that extends for 50 km beyond the rim. Topographically the structure consists of a central plateau, between 664 to 937 m above sea level, which is surrounded by concentric valleys of the Mvoung and Nouna rivers, which are south-flowing tributaries of the Ogooué. ... The country rocks around the structure consist entirely of Archean granites, gneisses and greenstone belts (granite, gneiss, banded iron formation, amphibolite, mica-schist, diorite, monzonite, K-feldspar porphyry) of the North Gabon block. The ca. 3.1 to 2.9 Ga supracrustal greenstone belts comprise banded iron-formations, amphibolites and mica-schists, which have a high magnetic relief, and which also show up as high-relief topographic features in Sidelooking Airborne Radar (SLAR) images. The heterogeneous granitoids (diorites, monzonites, Kfeldspar porphyries), are dated at 3.04 to 2.86 Ga. The foliations of these granites are generally conformable with those in the greenstones. Some
calc-alkaline granites, dated at 2.76 Ga, are clearly discordant and intrusive into the greenstones." Possibly double impact with Mekambo. "Minkebe must post-date the 3.1-2.8 Ga Archean basement, but the Mekambo structure appears to be covered by the Paleoproterozoic (c. 2.1 Ga) Sembé-Ouesso Group, and both structures are cut by the Paleoproterozoic Nkan-Mekogo strike-slip fault. It thus appears that these structures were formed between ca. 2.8 and 2.1 Ga." - Antoine et al. (2000). All data from Antoine et al. (2000).

Data from Legg et al. (2004), coordinates from Google Earth and figures in Legg et al. (2004). Also see Catalina and Emery Knoll structures. Abstract from Legg et al. (2004): "Digital mosaics of swath and conventional bathymetry data reveal large, distinct near-circular crater structures in the Inner Continental Borderland offshore southern California. Two have maximum crater diameters that exceed 30 km and a third has a crater diameter of approximately 12 km. All three features exhibit the morphology of large complex craters (raised outer rim, ring moat and central uplift) yet their exact origin remains a mystery. Preliminary analyses of available seismic, gravity and magnetic data over these structures reveal both similarities and distinct differences in geometry, structure and geophysical signature to known impact sites. All three crater structures, however, occur within the Catalina terrane, a highly extended volcanic and metamorphic province floored by Catalina schist basement. A likely alternative origin may thus involve explosive volcanism, caldera collapse and resurgent magmatism, and/or possibly plutonism and schist remobilization associated with the Catalina terrane. No single model for crater formation, whether impact, caldera or pluton, fully accounts for all of the present observations regarding the morphology, internal structure and known geology of these near-circular features. Timing of crater formation post-dates the initial rifting and rotation of the western Transverse Ranges, and appears to predate major right slip along the San Clemente and San Diego Trough fault systems—or approximately 18 to 16 Ma. Regardless of their origin, these complex craters represent some of the largest structures of their kind in western North America and provide a unique opportunity to better understand the development of unusual crater structures in a submarine environment."

Circular depression noted by S. Hamilton as a possible impact crater (2007, pers. comm.) The depression has a rim-rim diameter of 450-420 with the longer axis oriented SW-NE. No raised rim could be recognized on Google Earth DEM. The interior is filled with evaporite and probably mud/sand deposits and is 6-10 m below the rim. The NE rim is punctuated by a circular feature ~40 m in diameter, which could be another impact crater. Observations from Google Earth. Assuming impact origin and considering the degree of preservation the structure could be of Quaternary age. The depression is the largest one of a group of depressions within a distance of several kilometers and I (D. Rajmon) tentatively asigned them to a crater field named after the largest structure. Geologic maps of the area indicate target consisting of Cenozoic Laterite/Sand and underlying upper Proterozoic Quartz Sandstone (S. Hamilton, 2007, pers. comm.).

"About 20 years ago while I was flying a small aircraft at about 6000 ft. altitude from Merritt Island, Florida to Macon, Ga. I was startled to see a perfect meteor crater in an extremely remote area of the Okefenokee swamp.  I remember it as looking far more like something seen on the moon than in a Georgia swamp.  Now we have a new tool in Google Earth, so I have spent some time trying to find the crater that way.  The swamps are filled with small circular objects, but I have identified one which might have been the crater I saw.  Interestingly, although I looked throughout the swamp area, the circle I found is almost on a direct line from Merritt Island to Macon. I saw the crater from some distance away, at a small angle to horizontal,  which accentuated the ruggedness of the sides, but the straight down perspective of Google Earth makes it hard to say this circle is the crater I saw.  It is also difficult to judge the size from an airplane, but the circle I found on Google earth scales about 55 meters.  I must have been a mile or two from the crater in the airplane, so I would think it would have been larger than that." - (Andrew Conlyn, 21Apr2010, pers. comm.). Several other circular features suggest the Okefenokee structure could be a member of a crater field. The structure (whether of impact or other origin) most likely formed in Holocene, i.e. <12 ka old, otherwise it would be destroyed by the fluvial processes. Likely formed in a swamp or lake environment, so the water depth during formation would be up to a few meters.

Barretto (2006) reported a circular depression 550 m in diameter and an occurrence of breccias with evidence of partial melting and shatter cones. Photographs document a rusty colored breccia hand sample and several fragments with striated surfaces but no clear shatter cones. The structure is located in the head of a valley and the NE rim of the structure is 70 m higher than the SW rim. The bedrock at the site is gneissic syenite (A. Neumair and P. Barretto, 2009, pers. communication).
Barretto (2008; 2009) noted that the Panela structure is elongated in the same direction as the Rio Cuarto craters and speculated that they could be related and formed during a postulated Tupana event. Barretto (2008; 2009)] further noted prehistoric drawings at several archeological sites surrounding Panela structure that could be interpreted as recording a meteorite fall. These drawings date around 1200 year B.C. (radiocarbon dates on charcoal).
The relationship of the structure to the prehistoric paintings is speculative at the moment and the age (regardless of the structure origin) is better established based on preserved geomorphology at Quaternary, i.e. <~1.8 Ma.

Proposed complex impact structure, the central uplift is approximately 2.5km in diameter. I date the formation of this structure Late Pennsylvanian to Tertiary. The youngest rocks directly disturbed are late Pennsylvanian and the earliest deposition on top of the structure is late Tertiary. The crater radius measured from center of the central uplift to the edge of the ring syncline ~6.5km measured on aerial photos. The existing morphological structure is a pie shaped wedge with the apex to the north. The central uplift is well preserved in the north, and the ring syncline is well preserved to the south. The central uplift seems to have been formed by two bolides and is a topographic low. The central uplift pipe or throat (?) is filled breccia clasts from dust size to huge 50 meter clasts of broken and rotated Pennsylvanian Formation sequences with bedding planes. I have anecdotal evidence that a water well drilled near the southern edge of the central uplift encountered basement rock at approximately 50 meters; however, estimating the stratigraphic position that the well was spuded in by correlating with the formations exposed in the wall of the central uplift I would expect to encounter the Precambrian at approximately 200 meters. By correlating the outcrop of a chert marker bed in the central uplift wall with the chert in large blocks of mega breccia in the central uplift I have also estimated ~200 meters of uplift. There is a ring syncline roughly concentric with the central uplift; however, the ring syncline seems a little too large for a central uplift of this size. I have found folds, faults and crushed formation that match the description and diagrams of radial transpression ridges, (Kenkmann and von Dalwigk, 2000). I have found what I believe are shatter cones in a siliceous shale within the central uplift. I have found hard Pennsylvanian limestone injected with angular (cataclastically brecciated?) sand that I believe are clastic dikes. I have found planar structures in some grains of porous and permeable Pennsylvanian sandstone that does not show any evidence of either contact or regional metamorphism. The best examples of the planar elements are spaced less than 10 microns and the planar fractures are greater than 15 microns. The planar microstructures will probably be classified as low pressure or of tectonic origin. The planar microstructures are localized in the structure, which would rule out the possibility that the grains with tectonic planar microstructures are eroded from a metamorphosed rock. I separated grains with PM’s and mounted them on a spindle stage and using methods developed by F. Donald Bloss (Bloss, 1981). I measured the orientation of the planar features and plotted those angles against a quartz template to determine the frequency of uniquely indexed PM’s. A histogram of frequency of uniquely indexed planar microstructure orientations in quartz grains from Pennsylvanian sandstone within the structure gave the following results: C-axis angle to perpendicular to PM (degrees), 30 grains examined, 108 PM’s measured, 89% of PM’s were uniquely classified, 11% PM’s unclassified, plus or minus 5 degree margin of error, 9.3% @  0.0 degrees, 10.2% @ 22.95 degrees, 11.1% @ 32.42 degrees, 11.1% @ 47.72degrees, 7.4% @ 51.79 degrees, 13% @ 65.55 degrees, 11.1% @ 73.42 degrees, 12% @ 81.95 degrees, and 3.8% @ 90 degrees. The unusual frequency distribution of the measured PM’s is probably due to their being formed in a porous sedimentary rock at considerable depth. The PM’s formed in porous sedimentary rock probably do not fit the ridged PDF’s standard and therefore not definitive, but I believe they were caused by a shock wave and are significant when considering the entire body of evidence (Grieve et al., 1996; French et al., 2004). Geologists Marjorie Chan and David Dinter of the University of Utah; Jared Morrow of UNC  have visited the sight and have offered me encouragement but have not expressed an opinion one way or the other as to its impact origin. A graduate student under the supervision of Marjorie Chan is working on a geological map of the Pecos Structure and although she has not finished her thesis I believe that she is considering classifying the mega-breccia in the central uplift as a land slide. Age calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

Hargraves and Fuller (1981) observed that the accurate northwestern rim of the upper Witwatersrand sedimentary basin in South Africa represents a segment of circular structure roughly 350 km in diameter. A 500 km diameter circle can be drawn following an outline of the lower Witwatersrand Supergroup (lower Nsuze and upper Mozaan Subgroups of the Pongola Group) and centered at lat. -27.5, lon. 28.2. The center of these circles coincide with a positive Bouguer gravity anomaly, near Reitz, South Africa. Hargraves and Fuller (1981) considered several mechanisms that could establish such a large circular structure associated with substantial crust thinning to allow sustained subsidence and deposition of sediments - mantle hot spot, a plume or other form of diapirism. They further explored the possibility of impact origin of this structure noting that the structure does not necessarily need to represent the crater and that a 250 km crater could be sufficient to generate the observed 500 km circular structure. Impact statistics predict a 250 km crater every 200-300 Ma (Hargraves and Fuller, 1981). Zircons from lava in the lower Nsuze subgroup (3090 ± 90 Ma) and igneous rocks (2874 Ma, Rb-Sr)  intruding the Pongola Group (Hargraves and Fuller, 1981 and references within) constrain the formation of the Reitz Ring at ~3.1 Ga (D.Rajmon).

properties.Age_Ma: Late Campanian to Pleistocene, possibly near Campanian/Maastrichtian boundary
properties.Notes:
A circular depression discovered on continuous seismic profiling data (5 lines crossing the structure) on the bottom surface and underlying acoustic basement. The structure diameter along the isobath 5900 m is 12 km and the depression depth in the basement relief is 700 m. The acoustic basement is exposed on on the southeastern slope and partially on the northern slope. The basement depression is filled with 400m of sediments. The morphology of the structure (h/D = 0.04) and its isolated nature are consistent with this being an impact structure (Levin et al., 2006). Levin et al. (2006) refers to Nemchenko et al. (1997), for a discussion of alternative origins. Levin et al. (2006) considered the size of the structure and the present water depth, and concluded that the structure must have formed at a time when the sea level was substantially lower. The sediments in the area comprise Berriasian-Holocene. The Berriasian-Campanian carbonates form the basement seismic complex were deposited at water depth 2 km shallower than today. The siliceous deposits filling the structure formed at a more abyssal conditions (Levin et al., 2006). Levin et al. (2006) thus concluded that the structucture formed near the Cretaceous-Paleogene boundary and linked it to a proposed chain of Oasis, Kamennyi and Karskii craters. Presented stratigraphic data leave considerable uncertainty in the age of the structure however, as the structure could have formed during the later stages of the carbonate deposition and there is no information presented about the upper age limit other than that the structure is filled with 700m of post-Campanian abyssal sediments. The seismic profile (in Levin et al., 2006) also shows that the post-structure sediments are about 50 m thick around the structure. The structure thus could be quite young. The age of the structure thus can be approximatelly constrained within the late Campanian through Pleistocene, i.e. about 75-0.01Ma. Assuming impact origin, the need for target water depth being shallower than today constrains the upper age of the structure to the transition between shallower carbonate and deeper silicic sedimentation around Campanian/Maastrichtian boundary, i.e. ~70 Ma. The adopted age in this database is thus 70 Ma with an uncertainty range 75-0.01 (D. Rajmon). The stratigraphic age calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). Note that all theoretical and observational evidence suggest that crater chains do not form on the Earth (see reviews by Melosh, 1998 or Rajmon, 2007)

"We are investigating a possible Pleistocene impact structure near the town of General San Martin close to the boundary between Buenos Aires and La Pampa Provinces. Although unimpressive in satellite photography, the structure is unambiguous in radar (Fig. 4). Its relief is a significant regional anomaly. Aerial reconnaissance confirms that the rim creates a broad topographic rise distinct from the numerous other lakes and salt pans in the area. It is 10 to 12 km in diameter, and its floor lies at least 55 meters below the rim. Ground observations show that the rim is composed of highly fractured carbonate-cemented loess in places covered by carbonate breccias similar to some of the deposits surrounding La Dulce. Presently, direct evidence for an impact origin is lacking. However, we have sampled a glassy mass unearthed only a few kilometers from the structure which is very similar to tagamitic bombs found near the rims of known impact craters. This impact melt gives a tentative 40Ar/39Ar age of approximately 1.2 Ma." - Harris et al. (2007)

A circular feature prominent on the satellite images reported by an engineer Ali Fatollahzadeh (2009 August, pers. com.). It is broad shallow depression with a light colored raised rim 200 m in diameter. It lies in an area of a flat desert with several meter scale relief of bedrock ridges (folds?) striking predominantly NE-SW. About 300 m north of the structure runs a curvilinear feature that cuts across the ridges (fault?) and that marks a margin of a sedimentary basin further north. Several small dry streams cut across the circular feature. Judging from the stratigraphy of rock outcrops along dry stream beds in the area and the main fault(?), the light material in the circular rim was uplifted from below the dark colored surface. A review of the satellite images within a 100 km radius revealed a fold-dominated bedrock geology and desert streams and sedimentary basins. No obvious volcanic or diapiric features show in the area, although some black to rusty colored features could be basaltic pyroclastics or knobs or an eroding bedrock. These form sharp elongated ridges, or small cones or patches unlike the circular feature reported here. Preserved geomorphology of the circular feature suggests <1 Ma age.

Ali Fatollahzadeh reported: “...I saw geographic maps of this area and the nearest salt domes are 500 Miles Away. From land it [the circular feature] seems like a small curved mountain (half circle) that is about 50 meters high and in front of that it is a (quarter circle) like mountain. A seasonal creek path crosses the circle and the places the creek crosses the circle aren't as high as surrounding mountain. The rims are rusty and it seems erosion broke the mountain rocks and small rocks shed by gravity in the middle of circle. In the center of two rounded mountains I saw a small dark area about 5-10 meters in diameter. I took samples from rims and this central area. Maybe I can get there to the geology faculty for analysis. The area is completely unpopulated and there isn’t any mountains, rivers nearby. The nearest town to the site is "Seghaleh" that means "Three Castles".”

Chatterjee et al. (2006) described Shiva structure buried in the Bombay Basin on the western shelf of India incorporating the Amirante Basin, earlier proposed impact feature. Shiva structure has been interpreted on the basis of potential fields, seismic and drilling data and ground and laboratory work. The structure has a roughly rectangular shape defined by Panvel Flexure onshore western India (eastern border), Narmada Fault in the Arabian Sea (northern border), Kori Arch (western border) and the Ratnagiri fault (southern border). The diagonal is about 500 km. Buried structural highs ~200 km in diameter are interpreted as the central peak ring. A group of elevated structures with a diameter of 550 km is considered a possible outer ring. These structural elements form a basement consisting of Neoproterozoic granites and Deccan Traps basalts. The basement is covered by Tertiary sediments (Chatterjee et al., 2006). 
Chatterjee et al. (2006) refer to several low seismic velocities and negative gravity anomalies and interpret them as evidence for fracturing of the crystalline basement.
Chatterjee et al. (2006) listed following lines of evidence for impact:
- Pseudotachylites – two optical photographs showed dark veins in the basement granite described as aphanitic, micro- to cryptocrystalline material. One SEM photographs showed what was interpreted as pure silica glass referring to energy dispersive X-ray spectra (EDXS) data (not shown). Insufficient evidence was shown that the veins were melted and that they are actual pseudotachylites. Further, pseudotachylites form at various tectonic environments and do not constitute evidence for an impact.
- Rhyolite dikes – no data were presented, only speculation that such rocks could have been formed by shock target melting.
- Geophysical anomaly – presented a map of previously published low resolution gravity map with –15 mGal central anomaly and rising to +10 to +35 mGal in the “annular trough” and wetern central ring and up to +40 mGal towards the coast. It is speculated that the elongated positive gravity high in the west is related to an igneous complex, which is further speculated to be an impact melt. No evidence was presented such interpretation.
- Geothermal anomaly – referred to a study that attributed high heat flow to crustal stretching possibly caused by a geodynamic even such as an impact. 
- Reference to reports of shocked quartz and geochemical anomalies from several K-T boundary sections in India – extensive but entirely speculative discussion of the connection between these sections, impact induced melting and the Shiva structure.
Chatterjee et al. (2006) estimated the age of the structure at ~65 Ma based on various stratigraphic considerations and assuming the impact origin of the structure and its association with reported impact evidence from various locations across India.

Other references: (Chatterjee, 1997; Pandey and Agrawal, 2000; Chatterjee, 2003)

The Middle-Ural ring structure - MURS - (Sredne-Uralskaya kolcevaya struktura) is expressed at the surface as series of highlands forming a subdued circular ridge in its northern, western and southern part. The eastern side is delineated by and arc of Ural Mts., which stands out from nearly linear trend of the Ural Mts. Two highlands occure near the center of the structure. The relative relief betweet the circular ring and the interior of the structure is 150-1600 m. Faults and rivers in the area follow radial and tangential pattern centered on the morphological ring. The structure coincides with an isometric depression in the basement reaching -8 km elevation and displaying central high of -3 km just below the central highs expressed at the surface. The structure thus appears to be of Precambrian age (Burba, 2003a,b).

Mashchak and Naumov (1996) reported a circular feature in satellite imagery, associated with –10 mGal Bouger anomaly and weakly contrasting magnetic field (data not shown). Exposed target rocks include Archean and Early Proterozoic gneises and granites. NE and SW quadrants of the structure contain erosional remnants of polymict breccia preserved in annular depression. The breccia contains fragments of the target and Early Proterozoic metavolcanites and phylites. The rocks were later metamorphosed at epidote-amphibolite facies. A few fragments with fluid textures may represent recrystallized melt (Mashchak and Naumov, 1996). Mashchak and Naumov (1996) also reported deformation in quartz and feldspar, including several sets of PDFs but the presented data do not support these claims. The poor quality photomicrographs show 2-3 sets of linear features in quartz, but many of those features are clearly non-planar and non-parallel. Many of these features are spaced ~<0.01 mm consistent with PDFs but some are spaced up to ~0.02 mm. A histogram of crystallographic orientations shows a peak around {10-13} and minor peak around {10-11}. The features may be considered PFs. Mashchak and Naumov (1996) considered that the structure is overlain by basal conglomerates of Jatulian Fm. estimated to be of 2300 Ma age and which was preceded by considerable erosion and estimated the age of the structure at 2400 Ma. Presented evidence, however, constrains the age as post Archean and pre 2300 Ma, i.e. 2500-2300 Ma (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2004). Coordinates from Google Earth based on maps in Mashchak and Naumov (1996). Diameter corresponds to the outer shore of the arcuate lakes. Earlier report in (Mashchak and Orlova, 1986). Several other researchers pointed out that they did not see anything unusual in the area and that the breccia with plannar deformation may be glacial till.
