Jensen (1971) reported several outcrops apparently shocked rocks on the sw. side of the Tâterât fjord near Agto in the west Greenland. He noted that texture of the gneisses in the area was destroyed and the gneisses were penetrated with a network of dark aphanitic veins, which he called pseudotachylites. Quartz, plagiaoclase and K-feldspars in the gneiss and in the fragments within the pseudotachylytes contain decorated and non-decorated planar elements. The rocks contain diaplectic and melt glass, with gradual trasition between the two. Felsic grains have fused rims with flow texture. Pyroxenes and amphiboles have additional planar elements, deformation twins, reduced birefringence and no pleochroism. Both mineral locally disintegrated. Garnet and apatite display plannar elements. These deformation effects are concentrated in an area of a few square kilometers but can be observed on an area of at least 30 km2 (Jensen, 1971). 1.5 km from the described area runs a thrust zone. The thrust zone extends for at least 130 km and, in the vicinity of the described area, it contains a lens of relic gneiss with a 10 m long and up to 5 cm wide hyalomylonite vein. The gneiss lens is crushed and contains many of the same features described from the nearby area. The hyalomylonite vein is parallel to the thrust and to the gneiss foliation and contains spherulites and crushed grains. Major and trace element composition of the hyalomylonite and the gneiss is very similar. Rocks beyond the discussed area show normal tectonic deformation (Jensen, 1971). 
K/Ar age of the glass is 3070 ± 70 Ma, which is at odds with generally accepted 1790-1650 Ma age of the Nagssugtôqidian mobile belt. The meaning of the K/Ar age is thus uncertain (Jensen, 1971 and references within).
Coordinates are derived from map in Jensen (1971) and Google Earth and point in roughly in the middle of the outcrops indicated in Jensen (1971). Age is broadly limited to Precambrian.

Crater like feature with a circular rim with a 13 km diameter and a central uplifted region. Relief from the bottom to the crest is greater than 400 m. Hilly uplifted terrain encircles the structure, which is situated in the Jurassic granites and surrounded by the 2 Ga old metamorphic complex of gneiss and schist. The north-south oriented Tongducheon fault cuts the structure in half (Jones et al., 1995 in Trenc et al., 1999). Kang et al. (1985 in Trenc et al., 1999) suggested that fracturing along the circular joint during cooling of the granite pluton induced formation of the structure. Jones et al. (1995 in Trenc et al., 1999) questioned the possibility of a magmatic origin for the structure and suggested that it was caused by a meteoritic impact. Trenc et al. (1999) analyzed Shuttle, Landsat TM and SPOT images and identified lineaments that mark a fault-bounded polygonal rim as well as numerous shorter lineaments with various orientations representing ridges and valleys (Trenc et al., 1999). Kwon and Sagong (1998) noted that the elevated rim coresponds to the occurence of garnet-biotite granite whereas the depression corresponds to biotite (+- hornblend) granite. They sugested that the morphological expression is due to differential weathering. They further argued that the feature represents a subvolcanic ring dike as opposed to impact structure referring to radiometric dating that indicates ~100 dg.C/Ma cooling rate and referring to geobarometry studies that indicated the depth of emplacement of ~14 km. Biotite K-Ar age for the garnet-bearing granite is 165.8 ± 2.4 Ma and for the biotite granite 164.8 ± 6.6 Ma (Yun, 1995 in Kwon and Sagong, 1998). Whole rock Rb-Sr for both granites is 167 ± 19 Ma (Kwon and Lan, 1995 in Kwon and Sagong, 1998). U-Pb sphene age of the biotite granite is 168.2 ± 6.6 Ma (Kwon and Sagong, 1998). Therefore the structure is ~165 Ma old (if magmatic) or yourger (if impact).

Kwon and Sagong (1998) called the feature the Uijongbu structure after the town outside the southern rim of the structure. This name is also adopted in this database because it is more local to the structure as opposed to originally proposed name Seoul.

Data from (Genest et al., 2005), coordinates for Chibougamau Formation originally interpreted as tillite now reinterpreted as possible impact ejecta. Associated with clastic dykes. "The first petrographic results are: 1) no PDFs have been observed yet; 2) partly molten fragments are present; 3) presence of microbreccias surrounding clasts that are within a larger breccia; 4) flow structures; 5) amygdules; and 6) presence of reduced (burned) dolomite clasts. By the present, we postulate that the Chibougamau tillite, instead of being glaciogenic, is better explained as the product of an ejecta blanket owing to an impact event, maybe the one responsible for the shatter cones observed within the stromatolitic dolomite unit of the paleoproterozoic Mistassini Basin which displays a suggestive curved geomorphic pattern." - (Genest et al., 2005).

Subsurface structure offshore Namibia revealed on 3D seismic. Oval about 20x30 km, longer axis parallel to the coast (NW-SE) (Roger Swart, pers. comm. 2006). I (D. Rajmon) briefly saw a SW-NE seismic line across the structure. The structure has a central structural high surrounded by lows on boths sides. The lows appear to be downfaulted basement blocks with normal faults dipping toward the center of the structure. The structure is overlaid by a thick package of subhorizontal reflectors dipping toward SW above the sw rim of the structure. The reflectors are truncated on the NE side of the underlying structure. The surface of the reflector package thus have a domal appearance. The seismic line also shows basement rising above the structure toward NE forming continental shelf. There is another elevated structure SW off the suspected impact structure, which R. Swart said was a sea mount. The owner of the seismic data is TGS and it may be willing to provide one 2D line for academic research (Roger Swart, pers. comm. 2006). Sintezneftegas is planning to drill a well in the structure around September 2007 (Roger Swart, pers. comm. 2006). The structure is in an area of continental rifting with many volcanic features but no salt (Roger Swart, pers. comm. 2006). The age of the structure is estimated from seismic stratigraphy at Aptian-Albian (Roger Swart, pers. comm. 2006) and calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

A circular string of a dark rock cropping out from bellow fluvial and eolian sediments noted by Marc Fokker on Google Earth. These rocks define a rim that is up to 50 m higher then the surrounding terrain. The bedrock also crops out in the center of the circular structure and a more isolated but common outcrops are scattered throughout the western half of the structure and they also stand up to a few tens of meters above the surrounding sediment. Overall the eastern half of the structure appears to be higher than the western half. The structure is not inconsitent with an impact origin but a volcanic or hydrothermal origin is also possible.

A near circular depression 230x280 m in diameter and  2-3 m deep in a dessert of the central Australia. Radially oriented dry drainage pattern confirms the DEM model of Google Earth. Individual streams reach 50-250 m beyond the rim. The rim is defined by the extend of darker color inside the crater (soil and vegetation), apparent 1m drop in elevation toward the center of the depression and overall visual impression of the crest of slightly elevated rim (even though yhe DEM does not resolve the elevation of the rim from the background). The southern and south eastern rim appears fairly straight, apparently controled by a fault or a fracture striking WSW-NE and extending outside the depression. Several other small round depressions could be related. Reported by LeoKilligrew (pers. comm., 2009), all observation from Google Earth.

A near circular depression with a central peak offshore Alaska /British Columbia (submitted by Wayne Petty). The structure is located in deep water 200 km from the shelf edge on a sediment appron mantling the shelf edge. The seafloor map on Google Earth shows major submarine channel systems carrying sediment from the shelf edge accross the sediment appron to the deep basin. The structure sits within a smooth area in between the channels. The central peak of the structure has a size and morphology similar to the Bowie hot spot sea mountains forming a trail further offshore. The structure does not fit the geographic distribution trend of these mountains and is surrounded by a distinct depression, which is not present around any of the sea mountains. Visually, the geomorphology of the structure is consistent with that of a complex impact crater. The crater morphology is, however, difficult to reconcile with the ~3 km water depth, which would likely prevent a formation of a typical crater. The clear morphology of the structure in an area of active sedimentation suggests a young age less than ~10 Ma.
Circular structure with central elevation. Could be a volcanic caldera but impact origin possible. Interpretation based on Google Earth satellite imagery.

“Mid-resolution satellite images on maps.google.com show prominent circular feature ~4.5 km in diameter with central darker core located at lat. 66.273 º and lon. 78.444 º; ~40 km north of the town of Urengoy, Tyumen district, Russia. High-resolution image does not show the structure well because it is covered under snow. The appearance of this structure is anomalous for the area and thus attracted attention. The feature makes an impression of slightly raised rim and raised central darker area. However, closer image inspection reveals that the northeastern section of the rim is defined by Bolshaya Yar’yakha river (Болшая Ярьяха) and the eastern to southern rim by its tributary placing the structure outline at a topographic low. Left bank tributaries of these rivers flow radially from the middle of the annular zone between the core and the rim of the structure. The right bank tributaries (flowing from outside of the structure) form irregular dendritic pattern. The western rim is a bit diffuse, partly defined by a string of lakes. The NW segment of the rim appears overprinted by an area with many lakes. Individual rim segments appear fairly linear defining an overall hexa- to septagonal outline. The core is 1.5 km in diameter and shows radial grooves (drainage pattern or some structural elements). It is rimmed with lakes in the NW to SW and two lakes are present on the west central part of the core. The digital elevation model on Google Earth indicates the highest elevation (40-44 m above sea level) in the SE segment of the annulus (consistent with the radial drainage). From there, the elevation drops outward toward the river (37-38 m asl) and inward (37-38 m asl) and the whole western half of the structure is sloping down toward west (25-30 m asl along the western rim).” - Rajmon (2009)

Regional geology
“The structure is located within the West Siberian basin, a prolific hydrocarbon producer. The supergiant Urengoy gas field is located about 60 km west of the circular structure. The basin was established on crystalline Archean and Proterozoic basement. The basement is overlain by a widely, but not completely, metamorphosed and folded Paleozoic units. These units are bounded by a major regional unconformity associated with Hercynian uplift during the Permian. The top of the Paleozoic section is 6.5-7.5 km below surface at the Urengoy field. Late Permian through Early Triassic extension created north-south trending rifts. The largest of these rifts is the Koltogor-Urengoy rift system, which extends for 1200-1300 km from the southeast of the city of Nezhevartovsk to, and under, the Taz gulf in the north. This rift system bounds the Urengoy field anticline and runs under the circular feature. The deposition in the rifts resumed with siliciclastics and volcaniclastics capped by the ~250 Ma flood basalts.  The sedimentation then continued through several cycles of continental, lacustrine and marine siliclastics through Mesozoic and Cenozoic. Notable within these sequences are the deep marine organic rich Upper Jurassic Bazhenov shales, the principal source rocks within the basin. Besides siliciclastics, coal deposits occur within the Lower Jurassic, the Albian-Cenomanian Pokur Formation and in the Oligocene. Thin limestone beds occur in the western part of the basin within Aptian-Cenomanian and marls occur throughout Aptian-Eocene. Much of the Oligocene-Miocene sediments were eroded during Pliocene. The Mesozoic to Cenozoic sediments have been periodically deformed along the rejuvenated linear basement structures. Significant transpressional deformation affected the whole basin in early Oligocene generating uplifts, inverted structures, broad anticlinal structures and positive flower structures. Near surface faults in the region around the circular feature are trending NW-SE with vertical and right lateral offsets. Associated extension and Riedel fractures are trending NE-SW and N-S (Grace and Hart, 1990; Galushkin et al., 1999; Vyssotski et al., 2006). Quaternary fluvial and lacustrine deposits overlie the erosional surface of Eocene-Oligocene sediments. Meandering rivers and thermokarst lakes dominate the surface geomorphology.” - Rajmon (2009)
“The circular structure is located on a regional N-S trending positive gravity and magnetic anomalies corresponding to the Permian graben structures. The resolution of these regional potential fields data is too coarse to resolve the 4.5 km circular feature.” - Rajmon (2009)

Interpretation
“The geologic reviews of the area cited above mention no recent igneous activity, no salt, no carbonate karst and no shale diapirism. The geomorphology suggests the circular feature is too large and established for some time for it to be of thermokarst or nuclear explosion origin. The author is not aware of any glacial or periglacial feature consistent with the discussed circular feature. The closest periglacial feature could be a collapsed pingo although the core of the discussed feature is ~2.5 times larger than the 600 m diameter of the largest known pingo (Anderson, 2006). Transpressional tectonic origin is possible although the unique character of the feature in a wider area and a distinct central symmetry reduce the probability of such origin. The proximity of major oil and gas accumulations demands consideration of origin via gas eruption. In that case, other similar features would be expected in the area, possibly arranged along faults. No such features can be observed on satellite images and were not mentioned in the above geological reviews. The nature of the feature is consistent with impact origin and there is no information currently available to the author arguing against such origin. The polygonal outline of the feature indicates the regional faults controlled its formation to some extend.” - Rajmon (2009)

Age
“The circular pattern appears to control recent drainage and appears to be overprinted by periglacial geomorphology. This suggests pre-Holocene age. The feature manifests itself in the surface units, which could be Pleistocene or pre-erosion Eocene-Oligocene deposits. The age of the feature thus can be tentatively constrained to Eocene-Pleistocene or 55.8-0.0115 Ma (calibrated with Gradstein et al., 2006).” - Rajmon (2009)

Tektite context
“Interestingly, the structure is located ~50 and 80 km ENE of two locations where three fragments of natural glass described as tektites "urengoyites" were found and reported by Masaitis et al. (1988). The discussed feature was, in fact, discovered unexpectedly while trying to determine the field coordinates of the reported tektites.” - Rajmon (2009)

The satellite imagery shows drilling sites on the structure.

A round depression on the northern bank of the R.L. Harris Reservoir on the Little Tallapoosa River reported by Robert Stanley (Stan) Muse, Donald (Don) Matthew Muse (2009, pers. comm). The rim is ~100x150 m in diameter elongated in the NE-SW direction and has a variable height above the depression floor - 5 m in the south on the sloping river bank and 14 m in the north where the surrounding land surface is roughly horizontal. The depression appears anomalous in the regional geomorphological pattern as represented on the Google topographic map. Its appearance and position suggests a fairly recent (Quaternary) age. Elevation measurements and latitude, longitude 33.38855, -85.46945 (WGS84) from Google Earth. "Named after the town of 'Wedowee' (town was named after an American Indian Chief of the same name)... The entire area is covered with very dense foliage. The feature is definitely not man-made. We found some upturned rocks and boulders. We found many exposed quarts rocks ranging from fist size to bowling ball size. Exposed quarts was not found in other areas of close proximity.  We brought back some quartz samples which appeared to be fractured, however this could have been done in tool making by American Creek Indians who lived in the area. Therefore, findings at this time are inconclusive." (R.S. Stan and D.M. Muse, 2009, pers. comm.)

Lower Permian shales and limestones of the Lueder Formation are uplifted ~75 m and exposed at the surface penetrating otherwise flat-lying Permian shales also belonging to the Lueders Fm. and sandstones . The structure is accompanied by mostly radial faulting and folding. The exposed beds dip radially away from the center at 37 to 68 dg. Well drilling constrains the deformation above the depth of 370 m. The lobate bed exposure pattern has a maximum diameter 460 m. A structural map based on sparse wells drilled in the area indicates ~3.2 km diameter and also indicated a syncline to the SE of the uplift and tangentially elongated to the structure (Hughes, 1932). Hughes (1932) considered compressional origin, differential compaction around a steep volcanic cone and a deep or shallow volcanic intrusion. He rejected all of those hypotheses and interpreted the structure as a result of shale diapirism. Monnig (1963) proposed impact origin of the structure although he did not find any shatter cones.

If the mapped syncline represents annular trough of an impact structure the diameter of the whole structure could be 4.5-6 km. The age of the structure is post Lower Permian Lueder Fm. The age limit chosen for the database is base Permian and calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004). The coordinates have been identified based on information in Hughes (1932).

von Frese et al. (2006) reported gravity high in the GRACE satellite data 320 km in diameter centered in a circular ridge 480 km in diameter defined by satellite radar data. They estimated the age of the feature at ~250 Ma without any reasoning. Wide uncertainty is therefore asigned here between 100 Ma (rifting, last continental scale crustal event in that part of Antarctica) and ~2.5 Ga (age of appreciable amount of crust on the Earth).
This structure is roughly collocated but different from Wilkes Land 1. See Gorder (2006) for interview and images.

One of the structures identified by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) on X-SAR images. No particular reasons other than appearance on radar and visible light images provided to support an impact origin. Age estimated by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) based on geological and geographical considerations without further specification. Location of the crater verified by D.Rajmon through personal communication with R. Gorelli and coordinates obtained from Google Earth (D.Rajmon). Diameter from (Gorelli, 1998a, b). Observations by David Rajmon on Google Earth: The feature is a broad topographic high on a coastal plain surrounded by a circular valley, with two streams flowing from SW side of the structure around the topographic high in opposite directions. The relative relief between the valley and the structure center is ~20 m. The diameter of the valley is ~16 km. Another feature with very similar characteristics is immediately to the SE (lat 31.233, lon 15.769) and with a diameter  8.5 km. I could not find any other similar structure. These features, however, do not show any other characteristics pointing toward impact origin and they could just be a result of interplay of regional tectonic style and river erosion.

Circular depression noted by S. Hamilton as a possible impact crater (2007, pers. comm.) The depression has a rim-rim diameter of ~2.8 km with an alongation in the NE quadrant. The rim is raised 1-3 m above the surrounding terrain. The interior is filled with evaporite deposites and and a lake, which is ~10 m below the rim. Observations from Google Earth. Assuming impact origin and considering the degree of preservation the structure could be of Cenozoic age.

The structure is defined by a low irregular circular ridge separating inside shallow basin drained toward northwest and a radial drainage outside the ridge. The ridge is ~1.5 km in diameter and the zone with the radial drainage is ~3-4 km in diameter. P. Johnson (2010, pers. comm.) proposed it could be a central part of an impact structure and called it Abimily. The structure is situated in mostly flat-lying terrain of the Cambrian Amadeus Basin, on the borderline of C1-C3 formations (dolostone, limestone, sandstone, shale and conglomerate) (P. Johnson, 2010, pers. comm. citing Ahmad and Scrimgeour, 2006). Mapping indicates a gravity signature  1000 to 1500 um/s² for the region (based on ground stations)  (P. Johnson, 2010, pers. comm. citing Clifton, 2009), and total magnetic intensity appears neutral  (P. Johnson, 2010, pers. comm. citing Ahmad and Scrimgeour, 2006; Clifton, 2009). However, the stratigraphy in the rim and in the inner hills (as observed on the satellite images on Google Earth) is fairly consistent and flat or gently dipping. It suggests the structure is a core of a syncline, hence fairly continuous strata cropping out at the hills in the structure. The gray layer appears to be more resistant than the brown layers and it protected the softer rock below. Where it was cut by erosion the underlying layer washes away, hence the sloping surface outside the gray rim. It is consistent with the tectonic deformation in that region. A disturbed bedding one would expect if it were a central uplift of an impact structure is not visible.

References:
Ahmad M and Scrimgeour IR, 2006. Geological map of the Northern Territory, 1:2 500 000 scale. Northern Territory Geological Survey, Darwin. Online: http://www.nt.gov.au/d/Minerals_Energy/Geoscience/Content/File/nt_geological_map2006.pdf , accessed 14 January 2010.
Clifton R, 2009. Gravity map of the Northern Territory, 1:2 500 000 scale. Northern Territory Geological Survey, Darwin. Online: http://www.nt.gov.au/d/Minerals_Energy/Geoscience/Content/File/nt_gravity_map.pdf  accessed 14 January 2010.

A circular wooded crest with a central basin proposed by H. Sørensen (2009, pers. comm.) as a possible impact structure. The elevation of the crest varies from 220 to 320 m a.s.l., the basin floor is at ~185 m a.s.l., surounding valleys are are at ~100-115 m a.s.l.. The feature lies on a southward continuation of a fold axis and is surounded by multiple other hills apparently related to the regional tectonic trends. Harz Mountains are a few kilometers to the east. The geomorphological context suggests a volcanic or tectonic origin. The feature is crosed by a railway tunnel. All data from Google Earth.

Circular structure reported by Paillou et al. (2003) as a confirmed impact crater.  The structure occurs in Lower Cretaceous sandstones indicating <140 Ma (Paillou et al., 2003). Cited evidence for impact includes “shatter cones” close to the northeastern inner ridge and pointing to the center of the structure, breccia and “planar fractures” (Paillou et al., 2003). 

Review of the satellite images and digital elevation model on Google Earth and in Paillou et al. (2003) reveals multiple concentric ridges and troughs with a central region containing outcrops of dark rocks. The northwestern quadrant is cut by a NE trending linear zone of sand dunes. Two smaller circular structures with similar dark rocks in the center are located 32 and 25 km to the SW and a number of ~0.5 km sized structures occur in the area. This spatial association suggest an endogenic origin of the Arkenu 1 structure. The presented “shatter cones” (Paillou et al., 2003, fig. 6) could represent wind ablation features common in desserts. Incidentally, all photographs show only cone-shaped polished surfaces, none shows cones on freshly broken inner surface as could be expected for shatter cones. All studied cones are located in the NE quadrant of the structure, thus the pointing of their apexes toward the structure center is also consistent with the direction of prevailing winds indicated by the sand dunes in the area. The presence of breccia is also consistent with non-impact, possibly endogenic, origin. The reported planar fractures are not planar in fact (see Paillou et al., 2003, fig. 8) and PFs are not considered diagnostic shock features (French, 1998). The reported structure has been considered likely carbonatite complex of endogenic origin (Reimold, 2007 referring to personal communication).

Regan and Marsh (1982) reported a long-wave length magnetic anomaly in satellite magnetometer data in the vicinity of Bangui, Central African Republic; supported by analysis of air and ground magnetic surveys. They also reported a correlative gravity anomaly in ground gravity data. They noted that the anomaly, in an area of highly metamorphosed Precambrian rocks, does not correlate with any surficial features but is definitely crustal in origin and interpreted the anomaly as the result of an early intrusion into the crustal rocks of this region, followed by subsidence and deformation.  (Girdler et al., 1992) sugested impact origin combining topography, magnetic and gravity data and other geologic considerations. (Antoine et al., 1999) weakened the relationship of magnetic anomaly to the circular topography based on reprocessed magnetic data, which show that the anomaly continues and opens southwestward into Atlantic Ocean. DeCarli et al. (2002) argued that an impact of Bangui's size would trigger a decompression melting and a large scale volcanism that is not observed in this case.
Several other papers and abstracts on the Bangui anomaly can be found on NASA ADS.
Age from Girdler et al. (1992). Listed by (Moilanen, 2004) and (Fortes, 2000); both with wrong coordinates.

Stinchcomb (2005) proposed that a series of aligned hills capped by chert breccia - Nichols Knob, Big Yoeman, Blue Buck, Dyestone Mt., - represent remnants of four contemporaneous impact craters. The breccias are supposedly fallback or autochtonous breccia cemented by silica forming resistant cap preventing erosion. Coordinates read from topographic map. Considering that 1) no other evidence other than brecciation was presented, 2) no theoretical or observed evidence support existence of crater chains on the Earth, and 3) a number of other similar knobs can be identified on topographic map in the area,  the impact origin of these features appears unlikely.

(Eriksson et al., 1994) considered petrography and geochemistry of interbeded sandstones and felsites of Rooiberg Felsite Group and found it compatible with both impact and non-impact scenario. "Absence of high-pressure shock metamorphic effects, pseudotachylites, and impact and fallback breccias, cited by French (1990), constitutes important evidence against an impact origin for the Rooiberg felsites" - (Eriksson et al., 1994). A number of small pre-impact intrusive bodies with Bushveld age also occur within the collar of the Vredefort structure, 150 km south of the main Bushveld body (Graham et al., 2005). Lake in massive and layered quartz monzonite and granodiorite of Archean age, metamorphosed at 2.4 Ga and mylonitized at 2.445 Ga (Ermanovicz et al., 1972). Post 2.445 Ga breccia veins and pseudotachylite occur on the north shore (Ermanovicz et al., 1972). Listed as suspected impact structure by (Moilanen, 2004) without further information. The pseudotachylite and brecia zone is 22 m wide and 100 long and occurs along a mylonite zone, which extends 50 km (Ermanovicz et al., 1972). Coordinates from Google Earth based on a map in (Ermanovicz et al., 1972). Age is constrained by the pre-existing mylonitization event at 2445±70 Ma (K-Ar). The diameter is for the lake.

Zvonaric (1996) observed a circular pattern on Landsat images 20-50 km in diameter centered on the Lokve Lake near the town of Lokve, within the area of Gorski kotar, western Croatia. Zvonaric speculated that the impact occured in a shallow Cretaceous/Tertiary sea and that post impact erosion and later tectonic activity modified the structure. He mentioned a lack of impactites and suggested that they may be preserved in sinkholes. Zvonaric observed core with tilted Palaeozoic beds from Crni Lug-1 well and considered them to be "a typical profile of the astroblema". Inspection of the satellite images and morphology revealed subdued possible circular pattern in the described area. Considering the character of Zvonaric's observations and discussion, there appears to be no evidence for impact.

Size from (Brookfield, 2003), age from (EID, 2006), coordinates read from Google Earth. (Brookfield, 2003, 2006) reiterated that (Beals, 1968) proposed impact origin of the Hudson Bay coastal arc with a coherent upraised rim forming 155 dg arc and basin filled with Proterozoic sediments, and referred to (Goodings and Brookfield, 1992), who noticed that Sutton ridge can be structurally restored to a position aligned with the Hudson Bay arc and thus exdending the Hudson Arc to 240 dg. in the southwest. (Brookfield, 2003, 2006) mentions pseudotachylites, monomict and polymict breccias associated with faults along the Hudson Arc and, in absence of any other satisfactory hypothesis, allows the possibility of Hudson Bay being an impact structure with a minimum diameter 450 km. The best fit circle has a diameter 230 km (Brookfield, 2003, 2006). (EID, 2006) refers to work of Geological Survey of Canada, which found "no evidence of shock metamorphism or any indication that it might have been produced by an impact event. The Belcher Islands, which are often suggested as representing a central uplift, consist of a series of metasediments, unfractured and unbrecciated, from a higher stratigraphic level than the surrounding basement rocks outcropping on the shores of Hudson Bay. One would expect that the central uplift be composed of fractured and brecciated rocks from lower stratigraphic levels if Hudson Bay were an impact structure. Moreover, these sediments have been folded and thrusted during the Paleoproterozoic Orogeny (~1.85-1.80 Ga) by extremely slow tectonic processes quite incompatible with the rapid events that accompany impacts. Hudson Bay is still isostatically adjusting after retreat of the ice cover and it appears fortuitous that is has a circular form." Other reference:  (Wilson, 1968).

A round depression 19-96 m deep in limestone. There are several other round depressions 60-150 m in diameter occuring within a 5 km distance (Daniele Scagnoli, pers. comm., 2007). They are aligned along a valley that is probably marking a major SW-NE striking fault. The depth to diameter ratio of the depressions (data from Daniele Scagnoli, pers. comm., 2007) is generally greater than simple impact craters typically show. This all suggests that the depressions are karst features (sink holes). The rusty looking dense rocks reported within the area (Daniele Scagnoli, pers. comm., 2007, one photo showing crystal faces) appear to be pyrite or haematite.

Luobusa ophiolite, located in Tibet 110 km ESE of Lhasa, contains harzburgites, dunites and podiform chromitites. The chromites contain unusual mineral assemblages, including diamond, moissanite, Fe-silicides, wüstite, Ni-Fe-Cr-C alloys, PGE alloys and octahedral Mg-Fe silicates, native elements, including Si, Fe, Ni, Cr and graphite. The diamonds sizes range from micrometers to 0.5 mm (Robinson et al., 2004; Yang et al., 2007). Yang et al., 2007  reported polycrystalline coesite pseudomorphing after stishovite. The commonly accepted origin of the ophiolite is that it formed originally at a mid-ocean ridge (MOR) spreading centre at 177±33 Ma, and was later modified by suprasubduction zone magmatism at about 126 Ma. The chromitites formed in the suprasubduction zone environment from boninitic melts reacting with the host peridotites. The UHP minerals are believed to have been transported from the lower mantle by a plume and incorporated in the ophiolite during seafloor spreading at 176 Ma. Blocks of the mantle containing the UHP minerals were presumably picked up by the later boninitic melts, transported to shallow depth and incorporated in the chromitites during crystallization. The ophiolite experienced intraoceanic thrusting at 90-80 Ma and was finally exhumed and emplaced in the Early Neogene (Robinson et al., 2004 and references within). Yang et al., 2007  considered impact origin of the high pressure minerals but noted that there is no other evidence for an impact and prefered the magmatic/tectonic hypothesis. If an impact was indeed a part of the ophiolite geologic history it occurred during or after the chromite formation at 126 Ma and before the ophiolite emplacement. Early/Late Neogene boundary calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2004).

properties.Notes: "A circular depression 1.7 km in diameter and 6-10m deep (measured from SRTM files with 3DEM software) on the Mangueni plateau of the North Niger. The structure is covered by sand and sandstone fragments. The Mangueni plateau (Plateau de Mangueni) is a part of  a large intracratonic sedimentary basin, the Murzuq basin. The basin is floored by Archean and Proterozoic basement rocks of the East Saharan craton. It is filled with Cambrian to Carboniferous marine sediments and continental Jurassic to Cretaceous sediments. The structure is thus Cretaceous or younger. There are no volcanics in the vicinity. Used tools: google maps, SRTM files, Geology of Egypt and Libya (google books)." - Krisztián Klajnik (2009, 2010 pers. comm.). The multiring morphology at such a small diameter suggests non-impact origin (D. Rajmon).

A circular depression delineated by a sharp circular and slightly polygonal rim. The rim does not rise above the surrounding terrain (judging from the Google Earth elevation data). He bottom of the depression is 20 m lower than the rim and is filled with playa deposit. The northern part of the structure from the rim to about 40% distance to the center is occupied by a brown rock which loks the same and is at the same elevation as the surrounding terrain. This rock is separated from the surrounding terrain by a rim crack. The crack is visible as greenish zone with 1 m lower elevation than the brown rock on both sides of the crack. The material inside the circular depression also has a green color and appears to underlie the brown rock regionally. The circular structure is located inside a large fold. It appears conspicuously different from the regional folding pattern but a closer look at a more subtle features of the closing fold suggest that the circular structure is located right in the structural center of the closing fold. The circular depression is inconsistent with expected excavation if it was formed by an impact. The epression rather appears to be a result of a collaps, perhaps due to salt withdrawal or dissolution.

A round structure defined by perfect half-circle scarp 12 km in diameter, a more irregular remaining round rim 16 km in diameter, central elevation 5-6 km in diameter extending also further north. The central elevation reaches max elevation 2960 m asl, the rim elevation is ~2500 m asl, the annular depression in between varies around ~2000-2500 m asl. Bedding in the central high can be traced over long distance and appears gently inclined - rather inconsistent with an impact structure uplift or a volcano.

Submitted circular feature with rim defined by stream valleys in the SW, S to E. Center of the structure elevated shows the same bedrock as around the structure. A ridge of folded strata exposed immediately north of the structure and multiple smaller ridges of a dark rock are cropping out south of the main ridge, partly encroaching and crosscutting expected circular northern half of the circular structure. The small ridges follow the paten of folding in the region. The structure is likely a result of interaction of fluvial erosion and rock folding.
Circular structure. Likely an eroded volcanic feature since it occurs within a volcanic terrain. Interpretation based on Google Earth satellite imagery.

properties.Notes: Impact origin proposed by E. González on the basis of morphology as visible on satellite images (Google Earth/Map). Observations by D.Rajmon: Two concentric oval ridges separated by a through. The outer ridge has a diameter ~5 km. Subdued concentric pattern extends beyond the outer ridge with maximum diameter ~11 km. There are several other similar structures (appearance and size) in the area to the west and north. Some of them are associated with regional fracture pattern radially and tangentially oriented around them strongly suggesting origin via loading of crust with massive volcanoes. Some are associated with what appears to be dykes. There are also many smaller and much less eroded volcanic cones to the west of Uri. The Uri structure does appear to be an eroded volcano. All data derived from Google Earth/Map images, unpublished.

An oval depression 3x5 km in diameter proposed to be an impact crater by Marks et al. (1972) in Lambert et al. (1980) based on occurence of vitreous rocks in the center of the depression and lack of better explanation. The center of the depression is filled with undisturbed flat-lying clays, gypsiferrous clays and sand, probably derived from the surrounding foulded formations and probably deposited in a lake. Lambert et al. (1980) found no evidence of disturbance, fracturing or breccia nor any shock effects in the exposed walls. The found more outcrops of the crystalline rocks and interpreted them as small diabase dikes subjected to a retrograde metamorphism and cross cutting the young lake sediments. There are no fused clasts in the dikes and the outcrops occur on a line suggesting magmatic origin. The feature could be purely erosional or a result of a karst collapse perhaps of Upper Tertiary age (Lambert et al., 1980). Alternate name from Mikheeva (2006) referring to Valter and Gurov (1979). Lat/long in Lambert et al. (1980) is inaccurate and in Mikheeva is 4 dg far too north. The coordinates used here are from Google Earth.

Circular depresion ~35 m deep with nearly vertical walls. Another circular depresion ~230 m in diameter and ~10 m deep known as the Little Basin is located east of the Big basin. The St. Jacob Well inside the Little basin is a funnel shaped depression 18 m deep. The depressions are thought to be sinkholes caused by salt and gypsum dissolution, still active today (Kansas Geological Survey, 2005; Kansas Dept. of Wildlife and Parks, 2010). Formed in the Permian red beds (Stoeser et al., 2007). Cannon (1995,1997) noted another depression ~300 m in diameter, likely the one adjacent to the SW rim of the Big Basin. Cannon (1997) claimed that the depressions are isolated features, the beds in the rim of the Big Basin dip away from the center and that tektites occur outside the depression. Cannon (1997) proposed that the threee depressions are of impact origin and estimated their age at 80-100 ka based on the extend of erosion. However, Kansas Geological Survey (2005) summary of the geology of the Red Hills states that sinkholes are a common feature in the Red Hills area and quotes a few thousand years age of the two basins.

Several hundred thousand eliptical depressions on coastal plains of eastern USA with long axis oriented mostly NW-SE and diameters ranging from a few hundred meters to 9 km, typically 1-4 km. A large number of hypotheses have been developed to explain their origin including meteorite impacts. Kaczorowski (1977) showed that the morphology of these depressions is too shallow for an impact structure. Seismic data and rocks show no structural disturbance; magnetic anomalies exist near some of the depressions and not at others; the magnetic anomalies are offset from the depressions and if an iron meteorite was responsible for them, the meteorite would have to be buried many hundreds to a couple kilometers deep and would have to be 165-500 m in diameter. Drilling at at least one magnetic anomaly found no iron. No meteorite fragments were ever found. Basal lake sediment C14 ages at various lakes range from 6 ka to 50 ka (references in Kaczorowski, 1977). Luminescence dating by Ivester et al. (2002, 2003, 2004a, and 2004b) indicates that the depressions formed between 70,000 to 120,000 years ago.
Numerous websites can be found on the internet discussing the depressions. Extensive literature overview can be found in, e.g., Kaczorowski (1977) and Ross (1987).

A circular crater, about 4 kilometers in diameter found by El-Baz (1981) in Landsat images among the linear dunes of the Great Sand Sea, Egypt. "The crater lies on Nubia series sandstone, it has a sharp and crenulated rim crest, a terraced wall, a discontinuous inner structure (approximately 1.6 kilometers in diameter), and a few rim blocks". El-Baz (1981) noted partial erosion of the rim, rough textured deposit up to 2 km beyond the rim in the NE qudrant and mentioned that the structure could be an impact crater or a diorite intrusion (El-Baz, 1981). 

The structure is essentially delimited by basaltic dikes intruded into the bedrock (Barakat, 1994 in Orti et al., 2008) The basalt exposed at the rim shows wind erosional striations at its surface reminiscent of shatter cones (Orti et al., 2008). 

Unaware of the Barakat’s (1994) work, Rajmon and Shaulis (2007) investigated the structure using the satellite images and elevation data on Google Earth. They did not find any evidence for terraces in the wall. The rim appears rather irregular in a map view and rounded in a side view, particularly SE quadrant could be described as lobate (3 lobes). They found the geomorphologic characteristics of the El-Baz structure inconsistent with impact origin. Instead, they found it similar to other structures in the area and consistent with other origin such as volcanic or hydrothermal (Rajmon and Shaulis, 2007). 

Various papers mentioning the Nubian sandstone place it in the Lower Cretaceous, the base of the lower Cretaceous calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2006) thus sets the maximum age of the structure at 145 Ma. Coordinates accuracy improved on Google Earth.

Rossi (2002) found a circular feature on ASTER images. Subcircular inner crater is bound by an apparently concentric deformed region, Cambro-Ordovician bedrock, bordered by NE-SW elongated sand dunes. Possible secondary small crater 2 km towards N. Partially covered with sand dunes (Rossi, 2002). Orti et al (2008) pointed out that the geologic characteristics of this structure are very similar to that of the Tarek and other structures in the Gilf Kebir area of southern Egypt. The bedrock in this area consists of porous sandstone over crystalline Precambrian basement. Numerous linear to arcuate mineralized fractures and faults are selectively preserved from erosion and exposed at the surface. Wind abrasion striations reminiscent of shatter cones are present in the area. No evidence of impact related rocks was found (Rossi, 2002). The impact origin thus appears unlikely.

Age limit chosen at the base of Cambrian and calibrated with Gradstein et al. (2006).

Coordinates from Google Earth based on McHone and Greeley (1997) and Sørensen and Bauer (2003), diameter from (Storzer et al., 1971a). Semicircular basin on the west wall of the Otztaler-Ache valley, bound by Maurach barrier in the east thought to be a massive ladslide. A pumice-like material known since 1863; volcanic and impact origin proposed (Storzer et al., 1971a and referrences within). (Kurat and Richter, 1969) described inequilibrium melting in a fussed sample from Koefels and concluded it was formed by an impact. (Storzer et al., 1971a) obtained fission-track age for a fussed rock sample 8.0 ± 6.0 × 10^3 yr consistent with geological and C-14 results. "Lechatelierite, feldspar glasses and probable chaoite in 'Köfelsite' prove that temperatures far above those common for igneous processes existed at the time of formation. The presence of the tomorphic quartz, maskelynite and multiple sets of planar features in quartz and feldspars strongly indicates shock metamorphism" - (Storzer et al., 1971a). (Storzer et al., 1971b) is an abstract and (Storzer et al., 1972) is an erratum of (Storzer et al., 1971a). (Surenian, 1989) reported cleavage in quartz from gneiss and lechtelierite from a pumice-like glass (without providing credible evidence) and concluded that the Koefels slide was triggered by an impact. C. Koeberl reanalyzed the reported plannar features in quartz and found them to be tectonic deformation, not PDFs (Deutsch et al., 1994). Formation of these plannar features was discussed by Leroux and Doukhan (1993). Radar observation without image in (McHone and Greeley, 1997). (Kubik et al., 1998) assumed landslide origin and used material from Koefels to calibrate 10Be and 26Al production rates. (Kubik et al., 1998) refers to (Ivy-Ochs et al., 1998) for the error-weighted mean radiocarbon age 8750±25 years corresponding to the calibrated age (calendar age) of 9800±100 years relative to the year 1995. Erismann and Abele (2001, chap. 2.4) summarized history of investigation at Köfels and the field, theoretical and experimental evidence that shows the Köfels to be a landslide with a frictional melt. Original work documenting the landslide origin of Köfels feature include Erismann (1977), Erismann et al. (1977), Masch et al. (1985), Sørensen and Bauer (2003), and Hermanns et al. (2006). Early structure description by (Suess, 1936). SIR-C radar observation in (McHone and Greeley, 1997). Other referrences to earlier geological studies and C14 dating in (Storzer et al., 1971a).

Listed by Classen (1977) as doubtful referring to Hofmann (1973) and noting possible relationship to Ries and with coordinates within the lake. Also listed by Mikheeva (2006) as probable impact structure Bodenzeye referring to Valter and Gurov (1979). Inspection of satelite images and digital elevation model on Google Earth reveals that the lake is located on the northern edge of the Alps in a mouth of a major valley (Rhine Valley). The valley shows a wide floor with broad arcuate ridges across the valey. This is a typical geomorphology for a glacial valley filled with moraines (glacial deposits. The morains frequently form natural dams for glacial lakes. Lake Constance fits glacial depositional and orogenic structural patterns and shows no structural evidence for impact. The lake thus most probably formed during the last glaciation, which ended at ~10 ka. The glacial origin during Würm (24-10 ka) is indeed the generally accepted interpretation (see e.g. Wikipedia for more information). Other names: Lac de Constance, Lago di Costanza, Lago Bodanico, Bodensee.

The Richat structure consists of nested circular ridges of upturned rocks ~40 km in diameter and a central elevated core. It is is located in the Mauritanian part of the Sahara Desert, within the Proterozoic Taoudenni Basin that is bounded by the Man and Reguibat basements of Archean age (Monod and Pomerol, 1973 in Matton et al., 2005). It was originally considered of endogenic origin (references in Master and Karfunkel, 2001  and Matton et al., 2005) but the crater-like shape, the presence of kilometer-scale breccia and the discovery of coesite led Cailleux et al. (1964a) to impact interpretation (also see references in Master  and Karfunkel, 2001 and Dietz et al., 1969). Dietz et al., 1969 visited the structure and found no structural evidence for explosive activity and no megascopic or microscopic evidence for shock metamorphism, and concluded that the structure has an endogenic origin. Fudali (1969) investigated concentrates from the Richat breccia by optical and x-ray means and demonstrated that the supposed x-ray reflections of coesite are actually due to barite, introduced into the permeable crushed zone by groundwater.
Master and Karfunkel (2001), apparently still assuming existence of coesite at the Richat Dome, proposed the coesite and breccia origin via lightning strikes that superheated water in the sediment and that led to pressures of >3.5 GPa.
The field and petrographic studies of Matton et al. (2002) led to the conclusion that the chert breccia at Richat was formed by a process of syngenetic karst-dissolution collapse. The most likely interpretation is that the Richat chert was formed during a shelf high-stand and persisted in a sub-emergent setting from the Proterozoic up to the Cretaceous. Thus, the Richat chert appears to be an indication of a long term high-standing structural position. Matton et al. (2005) considered doming and the production of hydrothermal fluids instrumental in creating a favorable setting for dissolution. The circular Richat structure and its breccia core represent the superficial expression of a Cretaceous alkaline complex with an exceptionally well preserved hydrothermal karst infilling at its summit.

(Cordier et al., 1994) studied deformations in quartz via optical and TEM microscopy and concluded they were of tectonic origin. (Vrána, 1988) linked deposition of moldavites with the structure depression, reported elevated Cr and Ni in microgranodiorite dykes, unpublished K-Ar age of the dykes 228-277 Ma from Jessberger and Buzek. (Vrána, 1989b) described petrology and geochemistry of microgranodiorite dykes from the structure, which he believed were impact melt; reported lechatelierite. (Vrána, 1989a) re-published the same petrology and geochemistry work.  (Vrána, 1990a) again presented the dykes. (Vrána, 1990b) presented dykes from Ševětín as an example of features preserved in deeply eroded structures. (Vrána et al., 1993) is a full scale paper on the dykes suggesting impact origin. (Kopecký, 1997; Malecha and Suk, 1997) oppossed the impact hypothesis and called for cryptoexplosive origin. The geochemistry of the microgranodiorite dykes from the structure suggest crustal origin with possible mantle component; Ar/Ar age 272 ±2 Ma, probably related to early phase of E-W tectonic extension in the region (Košler et al., 2001). (Vrána, 2004) studied dykes in the Sušice structure and drew relationship to dykes in the Ševětín structure. The dykes were not considered of impact origin but rather volcanic.

Paillou et al. (2004) reported crater field with at least 50 circular structures 75 km × 60 km (23º10' N–23º40' N and 26º50' E–27º35' E) and studied 13 craters 20-1300m in diameter with possible shatter cones and planar structures in quartz.  Heggy et al. (Heggy et al., 2005) studied some of them with GPR.  Breccia has been observed at this particular crater. Paillou et al. (2006) identified total of 1312 crater-like structures on satellite images and visited additional 49 structures. All 62 visited structures are named and numbered GKCF xx, their diameters range from 10 m to 2120 m.  They reported raised rims, breccias at most of the studied structures and shatter cone-like features and subplanar microdeformation in quartz grains at some of the structures. All structures are filled with recent sediments; some were imaged with ground penetrating radar, which showed perturbed bedrock (sandstone, siltstone) below the sediments. Paillou et al. (2006) considered hydrothermal and impact origin for the structures. They found the hydrothermal hypothesis consistent with the sizes of the craters but they pointed out that there was no known magmatic activity in the region that could be responsible for this type of hydrothermal venting. They considered subsurface structure and circular as opposed to oval shape of the craters is iconsistent with hydrothermal origin. They found the planar microdeformations in quartz, shatter cone-like features and breccias consistent with impact origin but recognized that it is an insufficient evidence. They also noted that the area covered with these crater-form structures is much larger than other known impact crater fields but thought this could be explained by an impact of a rubble-pile asteroid. 

Di Martino et al. (2006) argued that the shatter cone-like features are clearly wind-born with directions aligned with prevailing wind orientation and the features crosscutting the breccia.

Orti et al. (2008) studied several of these structures (GKCF 1, 6-8, 11-13, GKS 1-3) and found:
- the breccias are intraformational within sandstones 
- no shock evidence in the breccias and no difference between rocks inside and outside the structures,
- sandstone bedding is undisturbed in the rims of these structures remaining either horizontal or regionally gently inclined 
- shatter cone –like features are surface wind abrasion striations affecting both clasts and matrix of the breccia and consistent with dominant wind directions.
- the pervasive alteration and impregnation of rocks with iron oxides/hydroxides and sulfides, and local or regional association of the structures with volcanic rocks strongly suggests origin vial hydrothermal venting. 

Age:
The structure occure on Albian formations and some are cut by basalt dykes of likely 46 Ma age. The structures thus formed within 112-46 Ma (Paillou et al., 2006). If the structures are of hydrothermal origin, the present day shape would be a smaller erosional remnant of originally larger structures. If the structures are of impact origin, the structures had to be buried rapidly to preserve the smallest (~10 m) ones. Considering the depositional/erosive history of the region, the age of the structures would most likely be 100-94 Ma (Paillou et al., 2006). Considering the hydrothermal interpretation, the features could have formed fairly recently. The youngest magmatic activity Orti et al. (2008) cited in the southern Egypt occurred in Lower Oligocene. The likely age of these structures thus could be 112-28 Ma.

All data from Paillou et al. (2006). The field was initially listed in this database under the structure name Gihan (GKCF03), which was the largest structure identified at the time. It is now listed under the name Tarek (GKCF59), which is the largest structure identified by Paillou et al. (2006).

Data from (Weihaupt, 1976); indicated young age conservatively interpreted by D. Rajmon as Neogen and calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004). Proposed by (Schmidt, 1962) based on negative gravity anomaly. Source crater for Australite tektites was also proposed in the region by (Barnes, 1961). Proposed by (Weihaupt, 1976) based on observed glacial morphology, thickenned ice, seismic and gravity data. Those data reveal a broad depression min 848 m deep and 243 km across, with 158.3-mGal free air gravity anomally, isostatically not ajusted and thus young. Weihaupt (1976) thought morphology corresponded well to impact craters and 4800-5800 km distance from Australite strewn fields was consistent with postulated distance of the tektites to the source crater. Glacial erosion and endogenic tectonic origin considered and rejected (Weihaupt, 1976). (Bentley, 1979) pointed out that the impact proposal was based on only one travers with some seismic and gravity data ambiguous. (Bentley, 1979) used nine airborn sounding traverses in the region to conclude that there is no sign of the proposed crater in the region; instead, there is a wide valley with a regional relief over 1500 m. Listed by (Moilanen, 2004) as Wilkens Land structure with lat 71.00/lon 140.00 and diameter 240 km without any referrence.

This structure is roughly collocated but different from Wilkes Land 2.

One of the structures identified by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) on X-SAR images. No particular reasons other than appearance on radar and visible light images provided to support an impact origin. Less than 1.1 Ma age estimated by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) based on geological and geographical considerations without further specification. Location of the crater verified by D.Rajmon and B. Shaulis through personal communication with R. Gorelli and coordinates obtained from Google Earth. Diameter measured on Google Earth. This location is actually an open pit mine in Ajo, Arizona, USA. Location mentioned in the paper was appoximately 5 km to the NE of the actual location. Paper location is at 112.91W, 32.38N while Google Earth Location is 112.865W, 32.356N.

Proposed by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) based on appearance on X-SAR and visible satellite images. Considered of certain impact origin, published diameter 3.77 km, age 3.7±0.3 Ma asigned based on an assumption that the structure formed at the same time with nearby Rotter Kamm impact structure.  Observations by D. Rajmon: A dark oval feature 3.5 by 4.5 km in diameter on X-SAR (radar) data mantling a linear ridge. Satellite image and DEM data (Google Earth) reveal a linear ridge up to 60 m tall, surrounded by a mantle with a surface sloping down radially away from the ridge, dropping additional 80-100 m of elevation from the base of the cliff. The extend of this morphological mantle coincides with the dark mantle on the X-SAR image. This mantling feature is best interpreted as a colluvium (an appron of material eroded from the ridge). The rock forming the ridge appears the same as the rock forming a cliff front parallel to the ridge and ~5 km to the NE. The cliffs display morphology and a colluvium mantle of the same scale and appearance on both the satellite radar images as the proposed impact structure. These observations clearly rule out impact origin of this feature. Location of the structure verified by D.Rajmon through personal communication with R. Gorelli and coordinates obtained from Google Earth (D.Rajmon). Single age is not applicable as the structure is a result of an ongoing erosion, calibrated with (Gradstein et al., 2004).

One of the structures identified by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) on X-SAR images. No particular reasons other than appearance on radar and visible light images provided to support an impact origin. Age 3.7±0.3 Ma asigned by (Gorelli, 1998a, b) based on an assumption that the structure formed at the same time with nearby Rotter Kamm impact structure. Location of the crater verified by D.Rajmon through personal communication with R. Gorelli and coordinates obtained from Google Earth (D.Rajmon). (Gorelli, 1998a, b) listed 0.57 km diameter. Observations by D. Rajmon: The feature is a dark ring on a radar image near the limit of resolution. On satellite image, this feature appears to be a colluvium mantle around a knob of a rock more resistant to erosion. Similar outcrops  and colluvium mantles are common in the surrounding region and there is nothing to suggest impact origin of this feature. Compare X-SAR 14A structure. Age is not applicable as the structure is a result of an ongoing erosion.
